Eagles2020DraftPicks}}\n{{Philadelphia Eagles roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hurts, Jalen}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Harris County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma Sooners football players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n", "name_user": "Connorwahl", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jalen_Hurts"}
{"title_page": "Carlos Kleiber", "text_new": "[[File:Carlos Kleiber.png|thumb|Carlos Kleiber]]\n'''Carlos Kleiber''' (3 July 1930 \u2013 13 July 2004) was an Austrian  [[conducting|conductor]] who is widely regarded as being among the greatest conductors of all time.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|title=Carlos Kleiber voted greatest conductor of all time|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/bbcworldwide/worldwidestories/pressreleases/2011/03_march/carlos_kleiber.shtml|accessdate=8 March 2015|agency=BBC Music|publisher=BBC Worldwide Press Releases|date=17 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nKleiber was born as '''Karl Ludwig Bonifacius Kleiber''' in [[Berlin]] in 1930, the son of the eminent Austrian conductor [[Erich Kleiber]] and American Ruth Goodrich, from Waterloo, Iowa.<ref name=Barber>{{cite book|last1=Barber|first1=Charles|title=Corresponding with Carlos: A Biography of Carlos Kleiber|date=2011|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8143-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MoWnChH_SyUC&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Harvey Sachs|authorlink=Harvey Sachs|title=The Conductor Who Could Not Tolerate Error|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/25/arts/music-the-conductor-who-could-not-tolerate-error.html?pagewanted=all|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2004-07-25|access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref> In 1935, the Kleiber family emigrated to [[Buenos Aires]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rockwell|first=John|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/20/arts/carlos-kleiber-is-dead-at-74-music-s-perfectionist-recluse.html|title=Carlos Kleiber Is Dead at 74; Music's Perfectionist Recluse|date=20 July 2004|work=New York Times|access-date=29 April 2020|url-status=live|page=B-9}}</ref> and Karl was renamed Carlos. As a youth, he had an English governess and grew up in English boarding schools. He also composed, sang, and played [[piano]] and [[timpani]]. While his father noticed his son's musical talents, he nevertheless dissuaded Carlos from pursuing a musical career: \"What a pity the boy is musically talented\", wrote Erich to a friend.<ref name=WPobit />\n\nCarlos first studied [[chemistry]] at [[ETH Zurich]], but soon decided to dedicate himself to music. He was [[r\u00e9p\u00e9titeur]] at the [[Staatstheater am G\u00e4rtnerplatz|G\u00e4rtnerplatz Theatre]] in [[Munich]] in 1952, and made his conducting debut with the [[operetta]] ''[[Gasparone]]'' at [[Potsdam]] theatre in 1954. From 1958 to 1964 he was ''Kapellmeister'' at the [[Deutsche Oper am Rhein]] in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] and [[Duisburg]], and then at the Opera in Zurich from 1964 to 1966. Between 1966 and 1973 he was first ''Kapellmeister'' in [[Stuttgart]], his last permanent post. During the following years, he often conducted at the [[Bavarian State Opera]] in Munich.\n\n== Mature career ==\nDuring his freelance career, Kleiber restricted his conducting appearances to a select number of occasions. He made his British debut in 1966 with a performance at the [[Edinburgh Festival]] of [[Alban Berg]]'s [[opera]] ''[[Wozzeck]]'', a work whose premiere his father had conducted in 1925.  Kleiber's repertoire at the [[Royal Opera House]] included ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'', ''[[Elektra (opera)|Elektra]]'', ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' and ''[[Otello]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Performance Database Search Results\n|publisher=Royal Opera House Collections Online|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/SearchResults.aspx?person=Carlos%20Kleiber&searchtype=workprodperf|accessdate=2014-08-04}}</ref>  He made his [[Bayreuth Festspielhaus|Bayreuth]] debut in 1974 conducting [[Richard Wagner]]'s ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]''.\n\nHis American debut came in 1978 with the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]],<ref>{{cite news|author=John Rockwell|authorlink=John Rockwell|title=Carlos Kleiber Is Dead at 74; Music's Perfectionist Recluse|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/20/arts/carlos-kleiber-is-dead-at-74-music-s-perfectionist-recluse.html?pagewanted=all|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2004-07-20|access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref> where he again conducted in 1983, his only US orchestra appearances.<ref>{{cite news | author=Michael Walsh | title=Unvarnished Symphonies | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,952033,00.html | work=Time | date=1983-07-13 | accessdate=2007-10-14}}</ref><ref name=\"Kenyon\">{{cite news|author=Nicholas Kenyon|authorlink=Nicholas Kenyon|title=Carlos Kleiber: Genius Wrapped in an Enigma|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/10/15/arts/music-carlos-kleiber-genius-wrapped-in-an-enigma.html?pagewanted=all|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1989-10-15|access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref> His New York [[Metropolitan Opera]] debut was in 1988, conducting [[Giacomo Puccini]]'s ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' with [[Luciano Pavarotti]] and [[Mirella Freni]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Donal Henahan|authorlink=Donal Henahan|title=Pavarotti and Freni in ''La Boheme''|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/24/arts/the-opera-pavarotti-and-freni-in-la-boheme.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1988-01-24| access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref> In 1989, following [[Herbert von Karajan]]'s resignation from the [[Berlin Philharmonic]], Kleiber was offered, but declined, the opportunity to succeed him as music director.<ref>Jacobs, Arthur (1990) \"Kleiber, Carlos\" ''The Penguin Dictionary of Musical Performers'' Viking, London</ref> Kleiber returned to the Met in 1989 to conduct ''[[La traviata]]'', and in 1990 for ''[[Otello]]''<ref>{{cite news|author=Donal Henahan|authorlink=Donal Henahan|title=Carlos Kleiber Leads Pl\u00e1cido Domingo in Verdi's ''Otello''|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/07/arts/review-opera-carlos-kleiber-leads-placido-domingo-in-verdi-s-otello.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1990-03-07|access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref> and ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donal Henahan|authorlink=Donal Henahan|title=Sweeping ''Rosenkavalier'' at the Met|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/09/27/arts/reviews-opera-sweeping-rosenkavalier-at-the-met.html?pagewanted=all|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1990-09-27|access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Carlos Kleiber.jpg|thumb|left|Kleiber, conducting at a rehearsal]]\nKleiber kept out of the public eye, and apparently gave an interview only once in his lifetime,<ref>Youtube [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3qydEss4m20 Rare Carlos Kleiber Interview in 1960]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.carlos-kleiber.com/res/179/english-translation-of-radio-interview-of-CK-in-german-from-7-december-1960|title=carlos-kleiber.com|website=www.carlos-kleiber.com}}</ref><ref>[http://www.carlos-kleiber.de/10-startseite/5-das-interview.html Fr\u00fche Ausnahme von der Regel \u2013 Das bislang einzige \u00fcberlieferte Interview von Carlos Kleiber]</ref> contrary to reports that he never gave one at all.<ref name=\"Kenyon\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Tolansky|first=John|title=Carlos Kleiber \u2013 Obituary|date=October 2004|url=http://www.gramophone.co.uk/editorial/carlos-kleiber-obituary-gramophone-october-2004-by-john-tolansky|work=[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/1990/jan/01/classicalmusicandopera.artsfeatures|title=Placido Domingo pays tribute to Carlos Kleiber|first=Martin|last=Kettle|authorlink=Martin Kettle|date=January 1, 1990|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> After he resigned from the Bavarian State Opera, his appearances became less frequent and he made only a few recordings.\n\nMost of these studio recordings are highly regarded; they include [[Ludwig van Beethoven]]'s [[Symphony No. 5 (Beethoven)|fifth]] and [[Symphony No. 7 (Beethoven)|seventh]] [[symphony|symphonies]] with the [[Vienna Philharmonic]],  [[Johannes Brahms]]' [[Symphony No. 4 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 4]] and [[Franz Schubert]]'s [[Symphony No. 3 (Schubert)|third]] and [[Symphony No. 8 (Schubert)|eighth]] (\"Unfinished\") symphonies, also with the Vienna Philharmonic, recordings of [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k|Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]]'s [[Piano Concerto (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Concerto for piano and orchestra]] with [[Sviatoslav Richter]], [[Carl Maria von Weber]]'s ''[[Der Freisch\u00fctz]]'', [[Johann Strauss II|Johann Strauss]]' ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'' and [[Giuseppe Verdi]]'s ''[[La traviata]]''.  His last studio recording was [[Richard Wagner]]'s ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' with the [[Staatskapelle Dresden]]. Recording sessions began in 1980 but Kleiber left before they were completed. However, as a musically complete performance had been set down, [[Deutsche Grammophon]] went ahead and released it, much to Kleiber's anger.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nKleiber's small studio discography has been increased by a number of releases of live recordings, often sourced from broadcast relays. These have included his two [[Vienna New Year's Concert]]s, and performances of Beethoven's Fourth, Sixth and Seventh Symphonies with the Bavarian State Orchestra. The Sixth is especially notable as being the only occasion on which Kleiber conducted the work; in this instance the source came not from a radio broadcast but a C-90 [[compact cassette]] recorded for his son.<ref>https://www.gramophone.co.uk/review/beethoven-symphony-no-6-0</ref>\n\n==Later years==\nKleiber retired from concert life in the early 1990s, occasionally reappearing for private or [[benefit concert]]s. For one such event in Ingolstadt, part of his payment consisted of a new [[Audi]] made to his specifications. His performances were painstakingly rehearsed, but often seemed spontaneous and inspired. In the opinion of many of his colleagues and audiences, he was an eccentric genius whom some placed among the greatest conductors of all time despite the paucity of his appearances.<ref name=WPobit>{{Cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A63106-2004Jul19.html?noredirect=on|title=Gifted, Eccentric Conductor Carlos Kleiber Dies at 74|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref><ref>\"Kleiber, Carlos\" ''Current Biography Yearbook'', 1991 edition, H. W. Wilson, New York, p. 338</ref><ref>Bernheimer, Martin (October 2004) \"Obituaries: Carlos Kleiber\" ''[[Opera News]]'' 69(4): p. 85;</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924075305/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4155/is_20040720/ai_n12555577 \"Carlos Kleiber, 74, widely admired conductor\"] by Panos Kakaviatos, ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', 20 July 2004</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2004/jul/21/guardianobituaries.artsobituaries|title=Obituary: Carlos Kleiber|first=Alan|last=Blyth|authorlink=Alan Blyth|date=July 21, 2004|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nHe was buried in the Slovenian village of [[Konj\u0161ica]] near [[Litija]] in 2004 together with his wife [[Stanislava Brezovar]], a [[ballet]] dancer, who had died seven months earlier.<ref>\"Obituary section: Kleiber, Carlos\" ''Current Biography Yearbook'', 2004 edition (New York: Wilson, 650).</ref> They had two children, a son Marko and a daughter Lillian.\n\n== Preserved performances ==\nKleiber's unique conducting style is preserved on video in a number of performances: Beethoven's [[Symphony No. 4 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 4]] and [[Symphony No. 7 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 7]] from the [[Concertgebouw]] in Amsterdam,<ref>{{cite news|author=Bernard Holland|authorlink=Bernard Holland|title=Conducting for Cultists: Beethoven from Kleiber|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/19/arts/conducting-for-cultists-beethoven-from-kleiber.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1987-06-19|access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref> Johann Strauss' ''Die Fledermaus'' from Munich, [[Richard Strauss]]' ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'' from both Munich and Vienna, [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]]'s [[Symphony No. 36 (Mozart)|36th]] symphony and Brahms' [[Symphony No. 2 (Brahms)|second]] symphony from the [[Musikverein]] in Vienna; Beethoven's [[Coriolan Overture]], Mozart's [[Symphony No. 33 (Mozart)|33rd]] and Brahms' fourth symphonies from [[Bavarian State Orchestra|Munich]] and Bizet's Carmen again from Vienna. He led the [[Vienna New Year's Concert|New Year's Concert]] of the Vienna Philharmonic in 1989 and 1992, and these are both preserved on video.\n\n==Legacy==\n\n===Documentary tributes===\n\nIn 2008 [[Rai Radio 3]] (Italian National Radio channel 3), inside its evening program ''Radio3 Suite'', broadcast a 10-episode program dedicated to Kleiber's legacy: ''Il Sorriso della Musica: un Ritratto di Carlos Kleiber'' (\"The Smile Of Music: A Portrait Of Carlos Kleiber\"), organized and hosted by Andrea Ottonello, with participation by [[Claudio Abbado]], [[Mirella Freni]], [[Maurizio Pollini]], and above all Carlos Kleiber's sister, Veronica. In his interview, Abbado termed Kleiber \"one of the greatest, if not the greatest, conductors of the 20th century\" (\"Carlos \u00e8 stato uno dei pi\u00f9 grandi, se non il pi\u00f9 grande, direttore del Novecento.\")<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radio.rai.it/radio3/radio3_suite/view.cfm?Q_EV_ID=240713&Q_PROG_ID=68 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029210845/http://www.radio.rai.it/radio3/radio3_suite/view.cfm?Q_EV_ID=240713&Q_PROG_ID=68 |archivedate=2013-10-29 }}</ref>\n\nOn 26 September 2009, BBC Radio 3 transmitted a documentary, ''Who Was Carlos Kleiber?''. Produced by Paul Frankl and presented by Ivan Hewett with research by Ruth Thomson, this feature was based on interviews with four who knew Kleiber well: tenor and conductor [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], music administrator and intendant Sir Peter Jonas, music journalist and critic Christine Lemke-Matvey and conductor\u2013pianist Charles Barber.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.carlos-kleiber.com/resources|title=carlos-kleiber.com|website=www.carlos-kleiber.com}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|fontsize=89%|quote=His gifts\u2014musical and dramatic insights, analytical abilities, technique, methods of explaining himself\u2014make him the greatest conductor of our day. When I work with him, I feel that he knows why the composer wrote every note, treated every phrase, conceived of every bit of orchestral color in a particular way...If he were to become the permanent conductor of a major orchestra, he could turn it into the greatest ensemble in history.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Domingo|first1=Pl\u00e1cido|title=My First Forty Years|date=1983|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=0-394-52329-6|pages=142\u20133}}</ref>|source= \u2014[[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] about his friend and colleague Carlos Kleiber, 1983}}\n\nBeginning in July 2014, upon the tenth anniversary of his death, a syndicate of public broadcasters in Canada, Great Britain and the United States aired a two-hour documentary, ''Carlos Kleiber: A Conductor Unlike Any Other'', about Kleiber as remembered by his colleagues. Producer Jon Tolansky, who himself played for Kleiber at the Royal Opera House Covent Garden, interviewed singers [[Ileana Cotruba\u0219]], [[Thomas Hampson]], Dame [[Felicity Lott]], the late Dame [[Margaret Price]] and [[Jonathan Summers]], members of the Chicago Symphony, Royal Opera House, London Symphony and Vienna Philharmonic orchestras, conductor and Kleiber friend Charles Barber, administrators Sir Peter Jonas and Sir John Tooley, and recording executive Costa Pilavachi. This audio essay incorporated numerous excerpts from Kleiber's most important recordings, including Beethoven's fifth and seventh symphonies, Verdi's ''La traviata'', Richard Strauss' ''Der Rosenkavalier'', and Weber's ''Der Freisch\u00fctz''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://correspondingwithcarlos.com/two-hour-radio-special-on-carlos-kleiber-now-available-online-and-free/|title=NOW: Carlos in Korean / Carlos on DGG Documentary|date=August 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Honors and posthumous evaluation===\n\nOn 21 June 2010, Ljubljana celebrated Carlos Kleiber's 80th birthday with a concert by the [[Vienna Philharmonic]] directed by Kleiber's friend [[Riccardo Muti]]. ''[[BBC Music Magazine]]'' announced on 17 March 2011 that Kleiber had been selected as \"the greatest conductor of all time.\" Some 100 current conductors, including [[Sir Colin Davis]], [[Gustavo Dudamel]], [[Valery Gergiev]] and [[Mariss Jansons]], participated in the BBC poll. Kleiber, who conducted just 96 concerts and around 400 operatic performances in his 74 years, was voted ahead of [[Leonard Bernstein]] and [[Claudio Abbado]], who took second and third places respectively.\n\n[[Susanna M\u00e4lkki]], Music director, Ensemble Intercontemporain, and one of the conductors polled, commented: \"Carlos Kleiber brought an incredible energy to music... Yes, he did have about five times as much time to rehearse than conductors do today, but he deserved it because his vision was remarkable, he knew what he wanted, and his attention to detail was truly inspiring.\"\n\nJeremy Pound, Deputy Editor of BBC Music Magazine, added: \"Asking 100 of today's conducting greats to name their idols and inspirations was a fascinating experience. Not least when so many named Carlos Kleiber, who in the course of his whole lifetime conducted fewer concerts than most of them direct in just a couple of years. Kleiber's incredible attention to detail, sheer enthusiasm for music, and astonishingly accomplished level of performance could never be doubted \u2013 perhaps 'less is more' is the real path to true greatness?\"\n\nAccording to Dr. Charles Barber, biographer, friend and pen-pal of Kleiber, another factor contributed to his legendary and unusual career. \"Uniquely, Carlos Kleiber combined the rigors of German analysis, form and discipline with the expressive vitality of Latin dance, pulse and joy. For nearly twenty years at the formative outset, a conductor baptized Karl gradually became Carlos. He never turned his back on that fascinating cultural biochemistry. It would shape everything he did.\"<ref name=Barber />\n\nKleiber was voted into the [[Gramophone Hall of Fame]] in 2012. [[Clemens Hellsberg]] (''[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]'', May 2012) said:\n\n<blockquote>What was it that propelled Carlos Kleiber to near mystical heights? It was the unforgettable experience of surpassing one's own boundaries, yet also the utter helplessness when he stormed off in the last minutes of a final rehearsal. This was not pretension but rather the expression of deepest despair, even though the orchestra had performed at the highest level \u2013 or perhaps for that very reason. Extreme contradictions characterised his personality: one constantly feared catastrophe, yet he was always available to musicians for private conversations. He had a vast repertoire, yet restricted himself to a very few works. His outbursts of rage could be directed at anyone, yet his interaction with children was characterised by a precious and fragile tenderness. In art there are no upward limits. Yet each generation needs at least one artist who exemplifies this. Kleiber reached to the stars for us; even when he broke down in his efforts, he still proved that they exist.</blockquote>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n* Cultural Honour of the City of Munich (1978)\n* [[Pour le M\u00e9rite for Science and Art]] (Germany, 1990)\n* [[Austrian Medal for Science and Art]] (1992){{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n* Golden Baton of [[La Scala]] (Milan, 1995)\n* [[Deutscher Schallplattenpreis|German Record Prize]]\n* [[Bavarian Order of Merit]]\n* [[Bavarian Maximilian Order for Science and Art]]\n* Grand Merit Cross with Star of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n\n== Discography ==\nDates refer to the original recorded performance, not necessarily date of commercial release. An asterisk indicates a recording of a live concert performance.\n* 1960: [[Georg Philipp Telemann]]: Suite in B flat major ([[Tafelmusik]]), Hamburger Rundfunkorchester, Profil*\n* 1960: [[Carl Philipp Emanuel Bach]]: Cello Concerto in B flat major, Hamburger Rundfunkorchester, Profil*\n* 1967: [[Gustav Mahler]]: ''[[Das Lied von der Erde]]'', [[Wiener Symphoniker]], Wiener Konzerthaus*. Soloists: [[Christa Ludwig]], [[Waldemar Kmentt]]\n* 1972: Borodin: [[Symphony No. 2 (Borodin)|Symphony No. 2]], [[Radio Symphony Orchestra]], [[H\u00e4nssler]]*\n* 1973: Weber: ''[[Der Freisch\u00fctz]]'', [[Staatskapelle Dresden]], [[Deutsche Grammophon|DG]]. Soloists: [[Gundula Janowitz]], [[Edith Mathis]], [[Peter Schreier]], [[Theo Adam]], [[Bernd Weikl]], [[Siegfried Vogel]], [[Franz Crass]].\n* 1973: Strauss: ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'' \u2013 complete, Soloists: Claire Watson; Brigitte Fassbaender; Lucia Popp; Orchestra Bayerische Staatsoper,  Orfeo D'or*\n* 1974: Beethoven: [[Symphony No. 5 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 5]], [[Vienna Philharmonic]], Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 1975: Strauss II: ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'', [[Bavarian State Opera]], Deutsche Grammophon. Soloists: [[Hermann Prey]], [[Julia Varady]], [[Lucia Popp]], [[Ren\u00e9 Kollo]], [[Ivan Rebroff]], [[Bernd Weikl]].\n* 1975-1976: Ludwig van Beethoven: [[Symphony No. 7 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 7]], Vienna Philharmonic, Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 1976: Dvo\u0159\u00e1k: [[Piano Concerto (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Concerto for piano and orchestra]], Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, EMI. Piano: [[Sviatoslav Richter]].\n* 1976: Verdi: ''[[Otello]]'', Orchestra and Chorus of Teatro alla Scala, Opera d'Oro*. Soloists: [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Mirella Freni]], [[Piero Cappuccilli]].\n* 1976-1977: Verdi: ''[[La traviata]]'', Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, Deutsche Grammophon. Soloists: [[Ileana Cotruba\u015f]], [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Sherrill Milnes]].\n* 1977: Richard Strauss: ''[[Elektra (opera)|Elektra]]'', live recording with the Orchestra of the [[Royal Opera House]], Connoisseur Label*. Soloists: [[Birgit Nilsson]], {{ill|Marta Szirmay|hu|Szirmay M\u00e1rta}} and [[Gwyneth Jones (soprano)|Gwyneth Jones]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2000/june00/elektra.htm|title=Richard Strauss: Elektra Kleiber: Classical CD Reviews-June 2000 Music on the Web(UK)|website=www.musicweb-international.com}}</ref>\n* 1978: Schubert: [[Symphony No. 3 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 3]], Vienna Philharmonic, Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 1978: Franz Schubert: [[Symphony No. 8 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 8 \"Unfinished\"]], Vienna Philharmonic, Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 1979: Puccini: ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'', Orchestra of [[Teatro alla Scala]], Golden Melodram/Myto*. Soloists: Ileana Cotruba\u0219, [[Luciano Pavarotti]]\n* 1979: Giacomo Puccini: ''La boh\u00e8me'', Orchestra of the Royal Opera House, Golden Melodram*. Soloists: Ileana Cotruba\u0219, [[Sona Ghazarian]]\n* 1980: Brahms: [[Symphony No. 4 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 4]], Vienna Philharmonic, Deutsche Grammophon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2000/mar/17/classicalmusicandopera|title=Brahms: Symphony No.4|first=Andrew|last=Clements|date=March 17, 2000|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n* 1980-1982: Wagner: ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'', Staatskapelle Dresden, Deutsche Grammophon. Soloists: [[Ren\u00e9 Kollo]], [[Margaret Price]], [[Brigitte Fassbaender]], [[Dietrich Fischer-Dieskau]], [[Kurt Moll]].\n* 1982: Ludwig van Beethoven: [[Symphony No. 4 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 4]], Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, Orfeo*.\n* 1982: Ludwig van Beethoven: Symphony No. 7, Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, Orfeo*.\n* 1983: Ludwig van Beethoven: [[Symphony No. 6 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 6]], Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, Orfeo*.\n* 1989: [[Vienna New Year's Concert]], Vienna Philharmonic, Sony Classical*.\n* 1992: Vienna New Year's Concert, Vienna Philharmonic, Sony Classical*.\n\n===Collections===\n* 2010: Complete Recordings on Deutsche Grammophon \u2013 12 CDs / Complete Opera and Concert DVDs on Deutsche Grammophon \u2013 10 DVDs\n* 2014: Complete orchestral Recordings on Deutsche Grammophon \u2013 3 CDs & 1 Blu-ray with Bonus Audio Documentary.\n\n== DVD releases ==\n* 1970: \"The Great conductors\", TDK and Arthaus. Overtures: ''[[Der Freisch\u00fctz]]'' & ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'' [[Stuttgart Radio Symphony Orchestra]] (rehearsals)\n* 1976: Verdi: ''[[Otello]]'', La Scala Milan Orchestra & Chorus, [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Mirella Freni]], [[Piero Cappuccilli]], Opera Legacies\n* 1978: Bizet: ''[[Carmen]]'', Vienna State Opera, TDK and Bel Canto. Soloists: [[Elena Obraztsova]], [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Yuri Mazurok]], [[Isobel Buchanan]].\n* 1979: Puccini: ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'', La Scala Milan Orchestra & Chorus, [[Ileana Cotruba\u0219]], [[Luciano Pavarotti]], Bel Canto Society\n* 1979: Strauss: ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'', Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, Deutsche Grammophon. Soloists: [[Gwyneth Jones (soprano)|Gwyneth Jones]], [[Brigitte Fassbaender]], [[Lucia Popp]], [[Francisco Araiza]].\n* 1983: Ludwig van Beethoven: Symphony No. 4, Symphony No. 7, [[Concertgebouw Orchestra|Concertgebouw Orchestra Amsterdam]], Philips.\n* 1986: Johann Strauss II: ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'', Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, Deutsche Grammophon. Soloists: [[Pamela Coburn]], [[Brigitte Fassbaender]], [[Janet Perry]], [[Eberhard Waechter (baritone)|Eberhard W\u00e4chter]].\n* 1989: Vienna New Year's Concert, Vienna Philharmonic, Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 1991: Mozart: [[Symphony No. 36 (Mozart)|Symphony No. 36]], Brahms: [[Symphony No. 2 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 2]], Vienna Philharmonic, Philips.\n* 1992: Vienna New Year's Concert, Vienna Philharmonic, Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 1994: Richard Strauss: ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'', [[Vienna State Opera|Orchestra of the Vienna State Opera]], Deutsche Grammophon. Soloists: [[Felicity Lott]], [[Kurt Moll]], [[Anne Sofie von Otter]], [[Gottfried Hornik]], [[Barbara Bonney]], [[Heinz Zednik]].\n* 1996: Ludwig van Beethoven: ''Coriolan'' Overture, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart: [[Symphony No. 33 (Mozart)|Symphony No. 33]], Johannes Brahms: Symphony No. 4, Bavarian State Orchestra, Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 2010: Complete Opera and Concert DVDs on Deutsche Grammophon \u2013 10 DVDs.\n* 2010: ''Carlos Kleiber \u2013 I Am Lost to the World'', documentary, Director: Georg W\u00fcbbolt, Production: BFMI / ZDF / 3sat, Distributor: C Major Entertainment.\n* 2011: ''Carlos Kleiber \u2013 Traces to Nowhere'', documentary, Director: Eric Schulz, Production: Servus TV, Distributor: EuroArts Music International.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Balestrazzi, Mauro: ''Carlos Kleiber \u2013 Angelo o demone?'', 2006, {{ISBN|88-8302-325-0}} (in Italian).\n* Drexel, Christina: ''Carlos Kleiber \u2013 ... einfach was dasteht!'', 2010, Verlag Dohr K\u00f6ln, {{ISBN|978-3-936655-89-6}} (in German).\n* Fischer, Jens Malte: ''Carlos Kleiber \u2013 Der skrupul\u00f6se Exzentriker'', 2006, {{ISBN|3-8353-0138-1}} (in German).\n* Vichev, Tomislav: ''Kleiber's Era'', 2003 (in Bulgarian).\n* Werner, Alexander: ''Carlos Kleiber \u2013 Eine Biografie'', 2007, 2nd, revised Edition, 2009, {{ISBN|978-3-7957-0598-5}}, 3rd Edition, paperback, July 2010 (in German)\n* Zignani, Alessandro: ''Il tramonto dell'Occidente'', 2010, {{ISBN|978-88-87203-95-0}}, Zecchini Editore (in Italian).\n\n== Filmography ==\n* [http://www.mediafire.com/?wn4lnykyqkk September 2009 BBC Radio program: ''Who Was Carlos Kleiber?'' ]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100823060702/http://www.servustv.com/cs/Satellite/Article/Spuren-ins-Nichts-011259286557317 Documentary ''Spuren ins Nichts \u2013 Der Dirigent Carlos Kleiber'', Deutschland, Slowenien, \u00d6sterreich, 2010, 52 Min., director Eric Schulz, Centauri, EuroArts Music International.Servus TV, 2010 ]\n* [http://www.cmajor-entertainment.com/catalogue/show/id/2341 TV documentary ''I am lost to the World'', directed by Georg W\u00fcbbolt, BFMI, ZDF, 3sat, C major Ent. March 2011]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.carlos-kleiber.de Biographer Alexander Werner's site]\n* [http://www.carlos-kleiber.com A memorial site with testimonials and video clips]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/carloskleiber2.0 Carlos Kleiber 2.0] (the Carlos Kleiber's community)\n* [http://www.thrsw.com Erich and Carlos Kleiber site]\n* [http://correspondingwithcarlos.com/ A site about the eponymous book]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070911161406/http://www.kleiber.hit.bg/en/ Kleiber's era]\n* {{Discogs artist}}\n\n{{Gramophone Hall of Fame}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Classical music}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kleiber, Carlos}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Austrian people]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Austrian conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:ETH Zurich alumni]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriates in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Austrian emigrants to Argentina]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriates in Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Deutsche Grammophon artists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bavarian Maximilian Order for Science and Art]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Austrian Decoration for Science and Art]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Pour le M\u00e9rite (civil class)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bavarian Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Carlos Kleiber.png|thumb|Carlos Kleiber]]\n'''Carlos Kleiber''' (3 July 1930 \u2013 13 July 2004) was an Austrian  [[conducting|conductor]] who is widely regarded as being among the greatest conductors of all time.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|title=Carlos Kleiber voted greatest conductor of all time|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/bbcworldwide/worldwidestories/pressreleases/2011/03_march/carlos_kleiber.shtml|accessdate=8 March 2015|agency=BBC Music|publisher=BBC Worldwide Press Releases|date=17 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nKleiber was born as '''Karl Ludwig Bonifacius Kleiber''' in [[Berlin]] in 1930, the son of the eminent Austrian conductor [[Erich Kleiber]] and American Ruth Goodrich, from Waterloo, Iowa.<ref name=Barber>{{cite book|last1=Barber|first1=Charles|title=Corresponding with Carlos: A Biography of Carlos Kleiber|date=2011|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8143-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MoWnChH_SyUC&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Harvey Sachs|authorlink=Harvey Sachs|title=The Conductor Who Could Not Tolerate Error|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/25/arts/music-the-conductor-who-could-not-tolerate-error.html?pagewanted=all|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2004-07-25|access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref> In 1935,{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} the Kleiber family emigrated to [[Buenos Aires]] and Karl was renamed Carlos. As a youth, he had an English governess and grew up in English boarding schools. He also composed, sang, and played [[piano]] and [[timpani]]. While his father noticed his son's musical talents, he nevertheless dissuaded Carlos from pursuing a musical career: \"What a pity the boy is musically talented\", wrote Erich to a friend.<ref name=WPobit />\n\nCarlos first studied [[chemistry]] at [[ETH Zurich]], but soon decided to dedicate himself to music. He was [[r\u00e9p\u00e9titeur]] at the [[Staatstheater am G\u00e4rtnerplatz|G\u00e4rtnerplatz Theatre]] in [[Munich]] in 1952, and made his conducting debut with the [[operetta]] ''[[Gasparone]]'' at [[Potsdam]] theatre in 1954. From 1958 to 1964 he was ''Kapellmeister'' at the [[Deutsche Oper am Rhein]] in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] and [[Duisburg]], and then at the Opera in Zurich from 1964 to 1966. Between 1966 and 1973 he was first ''Kapellmeister'' in [[Stuttgart]], his last permanent post. During the following years, he often conducted at the [[Bavarian State Opera]] in Munich.\n\n== Mature career ==\nDuring his freelance career, Kleiber restricted his conducting appearances to a select number of occasions. He made his British debut in 1966 with a performance at the [[Edinburgh Festival]] of [[Alban Berg]]'s [[opera]] ''[[Wozzeck]]'', a work whose premiere his father had conducted in 1925.  Kleiber's repertoire at the [[Royal Opera House]] included ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'', ''[[Elektra (opera)|Elektra]]'', ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' and ''[[Otello]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Performance Database Search Results\n|publisher=Royal Opera House Collections Online|url=http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/SearchResults.aspx?person=Carlos%20Kleiber&searchtype=workprodperf|accessdate=2014-08-04}}</ref>  He made his [[Bayreuth Festspielhaus|Bayreuth]] debut in 1974 conducting [[Richard Wagner]]'s ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]''.\n\nHis American debut came in 1978 with the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]],<ref>{{cite news|author=John Rockwell|authorlink=John Rockwell|title=Carlos Kleiber Is Dead at 74; Music's Perfectionist Recluse|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/20/arts/carlos-kleiber-is-dead-at-74-music-s-perfectionist-recluse.html?pagewanted=all|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2004-07-20|access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref> where he again conducted in 1983, his only US orchestra appearances.<ref>{{cite news | author=Michael Walsh | title=Unvarnished Symphonies | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,952033,00.html | work=Time | date=1983-07-13 | accessdate=2007-10-14}}</ref><ref name=\"Kenyon\">{{cite news|author=Nicholas Kenyon|authorlink=Nicholas Kenyon|title=Carlos Kleiber: Genius Wrapped in an Enigma|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/10/15/arts/music-carlos-kleiber-genius-wrapped-in-an-enigma.html?pagewanted=all|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1989-10-15|access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref> His New York [[Metropolitan Opera]] debut was in 1988, conducting [[Giacomo Puccini]]'s ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' with [[Luciano Pavarotti]] and [[Mirella Freni]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Donal Henahan|authorlink=Donal Henahan|title=Pavarotti and Freni in ''La Boheme''|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/24/arts/the-opera-pavarotti-and-freni-in-la-boheme.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1988-01-24| access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref> In 1989, following [[Herbert von Karajan]]'s resignation from the [[Berlin Philharmonic]], Kleiber was offered, but declined, the opportunity to succeed him as music director.<ref>Jacobs, Arthur (1990) \"Kleiber, Carlos\" ''The Penguin Dictionary of Musical Performers'' Viking, London</ref> Kleiber returned to the Met in 1989 to conduct ''[[La traviata]]'', and in 1990 for ''[[Otello]]''<ref>{{cite news|author=Donal Henahan|authorlink=Donal Henahan|title=Carlos Kleiber Leads Pl\u00e1cido Domingo in Verdi's ''Otello''|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/07/arts/review-opera-carlos-kleiber-leads-placido-domingo-in-verdi-s-otello.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1990-03-07|access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref> and ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donal Henahan|authorlink=Donal Henahan|title=Sweeping ''Rosenkavalier'' at the Met|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/09/27/arts/reviews-opera-sweeping-rosenkavalier-at-the-met.html?pagewanted=all|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1990-09-27|access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Carlos Kleiber.jpg|thumb|left|Kleiber, conducting at a rehearsal]]\nKleiber kept out of the public eye, and apparently gave an interview only once in his lifetime,<ref>Youtube [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3qydEss4m20 Rare Carlos Kleiber Interview in 1960]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.carlos-kleiber.com/res/179/english-translation-of-radio-interview-of-CK-in-german-from-7-december-1960|title=carlos-kleiber.com|website=www.carlos-kleiber.com}}</ref><ref>[http://www.carlos-kleiber.de/10-startseite/5-das-interview.html Fr\u00fche Ausnahme von der Regel \u2013 Das bislang einzige \u00fcberlieferte Interview von Carlos Kleiber]</ref> contrary to reports that he never gave one at all.<ref name=\"Kenyon\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Tolansky|first=John|title=Carlos Kleiber \u2013 Obituary|date=October 2004|url=http://www.gramophone.co.uk/editorial/carlos-kleiber-obituary-gramophone-october-2004-by-john-tolansky|work=[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/1990/jan/01/classicalmusicandopera.artsfeatures|title=Placido Domingo pays tribute to Carlos Kleiber|first=Martin|last=Kettle|authorlink=Martin Kettle|date=January 1, 1990|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> After he resigned from the Bavarian State Opera, his appearances became less frequent and he made only a few recordings.\n\nMost of these studio recordings are highly regarded; they include [[Ludwig van Beethoven]]'s [[Symphony No. 5 (Beethoven)|fifth]] and [[Symphony No. 7 (Beethoven)|seventh]] [[symphony|symphonies]] with the [[Vienna Philharmonic]],  [[Johannes Brahms]]' [[Symphony No. 4 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 4]] and [[Franz Schubert]]'s [[Symphony No. 3 (Schubert)|third]] and [[Symphony No. 8 (Schubert)|eighth]] (\"Unfinished\") symphonies, also with the Vienna Philharmonic, recordings of [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k|Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]]'s [[Piano Concerto (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Concerto for piano and orchestra]] with [[Sviatoslav Richter]], [[Carl Maria von Weber]]'s ''[[Der Freisch\u00fctz]]'', [[Johann Strauss II|Johann Strauss]]' ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'' and [[Giuseppe Verdi]]'s ''[[La traviata]]''.  His last studio recording was [[Richard Wagner]]'s ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' with the [[Staatskapelle Dresden]]. Recording sessions began in 1980 but Kleiber left before they were completed. However, as a musically complete performance had been set down, [[Deutsche Grammophon]] went ahead and released it, much to Kleiber's anger.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nKleiber's small studio discography has been increased by a number of releases of live recordings, often sourced from broadcast relays. These have included his two [[Vienna New Year's Concert]]s, and performances of Beethoven's Fourth, Sixth and Seventh Symphonies with the Bavarian State Orchestra. The Sixth is especially notable as being the only occasion on which Kleiber conducted the work; in this instance the source came not from a radio broadcast but a C-90 [[compact cassette]] recorded for his son.<ref>https://www.gramophone.co.uk/review/beethoven-symphony-no-6-0</ref>\n\n==Later years==\nKleiber retired from concert life in the early 1990s, occasionally reappearing for private or [[benefit concert]]s. For one such event in Ingolstadt, part of his payment consisted of a new [[Audi]] made to his specifications. His performances were painstakingly rehearsed, but often seemed spontaneous and inspired. In the opinion of many of his colleagues and audiences, he was an eccentric genius whom some placed among the greatest conductors of all time despite the paucity of his appearances.<ref name=WPobit>{{Cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A63106-2004Jul19.html?noredirect=on|title=Gifted, Eccentric Conductor Carlos Kleiber Dies at 74|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref><ref>\"Kleiber, Carlos\" ''Current Biography Yearbook'', 1991 edition, H. W. Wilson, New York, p. 338</ref><ref>Bernheimer, Martin (October 2004) \"Obituaries: Carlos Kleiber\" ''[[Opera News]]'' 69(4): p. 85;</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924075305/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4155/is_20040720/ai_n12555577 \"Carlos Kleiber, 74, widely admired conductor\"] by Panos Kakaviatos, ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', 20 July 2004</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2004/jul/21/guardianobituaries.artsobituaries|title=Obituary: Carlos Kleiber|first=Alan|last=Blyth|authorlink=Alan Blyth|date=July 21, 2004|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nHe was buried in the Slovenian village of [[Konj\u0161ica]] near [[Litija]] in 2004 together with his wife [[Stanislava Brezovar]], a [[ballet]] dancer, who had died seven months earlier.<ref>\"Obituary section: Kleiber, Carlos\" ''Current Biography Yearbook'', 2004 edition (New York: Wilson, 650).</ref> They had two children, a son Marko and a daughter Lillian.\n\n== Preserved performances ==\nKleiber's unique conducting style is preserved on video in a number of performances: Beethoven's [[Symphony No. 4 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 4]] and [[Symphony No. 7 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 7]] from the [[Concertgebouw]] in Amsterdam,<ref>{{cite news|author=Bernard Holland|authorlink=Bernard Holland|title=Conducting for Cultists: Beethoven from Kleiber|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/19/arts/conducting-for-cultists-beethoven-from-kleiber.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1987-06-19|access-date=2007-10-14}}</ref> Johann Strauss' ''Die Fledermaus'' from Munich, [[Richard Strauss]]' ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'' from both Munich and Vienna, [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]]'s [[Symphony No. 36 (Mozart)|36th]] symphony and Brahms' [[Symphony No. 2 (Brahms)|second]] symphony from the [[Musikverein]] in Vienna; Beethoven's [[Coriolan Overture]], Mozart's [[Symphony No. 33 (Mozart)|33rd]] and Brahms' fourth symphonies from [[Bavarian State Orchestra|Munich]] and Bizet's Carmen again from Vienna. He led the [[Vienna New Year's Concert|New Year's Concert]] of the Vienna Philharmonic in 1989 and 1992, and these are both preserved on video.\n\n==Legacy==\n\n===Documentary tributes===\n\nIn 2008 [[Rai Radio 3]] (Italian National Radio channel 3), inside its evening program ''Radio3 Suite'', broadcast a 10-episode program dedicated to Kleiber's legacy: ''Il Sorriso della Musica: un Ritratto di Carlos Kleiber'' (\"The Smile Of Music: A Portrait Of Carlos Kleiber\"), organized and hosted by Andrea Ottonello, with participation by [[Claudio Abbado]], [[Mirella Freni]], [[Maurizio Pollini]], and above all Carlos Kleiber's sister, Veronica. In his interview, Abbado termed Kleiber \"one of the greatest, if not the greatest, conductors of the 20th century\" (\"Carlos \u00e8 stato uno dei pi\u00f9 grandi, se non il pi\u00f9 grande, direttore del Novecento.\")<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radio.rai.it/radio3/radio3_suite/view.cfm?Q_EV_ID=240713&Q_PROG_ID=68 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029210845/http://www.radio.rai.it/radio3/radio3_suite/view.cfm?Q_EV_ID=240713&Q_PROG_ID=68 |archivedate=2013-10-29 }}</ref>\n\nOn 26 September 2009, BBC Radio 3 transmitted a documentary, ''Who Was Carlos Kleiber?''. Produced by Paul Frankl and presented by Ivan Hewett with research by Ruth Thomson, this feature was based on interviews with four who knew Kleiber well: tenor and conductor [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], music administrator and intendant Sir Peter Jonas, music journalist and critic Christine Lemke-Matvey and conductor\u2013pianist Charles Barber.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.carlos-kleiber.com/resources|title=carlos-kleiber.com|website=www.carlos-kleiber.com}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|fontsize=89%|quote=His gifts\u2014musical and dramatic insights, analytical abilities, technique, methods of explaining himself\u2014make him the greatest conductor of our day. When I work with him, I feel that he knows why the composer wrote every note, treated every phrase, conceived of every bit of orchestral color in a particular way...If he were to become the permanent conductor of a major orchestra, he could turn it into the greatest ensemble in history.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Domingo|first1=Pl\u00e1cido|title=My First Forty Years|date=1983|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=0-394-52329-6|pages=142\u20133}}</ref>|source= \u2014[[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] about his friend and colleague Carlos Kleiber, 1983}}\n\nBeginning in July 2014, upon the tenth anniversary of his death, a syndicate of public broadcasters in Canada, Great Britain and the United States aired a two-hour documentary, ''Carlos Kleiber: A Conductor Unlike Any Other'', about Kleiber as remembered by his colleagues. Producer Jon Tolansky, who himself played for Kleiber at the Royal Opera House Covent Garden, interviewed singers [[Ileana Cotruba\u0219]], [[Thomas Hampson]], Dame [[Felicity Lott]], the late Dame [[Margaret Price]] and [[Jonathan Summers]], members of the Chicago Symphony, Royal Opera House, London Symphony and Vienna Philharmonic orchestras, conductor and Kleiber friend Charles Barber, administrators Sir Peter Jonas and Sir John Tooley, and recording executive Costa Pilavachi. This audio essay incorporated numerous excerpts from Kleiber's most important recordings, including Beethoven's fifth and seventh symphonies, Verdi's ''La traviata'', Richard Strauss' ''Der Rosenkavalier'', and Weber's ''Der Freisch\u00fctz''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://correspondingwithcarlos.com/two-hour-radio-special-on-carlos-kleiber-now-available-online-and-free/|title=NOW: Carlos in Korean / Carlos on DGG Documentary|date=August 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Honors and posthumous evaluation===\n\nOn 21 June 2010, Ljubljana celebrated Carlos Kleiber's 80th birthday with a concert by the [[Vienna Philharmonic]] directed by Kleiber's friend [[Riccardo Muti]]. ''[[BBC Music Magazine]]'' announced on 17 March 2011 that Kleiber had been selected as \"the greatest conductor of all time.\" Some 100 current conductors, including [[Sir Colin Davis]], [[Gustavo Dudamel]], [[Valery Gergiev]] and [[Mariss Jansons]], participated in the BBC poll. Kleiber, who conducted just 96 concerts and around 400 operatic performances in his 74 years, was voted ahead of [[Leonard Bernstein]] and [[Claudio Abbado]], who took second and third places respectively.\n\n[[Susanna M\u00e4lkki]], Music director, Ensemble Intercontemporain, and one of the conductors polled, commented: \"Carlos Kleiber brought an incredible energy to music... Yes, he did have about five times as much time to rehearse than conductors do today, but he deserved it because his vision was remarkable, he knew what he wanted, and his attention to detail was truly inspiring.\"\n\nJeremy Pound, Deputy Editor of BBC Music Magazine, added: \"Asking 100 of today's conducting greats to name their idols and inspirations was a fascinating experience. Not least when so many named Carlos Kleiber, who in the course of his whole lifetime conducted fewer concerts than most of them direct in just a couple of years. Kleiber's incredible attention to detail, sheer enthusiasm for music, and astonishingly accomplished level of performance could never be doubted \u2013 perhaps 'less is more' is the real path to true greatness?\"\n\nAccording to Dr. Charles Barber, biographer, friend and pen-pal of Kleiber, another factor contributed to his legendary and unusual career. \"Uniquely, Carlos Kleiber combined the rigors of German analysis, form and discipline with the expressive vitality of Latin dance, pulse and joy. For nearly twenty years at the formative outset, a conductor baptized Karl gradually became Carlos. He never turned his back on that fascinating cultural biochemistry. It would shape everything he did.\"<ref name=Barber />\n\nKleiber was voted into the [[Gramophone Hall of Fame]] in 2012. [[Clemens Hellsberg]] (''[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]'', May 2012) said:\n\n<blockquote>What was it that propelled Carlos Kleiber to near mystical heights? It was the unforgettable experience of surpassing one's own boundaries, yet also the utter helplessness when he stormed off in the last minutes of a final rehearsal. This was not pretension but rather the expression of deepest despair, even though the orchestra had performed at the highest level \u2013 or perhaps for that very reason. Extreme contradictions characterised his personality: one constantly feared catastrophe, yet he was always available to musicians for private conversations. He had a vast repertoire, yet restricted himself to a very few works. His outbursts of rage could be directed at anyone, yet his interaction with children was characterised by a precious and fragile tenderness. In art there are no upward limits. Yet each generation needs at least one artist who exemplifies this. Kleiber reached to the stars for us; even when he broke down in his efforts, he still proved that they exist.</blockquote>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n* Cultural Honour of the City of Munich (1978)\n* [[Pour le M\u00e9rite for Science and Art]] (Germany, 1990)\n* [[Austrian Medal for Science and Art]] (1992){{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n* Golden Baton of [[La Scala]] (Milan, 1995)\n* [[Deutscher Schallplattenpreis|German Record Prize]]\n* [[Bavarian Order of Merit]]\n* [[Bavarian Maximilian Order for Science and Art]]\n* Grand Merit Cross with Star of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n\n== Discography ==\nDates refer to the original recorded performance, not necessarily date of commercial release. An asterisk indicates a recording of a live concert performance.\n* 1960: [[Georg Philipp Telemann]]: Suite in B flat major ([[Tafelmusik]]), Hamburger Rundfunkorchester, Profil*\n* 1960: [[Carl Philipp Emanuel Bach]]: Cello Concerto in B flat major, Hamburger Rundfunkorchester, Profil*\n* 1967: [[Gustav Mahler]]: ''[[Das Lied von der Erde]]'', [[Wiener Symphoniker]], Wiener Konzerthaus*. Soloists: [[Christa Ludwig]], [[Waldemar Kmentt]]\n* 1972: Borodin: [[Symphony No. 2 (Borodin)|Symphony No. 2]], [[Radio Symphony Orchestra]], [[H\u00e4nssler]]*\n* 1973: Weber: ''[[Der Freisch\u00fctz]]'', [[Staatskapelle Dresden]], [[Deutsche Grammophon|DG]]. Soloists: [[Gundula Janowitz]], [[Edith Mathis]], [[Peter Schreier]], [[Theo Adam]], [[Bernd Weikl]], [[Siegfried Vogel]], [[Franz Crass]].\n* 1973: Strauss: ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'' \u2013 complete, Soloists: Claire Watson; Brigitte Fassbaender; Lucia Popp; Orchestra Bayerische Staatsoper,  Orfeo D'or*\n* 1974: Beethoven: [[Symphony No. 5 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 5]], [[Vienna Philharmonic]], Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 1975: Strauss II: ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'', [[Bavarian State Opera]], Deutsche Grammophon. Soloists: [[Hermann Prey]], [[Julia Varady]], [[Lucia Popp]], [[Ren\u00e9 Kollo]], [[Ivan Rebroff]], [[Bernd Weikl]].\n* 1975-1976: Ludwig van Beethoven: [[Symphony No. 7 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 7]], Vienna Philharmonic, Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 1976: Dvo\u0159\u00e1k: [[Piano Concerto (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Concerto for piano and orchestra]], Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, EMI. Piano: [[Sviatoslav Richter]].\n* 1976: Verdi: ''[[Otello]]'', Orchestra and Chorus of Teatro alla Scala, Opera d'Oro*. Soloists: [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Mirella Freni]], [[Piero Cappuccilli]].\n* 1976-1977: Verdi: ''[[La traviata]]'', Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, Deutsche Grammophon. Soloists: [[Ileana Cotruba\u015f]], [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Sherrill Milnes]].\n* 1977: Richard Strauss: ''[[Elektra (opera)|Elektra]]'', live recording with the Orchestra of the [[Royal Opera House]], Connoisseur Label*. Soloists: [[Birgit Nilsson]], {{ill|Marta Szirmay|hu|Szirmay M\u00e1rta}} and [[Gwyneth Jones (soprano)|Gwyneth Jones]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2000/june00/elektra.htm|title=Richard Strauss: Elektra Kleiber: Classical CD Reviews-June 2000 Music on the Web(UK)|website=www.musicweb-international.com}}</ref>\n* 1978: Schubert: [[Symphony No. 3 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 3]], Vienna Philharmonic, Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 1978: Franz Schubert: [[Symphony No. 8 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 8 \"Unfinished\"]], Vienna Philharmonic, Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 1979: Puccini: ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'', Orchestra of [[Teatro alla Scala]], Golden Melodram/Myto*. Soloists: Ileana Cotruba\u0219, [[Luciano Pavarotti]]\n* 1979: Giacomo Puccini: ''La boh\u00e8me'', Orchestra of the Royal Opera House, Golden Melodram*. Soloists: Ileana Cotruba\u0219, [[Sona Ghazarian]]\n* 1980: Brahms: [[Symphony No. 4 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 4]], Vienna Philharmonic, Deutsche Grammophon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2000/mar/17/classicalmusicandopera|title=Brahms: Symphony No.4|first=Andrew|last=Clements|date=March 17, 2000|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n* 1980-1982: Wagner: ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'', Staatskapelle Dresden, Deutsche Grammophon. Soloists: [[Ren\u00e9 Kollo]], [[Margaret Price]], [[Brigitte Fassbaender]], [[Dietrich Fischer-Dieskau]], [[Kurt Moll]].\n* 1982: Ludwig van Beethoven: [[Symphony No. 4 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 4]], Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, Orfeo*.\n* 1982: Ludwig van Beethoven: Symphony No. 7, Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, Orfeo*.\n* 1983: Ludwig van Beethoven: [[Symphony No. 6 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 6]], Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, Orfeo*.\n* 1989: [[Vienna New Year's Concert]], Vienna Philharmonic, Sony Classical*.\n* 1992: Vienna New Year's Concert, Vienna Philharmonic, Sony Classical*.\n\n===Collections===\n* 2010: Complete Recordings on Deutsche Grammophon \u2013 12 CDs / Complete Opera and Concert DVDs on Deutsche Grammophon \u2013 10 DVDs\n* 2014: Complete orchestral Recordings on Deutsche Grammophon \u2013 3 CDs & 1 Blu-ray with Bonus Audio Documentary.\n\n== DVD releases ==\n* 1970: \"The Great conductors\", TDK and Arthaus. Overtures: ''[[Der Freisch\u00fctz]]'' & ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'' [[Stuttgart Radio Symphony Orchestra]] (rehearsals)\n* 1976: Verdi: ''[[Otello]]'', La Scala Milan Orchestra & Chorus, [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Mirella Freni]], [[Piero Cappuccilli]], Opera Legacies\n* 1978: Bizet: ''[[Carmen]]'', Vienna State Opera, TDK and Bel Canto. Soloists: [[Elena Obraztsova]], [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Yuri Mazurok]], [[Isobel Buchanan]].\n* 1979: Puccini: ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'', La Scala Milan Orchestra & Chorus, [[Ileana Cotruba\u0219]], [[Luciano Pavarotti]], Bel Canto Society\n* 1979: Strauss: ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'', Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, Deutsche Grammophon. Soloists: [[Gwyneth Jones (soprano)|Gwyneth Jones]], [[Brigitte Fassbaender]], [[Lucia Popp]], [[Francisco Araiza]].\n* 1983: Ludwig van Beethoven: Symphony No. 4, Symphony No. 7, [[Concertgebouw Orchestra|Concertgebouw Orchestra Amsterdam]], Philips.\n* 1986: Johann Strauss II: ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'', Orchestra of the Bavarian State Opera, Deutsche Grammophon. Soloists: [[Pamela Coburn]], [[Brigitte Fassbaender]], [[Janet Perry]], [[Eberhard Waechter (baritone)|Eberhard W\u00e4chter]].\n* 1989: Vienna New Year's Concert, Vienna Philharmonic, Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 1991: Mozart: [[Symphony No. 36 (Mozart)|Symphony No. 36]], Brahms: [[Symphony No. 2 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 2]], Vienna Philharmonic, Philips.\n* 1992: Vienna New Year's Concert, Vienna Philharmonic, Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 1994: Richard Strauss: ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'', [[Vienna State Opera|Orchestra of the Vienna State Opera]], Deutsche Grammophon. Soloists: [[Felicity Lott]], [[Kurt Moll]], [[Anne Sofie von Otter]], [[Gottfried Hornik]], [[Barbara Bonney]], [[Heinz Zednik]].\n* 1996: Ludwig van Beethoven: ''Coriolan'' Overture, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart: [[Symphony No. 33 (Mozart)|Symphony No. 33]], Johannes Brahms: Symphony No. 4, Bavarian State Orchestra, Deutsche Grammophon.\n* 2010: Complete Opera and Concert DVDs on Deutsche Grammophon \u2013 10 DVDs.\n* 2010: ''Carlos Kleiber \u2013 I Am Lost to the World'', documentary, Director: Georg W\u00fcbbolt, Production: BFMI / ZDF / 3sat, Distributor: C Major Entertainment.\n* 2011: ''Carlos Kleiber \u2013 Traces to Nowhere'', documentary, Director: Eric Schulz, Production: Servus TV, Distributor: EuroArts Music International.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Balestrazzi, Mauro: ''Carlos Kleiber \u2013 Angelo o demone?'', 2006, {{ISBN|88-8302-325-0}} (in Italian).\n* Drexel, Christina: ''Carlos Kleiber \u2013 ... einfach was dasteht!'', 2010, Verlag Dohr K\u00f6ln, {{ISBN|978-3-936655-89-6}} (in German).\n* Fischer, Jens Malte: ''Carlos Kleiber \u2013 Der skrupul\u00f6se Exzentriker'', 2006, {{ISBN|3-8353-0138-1}} (in German).\n* Vichev, Tomislav: ''Kleiber's Era'', 2003 (in Bulgarian).\n* Werner, Alexander: ''Carlos Kleiber \u2013 Eine Biografie'', 2007, 2nd, revised Edition, 2009, {{ISBN|978-3-7957-0598-5}}, 3rd Edition, paperback, July 2010 (in German)\n* Zignani, Alessandro: ''Il tramonto dell'Occidente'', 2010, {{ISBN|978-88-87203-95-0}}, Zecchini Editore (in Italian).\n\n== Filmography ==\n* [http://www.mediafire.com/?wn4lnykyqkk September 2009 BBC Radio program: ''Who Was Carlos Kleiber?'' ]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100823060702/http://www.servustv.com/cs/Satellite/Article/Spuren-ins-Nichts-011259286557317 Documentary ''Spuren ins Nichts \u2013 Der Dirigent Carlos Kleiber'', Deutschland, Slowenien, \u00d6sterreich, 2010, 52 Min., director Eric Schulz, Centauri, EuroArts Music International.Servus TV, 2010 ]\n* [http://www.cmajor-entertainment.com/catalogue/show/id/2341 TV documentary ''I am lost to the World'', directed by Georg W\u00fcbbolt, BFMI, ZDF, 3sat, C major Ent. March 2011]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.carlos-kleiber.de Biographer Alexander Werner's site]\n* [http://www.carlos-kleiber.com A memorial site with testimonials and video clips]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/carloskleiber2.0 Carlos Kleiber 2.0] (the Carlos Kleiber's community)\n* [http://www.thrsw.com Erich and Carlos Kleiber site]\n* [http://correspondingwithcarlos.com/ A site about the eponymous book]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070911161406/http://www.kleiber.hit.bg/en/ Kleiber's era]\n* {{Discogs artist}}\n\n{{Gramophone Hall of Fame}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Classical music}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kleiber, Carlos}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Austrian people]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Austrian conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:ETH Zurich alumni]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriates in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Austrian emigrants to Argentina]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriates in Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Deutsche Grammophon artists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bavarian Maximilian Order for Science and Art]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Austrian Decoration for Science and Art]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Pour le M\u00e9rite (civil class)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bavarian Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Johannes der Taucher", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Provided one requested footnote", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Kleiber"}
{"title_page": "Another Shore", "text_new": "{{short description|1948 film by Charles Crichton}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Another Shore\n| image          = AnotherShore1948Poster.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see WP:ALT -->\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Charles Crichton]]\n| producer       = [[Michael Balcon]] <br> [[Ivor Montagu]]\n| writer         = [[Kenneth Reddin]] (story)<br>Walter Meade (screenplay)\n| starring       = [[Robert Beatty]]<br>[[Moira Lister]]<br>[[Stanley Holloway]]\n| music          = [[Georges Auric]]|\n| cinematography = [[Douglas Slocombe]]\n| editing        = [[Bernard Gribble]]\n| studio         = [[Ealing Studios]]\n| distributor    = [[General Film Distributors]]\n| released       = 20 December 1948\n| runtime        = 77 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''Another Shore''''' is a 1948 [[Ealing Studios]] [[comedy film]] directed by [[Charles Crichton]].  It stars [[Robert Beatty]] as Gulliver Shields, an Irish customs official who dreams of living on a South Sea island; particularly [[Rarotonga]]. It is based on the book by [[Kenneth Reddin]], an Irish judge.\n\n==Premise==\nGulliver leaves his job in [[Dublin]] to sit on a park bench waiting for an elderly person to faint that, in his mind, he will rescue and they will reward him with an amount of money to get him to the South Seas. He meets Jennifer, a society playgirl who is fascinated by Gulliver's indifference to her.  The day of destiny comes when he has to choose between his dreams and Jennifer.\n\n==Main cast==\n* [[Robert Beatty]] \u2013 Gulliver Shields\n* [[Moira Lister]] \u2013 Jennifer\n* [[Stanley Holloway]] \u2013 Alastair McNeil\n* [[Michael Medwin]] \u2013 Yellow Bingham\n* [[Sheila Manahan]] \u2013 Nora\n* [[Fred O'Donovan]] \u2013 Coghlan\n* [[Maureen Delany]] \u2013 Mrs Gleeson\n* [[Dermot Kelly (actor)|Dermot Kelly]] \u2013 Boxer\n* [[Irene Worth]] \u2013 Bucsy Vere-Brown \n* [[Bill Shine (actor)|Bill Shine]] \u2013 Bats Vere-Brown \n* [[Muriel Aked]] \u2013 Old lady\n* [[Wilfrid Brambell]] \u2013 Arthur Moore\n* [[Michael J. Dolan]] \u2013 Twiss\n\n==Production==\n''Another Shore'' was filmed in [[Ireland]].\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|0040103|Another Shore}}\n*[https://archive.org/stream/variety172-1948-12#page/n9/mode/2up Review] at ''Variety''\n{{Charles Crichton}}\n{{Michael Balcon}}\n\n[[Category:1948 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Ealing Studios films]]\n[[Category:1940s comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Charles Crichton]]\n[[Category:Films set in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Georges Auric]]\n\n\n{{1940s-UK-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1948 film by Charles Crichton}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Another Shore\n| image          = AnotherShore1948Poster.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see WP:ALT -->\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Charles Crichton]]\n| producer       = [[Michael Balcon]] <br> [[Ivor Montagu]]\n| writer         = [[Kenneth Reddin]] (story)<br>Walter Meade (screenplay)\n| starring       = [[Robert Beatty]]<br>[[Moira Lister]]<br>[[Stanley Holloway]]\n| music          = [[Georges Auric]]|\n| cinematography = [[Douglas Slocombe]]\n| editing        = [[Bernard Gribble]]\n| studio         = [[Ealing Studios]]\n| distributor    = [[General Film Distributors]]\n| released       = 20 December 1948\n| runtime        = 77 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''Another Shore''''' is a 1948 [[Ealing Studios]] [[comedy film]] directed by [[Charles Crichton]].  It stars [[Robert Beatty]] as Gulliver Shields, an Irish customs official who dreams of living on a South Sea island; particularly [[Rarotonga]]. It is based on the book by [[Kenneth Reddin]], an Irish judge.\n\n==Premise==\nGulliver leaves his job in [[Dublin]] to sit on a park bench waiting for an elderly person to faint that, in his mind, he will rescue and they will reward him with an amount of money to get him to the South Seas. He meets Jennifer, a society playgirl who is fascinated by Gulliver's indifference to her.  The day of destiny comes when he has to choose between his dreams and Jennifer.\n\n==Main cast==\n* [[Robert Beatty]] \u2013 Gulliver Shields\n* [[Moira Lister]] \u2013 Jennifer\n* [[Stanley Holloway]] \u2013 Alastair McNeil\n* [[Michael Medwin]] \u2013 Yellow Bingham\n* [[Sheila Manahan]] \u2013 Nora\n* [[Fred O'Donovan]] \u2013 Coghlan\n* [[Maureen Delany]] \u2013 Mrs Gleeson\n* [[Dermot Kelly (actor)|Dermot Kelly]] \u2013 Boxer\n* [[Irene Worth]] \u2013 Bucsy Vere-Brown \n* [[Bill Shine (actor)]] \u2013 Bats Vere-Brown \n* [[Muriel Aked]] \u2013 Old lady\n* [[Wilfrid Brambell]] \u2013 Arthur Moore\n* [[Michael J. Dolan]] \u2013 Twiss\n\n==Production==\n''Another Shore'' was filmed in [[Ireland]].\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|0040103|Another Shore}}\n*[https://archive.org/stream/variety172-1948-12#page/n9/mode/2up Review] at ''Variety''\n{{Charles Crichton}}\n{{Michael Balcon}}\n\n[[Category:1948 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Ealing Studios films]]\n[[Category:1940s comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Charles Crichton]]\n[[Category:Films set in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Georges Auric]]\n\n\n{{1940s-UK-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Beryl reid fan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\