ll of Fame===\nEight former Alabama football players have been inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]], the fourth most among all colleges.<ref name=HOF>{{cite web|last=Hall of Fame|title=Inductees by College |url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/colleges.aspx |publisher=PFHOF |accessdate=November 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Alabama Crimson Tide|Inducted|Player|Seasons|NFL Team(s)|Years with NFL Team(s)}}\n|-\n| 1963 || [[Don Hutson]] || 1932\u20131934 || [[Green Bay Packers]] || 1935\u20131945\n|-\n| 1977 || [[Bart Starr]] || 1952\u20131955 || [[Green Bay Packers]] || 1956\u20131971\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1985 || rowspan=2 | [[Joe Namath]] || rowspan=2 | 1962\u20131964 || [[New York Jets]] || 1965\u20131976\n|-\n| [[Los Angeles Rams]] || 1977\n|-\n| 1991 || [[John Hannah (American football)|John Hannah]] || 1970\u20131972 || [[New England Patriots]] || 1973\u20131985\n|-\n| 1998 || [[Dwight Stephenson]] || 1977\u20131979 || [[Miami Dolphins]] || 1980\u20131987\n|-\n| 1999 || [[Ozzie Newsome]] || 1974\u20131977 || [[Cleveland Browns]] || 1978\u20131990\n|-\n| 2009 || [[Derrick Thomas]] || 1985\u20131988 || [[Kansas City Chiefs]] || 1989\u20131999\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 2016 || rowspan=3 | [[Ken Stabler]] || rowspan=3 | 1964\u20131967 || [[Oakland Raiders]] || 1970\u20131979\n|-\n| [[Houston Oilers]] || 1980\u20131981\n|-\n| [[New Orleans Saints]] || 1982\u20131984\n|}\n\n===Players in the National Football League===\nAlabama has 75 players with NFL teams as of April 2020.\n{{colbegin|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Jonathan Allen]], DE \u2013 [[Washington Redskins]]\n* [[Ryan Anderson (American football)|Ryan Anderson]], LB \u2013 [[Washington Redskins]]\n* [[Anthony Averett]], CB \u2013 [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n* [[Bradley Bozeman]], C \u2013 [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n* [[Tony Brown (defensive back, born 1995)|Tony Brown]], CB \u2013 [[Cincinnati Bengals]]\n* [[Isaiah Buggs]], DT - [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n* [[James Carpenter (American football)|James Carpenter]], OG \u2013 [[Atlanta Falcons]]\n* Shyheim Carter, S - [[New York Jets]]\n* [[Ha Ha Clinton-Dix]], S - [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n* [[Landon Collins]], S \u2013 [[Washington Redskins]]\n* [[Amari Cooper]], WR \u2013 [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n* Lester Cotton, OL - [[Las Vegas Raiders]]\n* [[Marcell Dareus]], DT \u2013 [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]\n* [[Raekwon Davis]], DT - [[Miami Dolphins]]\n* [[Gehrig Dieter]], WR - [[Kansas City Chiefs]]\n* [[Trevon Diggs]], CB - [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n* [[Kenyan Drake]], RB \u2013 [[Arizona Cardinals]]\n* Johnny Dwight, DE - [[Houston Texans]]\n* [[Rashaan Evans]], LB- [[Tennessee Titans]]\n<!-- * [[D.J. Fluker]], OT \u2013 [[Baltimore Ravens]] if he passes a physical -->\n* [[Minkah Fitzpatrick]], FS- [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n* [[Reuben Foster]], LB \u2013 [[Washington Redskins]]\n* [[Robert Foster (American football)|Robert Foster]], WR- [[Buffalo Bills]]\n* [[Brandon Greene]], OL- [[Carolina Panthers]]\n* [[Shaun Dion Hamilton]], LB- [[Washington Redskins]]\n* [[Da'Shawn Hand]], DE \u2013 [[Detroit Lions]]\n* [[Damien Harris]], RB - [[New England Patriots]]\n* [[Ronnie Harrison]], SS- [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]\n* [[J. C. Hassenauer]], C- [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n* [[Derrick Henry]], RB \u2013 [[Tennessee Titans]]\n* [[Hale Hentges]], TE- [[Washington Redskins]]\n* [[Dont'a Hightower]], LB \u2013 [[New England Patriots]]\n* [[OJ Howard]], TE \u2013 [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]\n* [[Marlon Humphrey]], CB- [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n* [[Mark Ingram Jr.|Mark Ingram]], RB- [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n* [[Eddie Jackson (safety)|Eddie Jackson]], S \u2013 [[Chicago Bears]]\n* [[Kareem Jackson]], CB \u2013 [[Denver Broncos]]\n* [[Josh Jacobs]], RB - [[Las Vegas Raiders]]\n* [[Anfernee Jennings]], LB - [[New England Patriots]]\n* [[Jerry Jeudy]], WR - [[Denver Broncos]]\n* [[Julio Jones]], WR \u2013 [[Atlanta Falcons]]\n* [[Ryan Kelly (American football)|Ryan Kelly]], C \u2013 [[Indianapolis Colts]]\n* [[Terrell Lewis (American football)|Terrell Lewis]], LB - [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n* Cole Mazza, LS- [[Los Angeles Chargers]]\n* Jared Mayden, S - [[San Francisco 49ers]]\n* [[AJ McCarron]], QB - [[Houston Texans]]\n* [[Xavier McKinney]], S - [[New York Giants]]\n* [[Christian Miller (American football)|Christian Miller]], LB - [[Carolina Panthers]]\n* [[CJ Mosley (linebacker)|CJ Mosley]], LB \u2013 [[New York Jets]]\n* [[Daron Payne]], NT \u2013 [[Washington Redskins]]\n* [[Ross Pierschbacher]], C - [[Washington Redskins]]\n* [[Reggie Ragland]], LB \u2013 [[Detroit Lions]]\n* [[Jarran Reed]], DT \u2013 [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n* [[Calvin Ridley]], WR \u2013 [[Atlanta Falcons]]\n* [[A'Shawn Robinson]], DT \u2013 [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n* [[Cam Robinson]], OT \u2013 [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]\n* [[Henry Ruggs III]], WR - [[Las Vegas Raiders]]\n* [[Bo Scarbrough]], RB - [[Detroit Lions]]\n* [[JK Scott]], P- [[Green Bay Packers]]\n* [[Cam Sims]], WR - [[Washington Redskins]]\n* [[Andre Smith (offensive tackle)|Andre Smith]], OT - [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n* [[Irv Smith Jr.]], TE - [[Minnesota Vikings]]\n* Saivion Smith, CB - [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n* [[Damion Square]], DT - [[Los Angeles Chargers]]\n* [[Tua Tagovailoa]], QB - [[Miami Dolphins]]\n* [[Deionte Thompson]], S - [[Arizona Cardinals]]\n* [[Dalvin Tomlinson]], DT \u2013 [[New York Giants]]\n* [[Levi Wallace (American football)|Levi Wallace]], CB- [[Buffalo Bills]]\n* [[Chance Warmack]], OL - [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n* [[DeAndrew White]], WR - [[Carolina Panthers]]\n* [[Jonah Williams]], OT - [[Cincinnati Bengals]]\n* [[Quinnen Williams]], DL - [[New York Jets]]\n* [[Tim Williams (American football)|Tim Williams]], LB \u2013 [[Green Bay Packers]]\n* [[Jedrick Wills]], OT - [[Cleveland Browns]]\n* [[Mack Wilson]], LB - [[Cleveland Browns]]\n* [[TJ Yeldon]], RB- [[Buffalo Bills]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Media==\nDuring the football season, the [[Crimson Tide Sports Network]] (CTSN) broadcasts multiple shows on gameday for most sports. The network includes more than 60 radio stations across the country. Radio stations [[WFFN]]-FM, [[WTSK]]-AM as a backup, broadcast all home games in the Tuscaloosa area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/radio-tv.html |title=Radio/TV Information |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=October 8, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080930090614/http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/radio-tv.html| archivedate= September 30, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nFootball radio broadcasts begin three hours prior to the game's designated kickoff time with Chris Stewart and Tyler Watts in ''Around the SEC''.<ref name=\"Game-broadcasts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/footbl-gameday.html |title=CTSN Game Broadcasts |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=October 8, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080914062559/http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/footbl-gameday.html| archivedate= September 14, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> The radio broadcast then moves to the ''Crimson Tide Tailgate Party'' hosted by Tom Roberts.<ref name=\"Game-broadcasts\" /> Immediately following the end of the game, the ''Fifth Quarter Show'' begins as host Eli Gold talks to coaches and players and gives game statistics.<ref name=\"Game-broadcasts\" /> For the 2008 season, former Alabama players and personalities were brought on to provide guest commentary for each broadcast.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/genrel/081208aac.html |title=CTSN Ready for 2008 Football Season |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=October 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Eli Gold.jpg|thumb|[[Eli Gold]] has done play-by-play work for Alabama football since 1988.]]\n'''Current radio staff''':<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/crew.html |title=The Crew |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=October 17, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081003074905/http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/crew.html| archivedate= October 3, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/radio-tv.html |title=Crimson Tide Radio and Television Information, Football |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=October 15, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080408073937/http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/radio-tv.html |archivedate=April 8, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Eli Gold]] \u2013 play-by-play\n* [[John Parker Wilson]] \u2013 color analyst\n* [[Rashad Johnson]] \u2013 sideline reporter\n* Chris Stewart, Tyler Watts \u2013 pre- and post-game show co-host\n* Tom Roberts \u2013 director of broadcasting\n* Tom Stipe, Butch Owens, Brian Roberts \u2013 producers\n\nStewart and Watts also provide play-by-play and color commentary respectively for CTSN pay-per-view television broadcasts.\n\n'''Former radio staff''':\n* [[Bert Bank]], founder of the Alabama Football Network, producer emeritus\n* John Forney, play-by-play\n* Jerry Duncan, sideline reporter\n* Paul Kennedy, play-by-play\n* Doug Layton, color analyst\n* [[Ken Stabler]], color analyst<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myespn.go.com/blogs/hashmarks/0-8-150/Ex-Raiders-star-Stabler-leaves-radio-gig.html |title=Ex-Raiders star Stabler leaves radio gig |publisher=ESPN |last=Williamson |first=Bill |date=July 11, 2008 |accessdate=October 8, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009061830/http://myespn.go.com/blogs/hashmarks/0-8-150/Ex-Raiders-star-Stabler-leaves-radio-gig.html |archivedate=October 9, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabama/huntsvilletimes/index.ssf?/base/sports/1215854130308570.xml&coll=1 |title=Stabler leaves UA radio job |work=The Huntsville Times |date=July 12, 2008 |accessdate=October 8, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609071808/http://www.al.com/alabama/huntsvilletimes/index.ssf?%2Fbase%2Fsports%2F1215854130308570.xml&coll=1 |archivedate=June 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Future opponents==\n\n===Non-division conference opponents===\nAlabama plays Tennessee as a permanent non-division opponent annually and rotates around the ''East'' division among the other six schools.<ref name=\"nondivopp\">{{cite web| title=SEC Future Football Schedule Rotation Announced|publisher=fbschedules.com| url=http://www.fbschedules.com/2014/05/sec-future-football-schedule-rotation-2025/|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#9E1B32; color:white; text-align:center;\"\n| '''2021''' || <span style=\"color:white;\">'''2022'''</span> || '''2023 ''' || '''2024''' || '''2025'''\n|- align=center\n| vs Tennessee || at Tennessee || vs Tennessee || at Tennessee || vs Tennessee\n|- align=center\n| at Florida || vs Vanderbilt || at Kentucky || vs South Carolina || at Missouri\n|}\n\n===Non-conference opponents===\nAnnounced schedules as of April 26, 2020.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Alabama Crimson Tide|2021|2022|2023|2024|2025|2026|2027|2028|2029|2030|2031|2032|2033|2034|2035}}\n|-\n| vs. [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]]\n| [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]]\n| [[Central Michigan Chippewas football|Central Michigan]]\n| [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky]]\n| at [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]]\n| at [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]]\n| West Virginia\n| at [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame]]\n| Notre Dame\n| at [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech]]\n| Georgia Tech\n| at [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]]\n| Oklahoma\n| at [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]]\n| Virginia Tech\n|- \n| [[Southern Miss Golden Eagles football|Southern Miss]]\n| at [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]]\n| Texas\n| [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]]\n| Louisiana\u2212Monroe\n| South Florida\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|- \n| [[New Mexico State Aggies football|New Mexico State]]\n| [[Louisiana-Monroe Warhawks football|Louisiana\u2212Monroe]]\n| at South Florida\n| at [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]]\n| Wisconsin\n| Florida State\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|- \n| [[Mercer Bears football|Mercer]]\n| [[Austin Peay Governors football|Austin Peay]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|}\n:'''Source:'''<ref name=\"nonconfopp\">{{cite web|url=https://fbschedules.com/ncaa/alabama/|title=Alabama Crimson Tide Football Future Schedules|publisher=FBSchedules.com|accessdate=April 26, 2020}}</ref>\n* The 2020 game against USC will be part of the [[Advocare Classic]] held at [[AT&T Stadium]] in [[Arlington, Texas]].<ref name=\"USC2020\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/23585956/alabama-crimson-tide-usc-trojans-kick-2020-season-arlington-texas|title=Alabama-USC to kick off 2020 season in Texas|work=ESPN.com|access-date=June 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* The 2021 game against Miami will be part of the [[Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game]] held at [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]].<ref name=\"MIA2021\">{{cite news |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/college/acc/university-of-miami/article171325272.html|title=Miami Hurricanes to renew football rivalry with Nick Saban and Alabama|first=George |last=Richards |newspaper=[[Miami Herald]] |date=September 5, 2017 |access-date=June 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alabama Crimson Tide home football stadiums]]\n* [[University of Alabama traditions]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-la|refs=\n{{efn-la|name=\"notea\"|In 1995, the NCAA forfeited Alabama eight regular season victories and one tie from the 1993 season.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alabama Put on Probation College football: NCAA sanctions program for three years. The team is banned from postseason play next season. |work=Los Angeles Times |date=August 3, 1995 <!--|accessdate=October 7, 2008-->}}</ref>}}\n{{efn-la|name=\"noteb\"|In 2009, the NCAA vaca}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=Southern Fried Football: The History, Passion, and Glory of the Great Southern Game |url=https://archive.org/details/southernfriedfoo0000barn |url-access=registration |last=Barnhart |first=Tony |author2=[[Keith Jackson]] |publisher=Triumph Books |year=2000 |isbn=1-60078-093-8}}\n* {{cite book |title=Roll Tide: The Alabama Crimson Tide Story |last=Davis |first=Terry |publisher=Creative Education |year=1999 |isbn=0-88682-975-5}}\n* {{cite book |title=Talk of the Tide: an oral history of Alabama football since 1920 |last=Forney |first=John |publisher=Crane Hill Publishers |year=1993 |isbn=1-881548-03-1}}\n* {{cite book |title=Crimson Nation |last=Gold |first=Eli |authorlink=Eli Gold |publisher=Thomas Nelson Incorporated |year=2005 |isbn=1-4016-0190-1 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/crimsonnation0000gold }}\n* {{cite book |title=The Crimson Tide \u2013 An Illustrated History |last=Groom |first=Winston |authorlink=Winston Groom |publisher=The University of Alabama Press |year=2000 |isbn=0-8173-1051-7}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Crimson Tide: Alabama Football |last=Langford |first=George |publisher=H. Regnery Co |year=1974 |isbn=0-8092-8363-8}}\n* {{cite book |title=Crimson Tide Madness: Great Eras in Alabama Football |last=Sharpe |first=Wilton |publisher=Cumberland House Publishing |year=2007 |isbn=1-58182-580-3}}\n* {{cite book |title=Tales from 1978\u201379 Alabama Football: A Time of Champions |last=Townsend |first=Steve |publisher=Sports Publishing LLC |year=2003 |isbn=1-58261-425-3}}\n* {{cite book |title=Crimson Storm Surge: Alabama Football Then and Now |last=Walsh |first=Christopher J. |publisher=Taylor Trade Publishing |year=2005 |isbn=1-58979-279-3}}\n* {{cite book |title=Football Powers of the South |last=Wells |first=Lawrence |publisher=Sports Yearbook Company |year=2000 |isbn=0-916242-27-7}}\n* {{cite book |title=Alabama Football: The Greatest Games, Players, Coaches, and Teams in the Glorious Tradition of Crimson Tide Football |author=Athlon Sports |author2=[[Mike Shula]] |publisher=Triumph Books |year=2006 |isbn=1-57243-880-0}}\n* {{cite book |title=Greatest Moments in Alabama Crimson Tide Football History |author=''[[The Tuscaloosa News]]'' |author2=Mike Bynum, Associated Press |publisher=Distributors |year=2003 |isbn=1-928846-65-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alabama Crimson Tide football}}\n* {{Official website}}\n<!-- List only OFFICIAL websites \u2013 others will be removed. See talk page discussion. -->\n\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{University of Alabama}}\n{{Southeastern Conference football navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football|*]]\n[[Category:American football teams established in 1892]]\n[[Category:1892 establishments in Alabama|Crimson Tide]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|University of Alabama Football Team}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NCAA football school\n| TeamName = Alabama Crimson Tide football\n| CurrentSeason = 2020 Alabama Crimson Tide football team\n| Image = Alabama Athletics logo.svg\n| ImageSize = 125\n| FirstYear = {{start date|1892}}\n| LastYear =\n| AthleticDirector = [[Greg Byrne (athletic director)|Greg Byrne]]\n| HeadCoach = [[Nick Saban]]\n| HeadCoachYear = 13th\n| HCWins = 152<!-- As of games through 1/1/2020 -->\n| HCLosses = 23 <!-- As of games through 1/1/2020 -->\n| Stadium = [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]]\n| StadCapacity = 101,821<ref name=\"BDS\" />\n| FieldName =\n| StadiumBuilt =\n| StadSurface = Natural grass\n| Location = [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]]\n| NCAAdivision = <!-- I, I FBS, I FCS, ... | League = -->\n| Conference = [[Southeastern Conference]]\n| ConfDivision = Western\n| PastAffiliations = [[Southern Conference]] (1921\u20131932)\n| ATWins = 916\n| ATLosses = 331\n| ATTies = 43<!--<sup id=\"inlinea\" class=\"reference\">[[#notea|[a]]]</sup><sup id=\"inlineb\" class=\"reference\">[[#noteb|[b]]]</sup> Needs to be included but is causing formula error-->\n| BowlWins = 42\n| BowlLosses = 26\n| BowlTies = 3\n| PlayoffApps = 5 (2014, '''2015''', 2016, '''2017''', 2018)\n| Playoffs = 6\u20133 ([[College Football Playoff|CFP]])\n| NatlTitles = 17 (1925, 1926, 1930, 1934, 1941, 1961, 1964, 1965, 1973, 1978, 1979, 1992, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2015, 2017)<ref name=\"Bama-NCs-text\" />\n| UnNatlTitles = 4 (1945, 1966, 1975, 1977)\n| NatlFinalist = 4\n| ConfTitles = 31 (Southern: 4; SEC: 27)\n| DivTitles = 14\n| Rivalries = [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]] ([[Iron Bowl|rivalry]]) <br>[[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] ([[Third Saturday in October|rivalry]]) <br>[[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] ([[Alabama\u2013LSU football rivalry|rivalry]]) <br>[[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]] ([[Alabama\u2013Mississippi State football rivalry|rivalry]]) <br>[[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]] ([[Alabama\u2013Ole Miss football rivalry|rivalry]]) <br>[[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] ([[Alabama\u2013Georgia football rivalry|rivalry]]) <br>[[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]] ([[Alabama\u2013Clemson football rivalry|rivalry]])\n| Heismans = 2\n| AllAmericans = 74\n| color1           = Crimson\n| color1hex        = 9d2235\n| color2           = White\n| color2hex        = ffffff\n| FightSong = Yea Alabama\n| Mascot = [[Big Al (mascot)|Big Al]]\n| MarchingBand = [[Million Dollar Band (marching band)|Million Dollar Band]]\n| PagFreeLabel = Outfitter\n| PagFreeValue = [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]\n| PagFreeLabel2 =\n| PagFreeValue2 =\n| uniform = [[File:Alabama crimson football uniform.png|200px]]\n| WebsiteName = Rolltide.com\n| WebsiteURL = https://rolltide.com/sports/football\n}}\n\nThe '''Alabama Crimson Tide football''' program represents the [[University of Alabama]] (variously Alabama, UA, or Bama) in the sport of [[American football]]. The team competes in the [[Football Bowl Subdivision]] (FBS) of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) and the Western Division of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web1.ncaa.org/onlineDir/exec/sponsorship?sortOrder=0&division=1A&sport=MFB |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210103938/http://web1.ncaa.org/onlineDir/exec/sponsorship?sortOrder=0&division=1A&sport=MFB |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 10, 2007 |title=NCAA Sports Sponsorship |publisher=NCAA |accessdate=October 2, 2008}}</ref> The team is currently coached by [[Nick Saban]]. The Crimson Tide is among the most storied and decorated football programs in NCAA history. Since beginning play in 1892, the program claims 17 [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|national championships]],<ref name=\"Bama-NCs-text\" /><ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" /><ref name=\"NCAA_Past-champs\" /> including 12 wire-service ([[AP Poll|AP]] or [[Coaches Poll|Coaches]]) national titles in the poll-era, and five other titles before the poll-era.<ref name=\"NCAA_Past-champs\" /><ref name=NCAA_current_champs>{{cite web |url=https://www.ncaa.com/history/football/fbs |title=Recognized National Championships by Year |publisher= NCAA Official Records |accessdate= January 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/2017/FBS.pdf</ref> From 1958 to 1982, the team was led by Hall of Fame coach [[Bear Bryant|Paul \"Bear\" Bryant]], who won six national championships with the program.<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" /> Despite numerous national and conference championships, it was not until 2009 that an Alabama player received a [[Heisman Trophy]], when running back [[Mark Ingram Jr.|Mark Ingram]] became the university's first winner. In 2015, [[Derrick Henry]] became the university's second Heisman winner.<ref name=\"Ingram-Heisman\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/13/sports/ncaafootball/13heisman.html |title=Mark Ingram Wins Heisman Trophy in Close Race |work=New York Times |author=Armstrong, Kevin |date=December 12, 2009 |accessdate=December 13, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114003932/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/13/sports/ncaafootball/13heisman.html|archivedate=November 14, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlabama has 916 official victories{{efn-la|name=\"notea\"}}{{efn-la|name=\"noteb\"}} in NCAA Division I (an additional 21 victories were vacated, and eight victories and one tie were forfeited), has won 31 conference championships (4 [[Southern Conference]] and 27 SEC championships), and has made an NCAA-record 71 postseason bowl appearances. Other NCAA records include 23 winning streaks of ten games or more and 19 seasons with a 10\u20130 start. The program has 34 seasons with ten wins or more (plus one vacated)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/alab/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2012-13/misc_non_event/2012FootballRecordBook.pdf |title=2012 Football Record Book |work=rolltide.com |author=The University of Alabama |publisher=rolltide.com |date=August 15, 2012 |accessdate=October 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130717112227/http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/alab/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2012-13/misc_non_event/2012FootballRecordBook.pdf |archivedate=July 17, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/powerrankings |title=2013 Week 12 College Football Power Rankings |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN |date=November 18, 2013 |accessdate=November 18, 2013 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091123225437/http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-no1-10win-seasons.html |archivedate= November 23, 2009 |url-status= live}}</ref> and has 41<sup id=\"inlineb\" class=\"reference\">[[#noteb|[b]]]</sup> bowl victories, both NCAA records.<ref name=\"2011 Records\">{{cite web |title=Official 2011 NCAA Football Records Book: Football Bowl Subdivision Records |url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/2011/FBS.pdf |publisher=National Collegiate Athletic Association |accessdate=July 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69ADBDpBX?url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/2011/FBS.pdf |archivedate=July 15, 2012 |page=128 |format=PDF |year=2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> Alabama has completed ten undefeated seasons, nine of which were perfect seasons. The Crimson Tide leads the SEC West Division with 14 division titles and 12 appearances in the [[SEC Championship Game]]. Alabama holds a winning record against every current and former SEC school. The [[Associated Press]] (AP) ranks Alabama 4th in all-time final AP Poll appearances, with 53 through the 2015 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collegepollarchive.com/football/ap/app_final.cfm |title=Total Appearances in the Final AP Poll |publisher=Collegepollarchive.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69A7cURvV?url=http://collegepollarchive.com/football/ap/app_final.cfm |archivedate=July 14, 2012 |url-status=live |accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://cfn.scout.com/2/1097657.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110920203815/http://cfn.scout.com/2/1097657.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= September 20, 2011 |title= The Greatest Program of all Time Is{{nbsp}}... |publisher= Scout with FoxSports.com |date= August 19, 2012 |accessdate= August 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAlabama plays its home games at [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]], located on the campus in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]].<ref name=\"BDS\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/facilities/bryant-denny.html |title=Bryant-Denny Stadium |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=August 19, 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100828081314/http://www.rolltide.com/facilities/bryant-denny.html |archivedate= August 28, 2010 |url-status= live}}</ref> With a capacity of 101,821,<ref name=\"BDS\" /> Bryant-Denny is the [[List of stadiums by capacity|8th largest]] non-racing stadium in the world and the [[List of North American stadiums by capacity|seventh largest]] stadium in the United States.\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of Alabama Crimson Tide football}}\n{{See also|List of Alabama Crimson Tide football seasons}}\n\n===Head coaching history===\n{{main|List of Alabama Crimson Tide head football coaches}}\n\nAlabama has had 28 head coaches since organized football began in 1892. Adopting the nickname ''\"Crimson Tide\"'' after the 1907 season, 12 coaches have led the Crimson Tide in postseason bowl games: [[Wallace Wade]], [[Frank Thomas (American football)|Frank Thomas]], [[Harold Drew|Harold D. \"Red\" Drew]], [[Bear Bryant]], [[Ray Perkins (wide receiver)|Ray Perkins]], [[Bill Curry]], [[Gene Stallings]], [[Mike DuBose]], [[Dennis Franchione]], [[Mike Shula]], [[Joe Kines]], and [[Nick Saban]].<ref name=\"Bama-NCs-text\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/trads/national-championships.html |title=National Championships |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=July 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022183419/http://www.rolltide.com/trads/national-championships.html |archivedate=October 22, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Eight of those coaches also won [[athletic conference|conference]] championships: Wade, Thomas, Drew, Bryant, Curry, Stallings, DuBose, and Saban. During their tenures, Wade, Thomas, Bryant, Stallings, and Saban all won [[NCAA Division I FBS National Football Championship|national championships]] with the Crimson Tide.<ref name=\"Bama-NCs-text\" />\n\nOf the 27 different head coaches who have led the Crimson Tide, Wade,<ref>{{College Football HoF|id=1402|name=Wallace Wade |accessdate=January 11, 2010}}</ref> Thomas,<ref>{{College Football HoF|id=1466|name=Frank Thomas |accessdate=January 9, 2010}}</ref> Bryant,<ref>{{College Football HoF|id=1955|name=Paul Bryant |accessdate=January 9, 2010}}</ref> and Stallings have been inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]]. The current head coach is Nick Saban, who was hired in January 2007.<ref name=\"Saban-hired\">{{cite news |last=Pasquarelli |first=Len |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2718488 |title=After repeated denials, Saban takes Bama job |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ESPN |date=January 4, 2007 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69ABmy7Ej?url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2718488 |archivedate=July 15, 2012 |accessdate=October 6, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===National championships===\nNational championships in [[NCAA]] [[Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]] college football are debated as the NCAA does not officially award the championship. Despite not naming an official [[NCAA Division I FBS National Football Championship|National Champion]], the NCAA provides lists of championships awarded by organizations it recognizes.<ref name=\"NCAA_Past-champs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.org/wps/ncaa?key=/ncaa/NCAA/Sports%20and%20Championship/General%20Information/ia_football_past_champs.html |title=Past Division I-A Football National Champions |publisher=NCAA |accessdate=December 29, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124233545/http://www.ncaa.org/wps/ncaa?key=%2Fncaa%2FNCAA%2FSports%20and%20Championship%2FGeneral%20Information%2Fia_football_past_champs.html |archivedate=November 24, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"NCAA-history\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ncaa.com/default.php?id=91434 |title=NCAA History |publisher=NCAA |accessdate=October 7, 2008}}{{dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> According to the official NCAA 2009 Division I Football Records Book, \"During the last 138 years, there have been more than 30 selectors of national champions using polls, historical research and mathematical rating systems. Beginning in 1936, the Associated Press began the best-known and most widely circulated poll of sportswriters and broadcasters. Before 1936, national champions were determined by historical research and retroactive ratings and polls. [...] The criteria for being included in this historical list of poll selectors is that the poll be national in scope, either through distribution in newspaper, television, radio and/or computer online.\"<ref name=\"2009 Division I Football Records Book\">{{cite web |url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/football_records/DI/2009/2009FBS.pdf |title=Football Bowl Subdivision Records pp. 76\u201378 |publisher=NCAA |accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSince World War II, Alabama claims only national championships awarded by the final [[AP Poll]] or the final [[Coaches' Poll]]. This policy is consistent with other FBS football programs with numerous national title claims, including Notre Dame, [[USC Trojans football|USC]], and [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]]. All national championships claimed by the University of Alabama were published in nationally syndicated newspapers and magazines, and each of the national championship selectors, and are cited in the Official 2010 NCAA [[Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]] Record Book.<ref>http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/DI/2010/2010FBS.pdf</ref> In addition to the championships claimed by the university, the NCAA has listed Alabama as receiving a championship for the [[1945 college football season|1945]], [[1966 NCAA University Division football season|1966]], [[1975 NCAA Division I football season|1975]], and [[1977 NCAA Division I football season|1977 college football seasons]].<ref name=\"NCAA_Past-champs\" /><ref name=\"NCAA-history\" />\n\nIn Alabama's 1982 media guide, the last for Coach Bryant, 1934 is listed as the only national championship before Coach Bryant in a footnote about the school's SEC history. In the 1980s, Alabama's Sports Information Director Wayne Atcheson started recognizing five pre-Bryant national championship teams (1925, 1926, 1930, 1934, 1941) by adding them to the University's Football Media Guide. According to Atcheson, he made the effort in the context of disputed titles being claimed by other schools, and \"to make Alabama football look the best it could look\" to compete with the other claimants. Atcheson maintains that the titles are the school's rightful claims.<ref name=\"Solomon-2010\">Solomon, John (January 6, 2010) \"[http://blog.al.com/solomon/2010/01/got_12.html Got 12? Here's how Alabama bumped up its claim to a dozen national titles]\". ''[[The Birmingham News]]''.</ref>\n\nThe [[University of Alabama]] 2009 Official Football Media Guide says Alabama had 12 national championships prior to winning the [[2010 BCS National Championship Game]].<ref>\"[http://www.rolltide.com/promotions/2009-m-footbl-guide.html\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119080308/http://www.rolltide.com/promotions/2009-m-footbl-guide.html |date=January 19, 2010}}</ref> The 2009, 2011, 2012, 2015, and 2017 titles bring the total number of national championships claimed by Alabama to 17. Twelve of Alabama's national championships were awarded by the wire-services ([[AP Poll|AP]], [[Coaches' Poll]]) or by winning the [[BCS National Championship Game]].<ref name=\"NCAA_Past-champs\" /><ref name=\"NCAA-history\" />\n\nIn January 2013, CNN suggested that Alabama might be college football's new dynasty,<ref name=\"Is Alabama college football's new dynasty?\">{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/01/08/sport/bcs-championship |publisher=CNN, Turner Broadcasting Company |title=Is Alabama college football's new dynasty? |accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> and in May 2013, Athlon Sports ranked Alabama's ongoing dynasty as the fourth-best since 1934, behind [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]] (1948\u201358), [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] (1986\u201392), and [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]] (1993\u201397).<ref name=\"Athlon Sports ranks the best dynasties in college football since the AP Poll debuted\">{{cite web |url=http://athlonsports.com/college-football/college-footballs-top-25-greatest-dynasties-ap-era |publisher=FoxSports.com |title=College Football's Top 25 Greatest Dynasties of the AP Era |accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====National championship seasons====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Alabama Crimson Tide|Season|Coach|Selectors|Record|Bowl}}\n|-\n| [[1925 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1925]] || rowspan=\"3\"|[[Wallace Wade]] || rowspan=\"4\"|Various || 10\u20130 || '''W''' [[1926 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]]\n|-\n| [[1926 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1926]] || 9\u20130\u20131 || T [[1927 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]]\n|-\n| [[1930 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1930]] || 10\u20130 || '''W''' [[1931 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]]\n|-\n| [[1934 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1934]] || rowspan=\"2\"| [[Frank Thomas (American football)|Frank Thomas]] || 10\u20130 || '''W''' [[1935 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]]\n|-\n| [[1941 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1941]] || Houlgate Poll || 9\u20132 || '''W''' [[1942 Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl Classic]]\n|-\n| [[1961 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1961]] || rowspan=\"6\"|[[Bear Bryant|Paul \"Bear\" Bryant]] || rowspan=\"2|[[AP Poll|AP]], [[Coaches Poll|Coaches']] || 11\u20130 || '''W''' [[1962 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]]\n|-\n| [[1964 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1964]] || 10\u20131 || L [[1965 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]]\n|-\n| [[1965 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1965]] || AP || 9\u20131\u20131 || '''W''' [[1966 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]]\n|-\n| [[1973 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1973]] || Coaches' || 11\u20131 || L [[1973 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]]\n|-\n| [[1978 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1978]] || AP || 11\u20131 || '''W''' [[1979 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]]\n|-\n| [[1979 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1979]] || rowspan=\"2\"|AP, Coaches' || 12\u20130 || '''W''' [[1980 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]]\n|-\n| [[1992 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1992]] || [[Gene Stallings]] || 13\u20130 || '''W''' [[1993 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]]\n|-\n| [[2009 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2009]] || rowspan=\"5\" | [[Nick Saban]] || rowspan=\"3\"|AP, Coaches', [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]] || 14\u20130 || '''W''' [[2010 BCS National Championship Game|BCS National Championship Game]]\n|-\n| [[2011 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2011]] || 12\u20131 || '''W''' [[2012 BCS National Championship Game|BCS National Championship Game]]\n|-\n| [[2012 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2012]] || 13\u20131 || '''W''' [[2013 BCS National Championship Game|BCS National Championship Game]]\n|-\n| [[2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2015]] || rowspan=\"2\"|AP, Coaches', [[College Football Playoff|CFP]] || 14\u20131 || '''W''' [[2015 Cotton Bowl Classic (December)|Cotton Bowl Classic]] <br />'''W''' [[2016 College Football Playoff National Championship|College Football Playoff National Championship]]\n|-\n| [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2017]] || 13\u20131 || '''W''' [[2018 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] <br />'''W''' [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship|College Football Playoff National Championship]]\n|}\n* '''1925''' \u2013 The [[1925 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Wallace Wade, completed the regular season 9\u20130\u20130, winning the [[Southern Conference]] championship. Alabama was then invited to play [[Washington Huskies football|Washington]] in the January 1, [[1926 Rose Bowl]]. Coach Wade's team initially fell behind the undefeated Huskies, but rallied in the second half to defeat Washington 20\u201319. The outstanding player of the game was [[Johnny Mack Brown]].<ref name=\"bowl_tradition\">{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/alab/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/history-bowlrecords.pdf |title=Bowl History |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=October 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523062558/http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/alab/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/history-bowlrecords.pdf |archivedate=May 23, 2011}}</ref> This game is viewed by many football historians as the single most important event for Southern football, and is hailed \"the football game that changed the South.\" Alabama was the first Southern football team to be invited to play in the Rose Bowl, and proved Southern teams could compete with those from the East, the Midwest and the West coast. The victory for Coach Wallace Wade established Alabama as a football powerhouse. The 1925 Alabama football team finished the season with a 10\u20130\u20130 record and was selected national champion by the Football Annual, Billingsley, and the [[Helms Athletic Foundation]].<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/fls/8000/files/files/14260.pdf |title=Alabama 2003 Media Guide: National Team Champions |year=2003 |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/699wD2csO?url=http://www.rolltide.com/fls/8000/files/files/14260.pdf |archivedate=July 14, 2012 |accessdate=October 2, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* '''1926''' \u2013 The [[1926 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Wallace Wade, completed the regular season 9\u20130\u20130, winning the Southern Conference championship. Alabama was then invited to play [[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford]] in the January 1, 1927, Rose Bowl. Coach Wade's team tied the Indians 7\u20137 to finish the season 9\u20130\u20131. The outstanding player of the game was Fred Pickhard.<ref name=\"bowl_tradition\" /> The 1926 Alabama football team was selected national champion by Billingsley and the [[Helms Athletic Foundation]].<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" />\n* '''1930''' \u2013 The [[1930 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Wallace Wade, completed the regular season 9\u20130\u20130, winning the Southern Conference championship. Alabama was then invited to play [[Washington State Cougars football|Washington State]] in the January 1, 1931, Rose Bowl. Coach Wade's team defeated the Cougars 24\u20130 to finish the season 10\u20130\u20130. The outstanding player of the game was John Campbell.<ref name=\"bowl_tradition\" /> The 1930 Alabama football team tied with Notre Dame as national champions in the Davis Poll.<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" />\n* '''1934''' \u2013 The [[1934 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by [[Frank Thomas (football coach)|Frank Thomas]], completed the regular season 9\u20130\u20130, winning the [[Southeastern Conference]] championship. Alabama was then invited to play [[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford]] in the January 1, 1935, Rose Bowl. Coach Thomas' team defeated the Indians 29\u201313 to finish the season 10\u20130\u20130. The outstanding player of the game was [[Dixie Howell|Millard \"Dixie\" Howell]].<ref name=\"bowl_tradition\" /> The 1934 Alabama football team was selected national champion by Dunkel, Williamson, and ''Football Thesaurus''.<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" /> The University of Alabama honored Ben McLeod, Jr., the 95-year\u2013old former backup End of the 1934 team at the September 6, 2008 Alabama\u2013Tulane game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20080906/news/809050259 |title=UA to honor its oldest living football player |work=Tuscaloosa News |date=September 5, 2008 |accessdate=October 8, 2008}}</ref>\n* '''1941''' \u2013 The [[1941 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Frank Thomas, completed the regular season 8\u20132\u20130. Alabama's squad finished third in the Southeastern Conference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secsports.com/index.php?s=&url_channel_id=0&url_article_id=202&change_well_id=2 |title=All\u2013Time Football Standings 1940\u20131949 |publisher=SEC Sports |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://timetravel.mementoweb.org/memento/2010/http://www.secsports.com/index.php?s=&url_channel_id=0&url_article_id=202&change_well_id=2 |archivedate=July 2, 2016}}</ref> After losing to [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]] 14-0 and [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]],<ref name=\"bowl_tradition\" /> 7\u20130, Alabama finished the regular season ranked No.{{nbsp}}20 in the [[AP Poll]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collegepollarchive.com/football/ap/seasons.cfm?seasonid=1941|title=1941 Final Football Polls \u2013 College Poll Archive \u2013 Historical College Football and Basketball Polls and Rankings|website=collegepollarchive.com}}</ref> which was finalized with two games left in the regular season.<ref name=SI_vault /> The onset of World War II changed the college football postseason.<ref name=\"January 4, 1942\" /> Alabama was one of ten teams chosen for post-season competition when they were invited to play [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]] in the January 1, 1942, [[Cotton Bowl Classic]]. Coach Thomas' team defeated the Aggies 29\u201321 to finish the season 9\u20132\u20130. Minnesota, the AP national champion, finished 8\u20130 and did not play in a bowl game per Big{{nbsp}}Ten rules. Alabama's outstanding players of the game were [[Holt Rast]], [[Don Whitmire]], and Jimmy Nelson.<ref name=\"bowl_tradition\" /> The squad was selected national champions by the Houlgate Poll, published in the nationally syndicated ''Football Thesaurus''.<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" /> The 2009 NCAA Record Book cites the [[Minnesota Golden Gophers football|Minnesota Golden Gophers]], the [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas Longhorns]], and the Alabama Crimson Tide as the three teams selected as national champions in 1941.<ref name=\"NCAA_Past-champs\" /> [[The Tuscaloosa News]] described the 1941 Alabama Crimson Tide as the university's best team since the 1934 [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]] Championship Team.<ref name=\"January 4, 1942\">{{cite news |title=Tiders to Return Home with Bowl Bacon Today |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=XUmZziu-z7kC&dat=19420104&printsec=frontpage |last=Staff Reporters |newspaper=The Tuscaloosa News |page=10 |date=January 4, 1942 |accessdate=July 27, 2011}}</ref> The September 11, 1967, issue of ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' lists Alabama's 1941 squad as national champion based on Alabama's strength of schedule relative to Minnesota's and because of the early final AP Poll.<ref name=SI_vault>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/vault/issue/43168/1/1?cover_view=1 |title= Sports Illustrated |date=September 11, 1967 |accessdate=December 17, 2015}}</ref>\n* '''1961''' \u2013 The [[1961 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Bear Bryant, completed the regular season 10\u20130\u20130, winning the Southeastern Conference championship. Led by quarterback [[Pat Trammell]], linebacker [[Lee Roy Jordan]] and two\u2013way lineman [[Billy Neighbors]], Alabama outscored their opponents 297\u201325. Alabama was then invited to play the #9\u2013ranked [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas Razorbacks]] in the January 1, [[1962 Sugar Bowl]]. Coach Bryant's team defeated the Razorbacks 10\u20133 to finish the season 11\u20130\u20130. The outstanding player of the game was Mike Fracchia.<ref name=\"bowl_tradition\" /> The 1961 Alabama football team was selected national champion by the [[AP Poll]] and [[Coaches' Poll]].<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" />\n* '''1964''' \u2013 The [[1964 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Bear Bryant, completed the regular season 10\u20130\u20130, winning the Southeastern Conference championship. Alabama was led by quarterback [[Joe Namath]]. Alabama was then invited to play the [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas Longhorns]] in the January 1, 1965, [[Orange Bowl (game)|Orange Bowl]]. Coach Bryant's team lost to the Longhorns 21\u201317 to finish the season 10\u20131\u20130. The outstanding player of the game was [[Joe Namath]].<ref name=\"bowl_tradition\" /> The 1964 Alabama football team was selected national champion by the AP Poll and the Coaches' Poll prior to bowl games.<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" /> The AP Poll waited until after the bowl games to select their champion for the 1965 season.\n* '''1965''' \u2013 The [[1965 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Bear Bryant, completed the regular season 8\u20131\u20131, winning the Southeastern Conference championship. The Tide lost to [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] and tied [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] during the regular season. Alabama was then invited to play [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]] in the January 1, [[1966 Orange Bowl]]. Coach Bryant's team defeated the Cornhuskers 39\u201328 to finish the season 9\u20131\u20131. The outstanding player of the game was [[Steve Sloan]].<ref name=\"bowl_tradition\" /> The 1965 Alabama football team was selected national champion by the AP Poll.<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" />\n* '''1973''' \u2013 The [[1973 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Bear Bryant, completed the regular season 11\u20130\u20130, winning the Southeastern Conference championship. Alabama was then invited to play Notre Dame in the December 31, 1973, Sugar Bowl. Coach Bryant's team lost to the Fighting Irish 24\u201323 to finish the season 11\u20131\u20130. The 1973 Alabama football team was selected national champion in the final regular season Coaches' Poll, which was finalized prior to the post-season bowl games.<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" /> The Coaches' Poll began selecting their champion after the bowl games starting in 1974. The post-bowl game AP Poll ranked Alabama 4th, and selected Notre Dame as its national champion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.appollarchive.com/football/ap/seasons.cfm?seasonid=1973|title=1973 Final AP Football Poll \u2013 AP Poll Archive \u2013 Historical College Football and Basketball Polls and Rankings|date=December 2, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202185221/http://www.appollarchive.com/football/ap/seasons.cfm?seasonid=1973|archivedate=December 2, 2009}}</ref>\n* '''1978''' \u2013 The [[1978 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Bear Bryant, completed the regular season 10\u20131\u20130, winning the Southeastern Conference championship. The Tide defeated #10\u2013ranked Nebraska 20\u20133, and defeated #11\u2013ranked [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]] 38\u201320, and lost to #7-ranked [[USC Trojans football|Southern California]] 24\u201314, during the regular season.<ref name=\"2010 USC Football Media Guide\">{{cite web |url=http://www.usctrojans.com/blog/2010/07/2010-usc-football-media-guide.html |title=2010 USC Football Media Guide |publisher=University of Southern California Sports Department |accessdate=November 22, 2013}}</ref> The #2-ranked Alabama Crimson Tide was then invited to play the #1\u2013ranked [[Penn State Nittany Lions football|Penn State]] in the January 1, [[1979 Sugar Bowl]]. Coach Bryant's team defeated the Nittany Lions 14\u20137 to finish the season 11\u20131\u20130. The outstanding player of the game was linebacker [[Barry Krauss]].<ref name=\"bowl_tradition\" /> Alabama was selected national champion by the AP Poll,<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" /> and Southern California was selected national champion by the Coaches' Poll.<ref name=\"2010 USC Football Media Guide\" />\n* '''1979''' \u2013 The [[1979 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Bear Bryant, completed the regular season 11\u20130\u20130, winning the Southeastern Conference championship. The Tide defeated #18\u2013ranked Tennessee 27\u201317, and defeated #14\u2013ranked Auburn 25\u201318 during the regular season. Alabama was then invited to play #6\u2013ranked Arkansas in the January 1, [[1980 Sugar Bowl]]. Coach Bryant's team defeated the Razorbacks 24\u20139 to finish the season 12\u20130\u20130. The outstanding player of the game was running back Major Ogilvie.<ref name=\"bowl_tradition\" /> The 1979 Alabama football team was selected national champion by the AP Poll and the Coaches' Poll.<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" />\n* '''1992''' \u2013 The [[1992 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Gene Stallings, completed the regular season 11\u20130\u20130. They then defeated #12\u2013ranked [[1992 Florida Gators football team|Florida]] in the [[1992 SEC Championship Game|inaugural SEC Championship Game]], defeating the Gators 28\u201321; the win gave Alabama its 20th SEC title and a record of 12\u20130\u20130. Alabama was then invited to play #1\u2013ranked [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]], led by Heisman trophy winner Gino Torretta, in the January 1, [[1993 Sugar Bowl]]. Coach Stallings' team defeated the Hurricanes 34\u201313 to finish the season 13\u20130\u20130. The outstanding player of the game was [[Derrick Lassic]].<ref name=\"bowl_tradition\" /> The 1992 Alabama football team was awarded the national championship by the AP Poll and the Coaches' Poll.<ref name=\"2003_media_guide\" />\n\n[[File:President Obama and the BCS National Champion Alabama Crimson Tide.jpg|thumb|The Crimson Tide meeting with President [[Barack Obama]] after winning the 2009 national championship |alt=President Obama receives an Alabama jersey at the White House with various team members and coaches present.]]\n* '''2009''' \u2013 The [[2009 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by [[Nick Saban]], finished with a 12\u20130 regular season. In the twelve wins, the Crimson Tide defeated four teams that were ranked at the time, including an opening day victory over No.{{nbsp}}7 [[2009 Virginia Tech Hokies football team|Virginia Tech]] in the [[Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game]]. The team headed back to the [[Georgia Dome]] in December to face off against [[2009 Florida Gators football team|#1 Florida]] in the [[2009 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship Game]]. The Crimson Tide defeated the Gators 32\u201313 in a rematch of the [[2008 SEC Championship Game|previous year's championship]].<ref name=\"2009-SEC-USAT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/college/football/sec/2009-12-05-alabama-florida_N.htm |title=Alabama rolls to 32\u201313 defeat of No.{{nbsp}}1 Florida in SEC title game |work=USA Today |author=Jones, David |date=December 8, 2009 |accessdate=January 17, 2010}}</ref> Alabama then traveled to [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]] to face #2-ranked [[2009 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]] in the [[2010 BCS National Championship Game]] at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]]. Alabama's Heisman Trophy-winning running back, [[Mark Ingram Jr.|Mark Ingram]], rushed for 116{{nbsp}}yards and two touchdowns in a 37\u201321 win.<ref name=\"2010-NC-USAT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/college/football/2010-01-07-bcs-title-game_N.htm |title=Alabama sidesteps Texas' charge to emerge with BCS title |work=USA Today |author=Whiteside, Kelly |date=January 7, 2010 |accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref> This was Alabama's first victory over Texas (1\u20137\u20131). Ingram was named the game's offensive MVP in Alabama's first [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]] victory. The 2009 Alabama football team was selected national champion by the AP and Coaches' Polls. The 2009 squad became the first FBS division team to defeat six teams ranked in the AP top 25 during one season and received a record six first team AP All-America selections. The 2009 team finished with a perfect 14\u20130 record, an all-time highest number of wins in a season for Alabama.\n* '''2011''' \u2013 The [[2011 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Nick Saban, completed the regular season 11\u20131. The only loss of the season was to [[2011 LSU vs. Alabama football game|LSU in overtime 9\u20136]].<ref name=\"2011LSUESPN\">{{cite news |title=LSU kicks winning field goal in OT for defensive-minded win over Alabama |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=313090333 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ESPN.com |date=November 5, 2011 |accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> The team did not play in the SEC Championship Game because of that loss, but won convincingly in its final three regular-season games and earned a No.{{nbsp}}2 ranking in the BCS poll.<ref name=\"2011LSURematch\">{{cite news |title=LSU, Alabama to play for title |agency=ESPN.com news services |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/7316817/lsu-tigers-alabama-crimson-tide-rematch-set-bcs-title-game |publisher=ESPN.com |date=December 4, 2011 |accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> For their final regular season game, Alabama defeated rival [[2011 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] 42-14.<ref name=\"2011AUESPN\">{{cite news |title=Alabama stomps Auburn behind Trent Richardson's 203{{nbsp}}yards |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=313300002 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ESPN.com |date=November 26, 2011 |accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> Alabama, led by Heisman trophy finalist [[Trent Richardson]], then qualified to play No.{{nbsp}}1 ranked LSU in the [[2012 BCS National Championship Game]].<ref name=\"2011LSURematch\" /> Coach Saban's team defeated the Tigers 21\u20130 and finished the season 12\u20131.<ref name=\"2011BCSESPN\">{{cite news |title=Alabama's D embarrasses LSU as five FGs, late TD seal national title |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=320090099 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ESPN.com |date=January 9, 2012 |accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> [[Jeremy Shelley]] had a bowl record-tying five field goals in the game, and the game's offensive MVP was [[AJ McCarron]], and the defensive MVP was [[Courtney Upshaw]].<ref name=\"2011BCSESPN\" /> With the win, Alabama became the first team to shutout its opponent in a BCS bowl game.<ref name=\"2011BCSESPN\" /> In addition to winning the BCS National Championship, the AP also awarded its national title to Alabama for the 8th time.<ref name=\"2011FinalPollESPN\">{{cite news |title=2011 NCAA Football Rankings \u2013 Postseason |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/rankings/_/year/2011/week/final |publisher=ESPN.com |accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref>\n* '''2012''' \u2013 The [[2012 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Nick Saban, completed the regular season 11\u20131. The only loss of the season was against [[2012 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]] 29\u201324.<ref name=\"2012TXESPN\">{{cite news |title=Johnny Manziel, Texas A&M pull upset as No.{{nbsp}}1 Alabama's rally falls short |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=323150333 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ESPN.com |date=November 10, 2012 |accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> Despite the loss, Alabama won the SEC Western division and went to the [[2012 SEC Championship Game]], where they defeated [[2012 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]] 32\u201328 for the 23rd conference championship in school history.<ref name=\"2012GAESPN\">{{cite news |title=Alabama holds off Georgia, reaches BCS Championship Game |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=323360061 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ESPN.com |date=December 1, 2012 |accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> Alabama earned a No.{{nbsp}}2 ranking in the final BCS rankings for the second straight year and as a result qualified for the [[2013 BCS National Championship Game]] against No.{{nbsp}}1 [[2012 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]].<ref name=\"2012BCSAnnounced\">{{cite news |title=Irish-Bama 1\u20132; N. Illinois busts BCS |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/8702724/bcs-bowl-schedule-northern-illinois-huskies-earn-orange-bowl-bid |agency=ESPN.com news services |publisher=ESPN.com |date=December 2, 2012 |accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> Alabama defeated the Fighting Irish 42\u201314, finished the season 13\u20131, and the game's offensive MVP was [[Eddie Lacy]], and the defensive MVP was [[C. J. Mosley (linebacker)|C.J. Mosley]].<ref name=\"2012NDESPN\">{{cite news |title=Alabama routs Notre Dame, wins 3rd BCS title in past 4 years |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=330070333 |agency=ESPN.com news services |publisher=ESPN.com |date=January 7, 2013 |accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> Alabama became the third team in history to win three national championships in a four-year period. This was Alabama's 9th AP national championship and 10th wire-service championship.<ref name=\"2012NDESPN\" />\n* '''2015''' \u2013 The [[2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Nick Saban, finished the regular season 11\u20131. Their only loss was to [[2015 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]] 43\u201337. They won the SEC Western Division title with a record of 7\u20131, defeating rivals LSU and Tennessee en route, and then defeated [[2015 Florida Gators football team|Florida]] 29\u201315 in the [[2015 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship]]. Alabama returned to the playoffs for the second consecutive season. After falling short in the semifinals against Ohio State in 2014, Alabama defeated the [[2015 Michigan State Spartans football team|Michigan State Spartans]] 38\u20130 in the [[2015 Cotton Bowl Classic (December)|Cotton Bowl]] to advance to the [[2016 College Football Playoff National Championship|Championship Game]]. Alabama beat the [[2015 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson Tigers]] 45\u201340 and won the 2015 FBS national championship. Alabama's Heisman Trophy-winning running back Derrick Henry rushed for 158{{nbsp}}yards and three touchdowns. This victory gave Coach Nick Saban his fifth national title, including four in the last seven seasons.\n* '''2017''' - The [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]], coached by Nick Saban, finished the regular season 11\u20131. Their only loss was at [[2017 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] 26\u201314. They won a share of the SEC Western Division title with a record of 7\u20131. Alabama returned to the playoffs for the fourth consecutive season. Alabama avenged the previous season's only loss in the National Championship game to [[2017 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]] with a 24\u20136 win in the [[2018 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]]. The Tide advanced to the [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship|Championship game]] for the third year in a row. Alabama defeated SEC opponent [[2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]] 26\u201323 in overtime. The victory gave Nick Saban his sixth national title, tying him with [[Bear Bryant|Paul W. Bryant]] for most all time. It's also Alabama's fifth title in the last nine seasons. Alabama jokingly declared February 26 as 2nd and 26 day to celebrated the touchdown [[Tua Tagovailoa|Tua]] threw on 2nd down and 26 to win the national title in overtime.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2018/2/26/17053880/alabama-declares-february-26th-holiday-title-game-2-26-touchdown-pass|title=In honor of title game TD, Bama declares February 26 a holiday|last=Moriarty|first=Morgan|date=2018-02-26|website=SBNation.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n===Conference championships===\nAlabama has won a total of 31 conference championships; this includes four Southern Conference and 27 SEC Championships. Alabama captured its four Southern Conference titles in 1924, 1925, 1926, and 1930. Alabama captured the first SEC title in 1933 and has won a total of 27 SEC Championships (1933, 1934, 1937, 1945, 1953, 1961, 1964, 1965, 1966, 1971, 1972, 1973, 1974, 1975, 1977, 1978, 1979, 1981, 1989, 1992, 1999, 2009, 2012, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2018). The school has won more SEC football titles than any other school, including eight since the conference split into separate divisions and added the [[SEC Championship Game|Championship Game]] in 1992. Alabama is the only school to win an SEC Championship in every decade since the conference was founded in 1933.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Alabama Crimson Tide|Season|Conference|Coach|Overall record|Conference record}}\n|-\n| [[1924 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1924]] || rowspan=\"4\"|[[Southern Conference|Southern]] || rowspan=\"4\"|[[Wallace Wade]] || 8\u20131 || 5\u20130\n|-\n| [[1925 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1925]]\u2020 || 10\u20130 || 7\u20130\n|-\n| [[1926 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1926]] || 9\u20130\u20131 || 8\u20130\n|-\n| [[1930 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1930]]\u2020 || 10\u20130 || 8\u20130\n|-\n| [[1933 Alabama Crimson Tide f