ins]]\n* [[Dont'a Hightower]], LB \u2013 [[New England Patriots]]\n* [[OJ Howard]], TE \u2013 [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]\n* [[Marlon Humphrey]], CB- [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n* [[Mark Ingram Jr.|Mark Ingram]], RB- [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n* [[Eddie Jackson (safety)|Eddie Jackson]], S \u2013 [[Chicago Bears]]\n* [[Kareem Jackson]], CB \u2013 [[Denver Broncos]]\n* [[Josh Jacobs]], RB - [[Las Vegas Raiders]]\n* [[Anfernee Jennings]], LB - [[New England Patriots]]\n* [[Jerry Jeudy]], WR - [[Denver Broncos]]\n* [[Julio Jones]], WR \u2013 [[Atlanta Falcons]]\n* [[Ryan Kelly (American football)|Ryan Kelly]], C \u2013 [[Indianapolis Colts]]\n* [[Terrell Lewis (American football)|Terrell Lewis]], LB - [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n* Cole Mazza, LS- [[Los Angeles Chargers]]\n* Jared Mayden, S - [[San Francisco 49ers]]\n* [[AJ McCarron]], QB - [[Houston Texans]]\n* [[Xavier McKinney]], S - [[New York Giants]]\n* [[Christian Miller (American football)|Christian Miller]], LB - [[Carolina Panthers]]\n* [[CJ Mosley (linebacker)|CJ Mosley]], LB \u2013 [[New York Jets]]\n* [[Daron Payne]], NT \u2013 [[Washington Redskins]]\n* [[Ross Pierschbacher]], C - [[Washington Redskins]]\n* [[Reggie Ragland]], LB \u2013 [[Detroit Lions]]\n* [[Jarran Reed]], DT \u2013 [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n* [[Calvin Ridley]], WR \u2013 [[Atlanta Falcons]]\n* [[A'Shawn Robinson]], DT \u2013 [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n* [[Cam Robinson]], OT \u2013 [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]\n* [[Henry Ruggs III]], WR - [[Las Vegas Raiders]]\n* [[Bo Scarbrough]], RB - [[Detroit Lions]]\n* [[JK Scott]], P- [[Green Bay Packers]]\n* [[Cam Sims]], WR - [[Washington Redskins]]\n* [[Andre Smith (offensive tackle)|Andre Smith]], OT - [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n* [[Irv Smith Jr.]], TE - [[Minnesota Vikings]]\n* Saivion Smith, CB - [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n* [[Damion Square]], DT - [[Los Angeles Chargers]]\n* [[Tua Tagovailoa]], QB - [[Miami Dolphins]]\n* [[Deionte Thompson]], S - [[Arizona Cardinals]]\n* [[Dalvin Tomlinson]], DT \u2013 [[New York Giants]]\n* [[Levi Wallace (American football)|Levi Wallace]], CB- [[Buffalo Bills]]\n* [[Chance Warmack]], OL - [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n* [[DeAndrew White]], WR - [[Carolina Panthers]]\n* [[Jonah Williams]], OT - [[Cincinnati Bengals]]\n* [[Quinnen Williams]], DL - [[New York Jets]]\n* [[Tim Williams (American football)|Tim Williams]], LB \u2013 [[Green Bay Packers]]\n* [[Jedrick Wills]], OT - [[Cleveland Browns]]\n* [[Mack Wilson]], LB - [[Cleveland Browns]]\n* [[TJ Yeldon]], RB- [[Buffalo Bills]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Media==\nDuring the football season, the [[Crimson Tide Sports Network]] (CTSN) broadcasts multiple shows on gameday for most sports. The network includes more than 60 radio stations across the country. Radio stations [[WFFN]]-FM, [[WTSK]]-AM as a backup, broadcast all home games in the Tuscaloosa area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/radio-tv.html |title=Radio/TV Information |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=October 8, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080930090614/http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/radio-tv.html| archivedate= September 30, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nFootball radio broadcasts begin three hours prior to the game's designated kickoff time with Chris Stewart and Tyler Watts in ''Around the SEC''.<ref name=\"Game-broadcasts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/footbl-gameday.html |title=CTSN Game Broadcasts |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=October 8, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080914062559/http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/footbl-gameday.html| archivedate= September 14, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> The radio broadcast then moves to the ''Crimson Tide Tailgate Party'' hosted by Tom Roberts.<ref name=\"Game-broadcasts\" /> Immediately following the end of the game, the ''Fifth Quarter Show'' begins as host Eli Gold talks to coaches and players and gives game statistics.<ref name=\"Game-broadcasts\" /> For the 2008 season, former Alabama players and personalities were brought on to provide guest commentary for each broadcast.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/genrel/081208aac.html |title=CTSN Ready for 2008 Football Season |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=October 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Eli Gold.jpg|thumb|[[Eli Gold]] has done play-by-play work for Alabama football since 1988.]]\n'''Current radio staff''':<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/crew.html |title=The Crew |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=October 17, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081003074905/http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/crew.html| archivedate= October 3, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/radio-tv.html |title=Crimson Tide Radio and Television Information, Football |publisher=University of Alabama Athletics |accessdate=October 15, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080408073937/http://www.rolltide.com/multimedia/radio-tv.html |archivedate=April 8, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Eli Gold]] \u2013 play-by-play\n* [[John Parker Wilson]] \u2013 color analyst\n* [[Rashad Johnson]] \u2013 sideline reporter\n* Chris Stewart, Tyler Watts \u2013 pre- and post-game show co-host\n* Tom Roberts \u2013 director of broadcasting\n* Tom Stipe, Butch Owens, Brian Roberts \u2013 producers\n\nStewart and Watts also provide play-by-play and color commentary respectively for CTSN pay-per-view television broadcasts.\n\n'''Former radio staff''':\n* [[Bert Bank]], founder of the Alabama Football Network, producer emeritus\n* John Forney, play-by-play\n* Jerry Duncan, sideline reporter\n* Paul Kennedy, play-by-play\n* Doug Layton, color analyst\n* [[Ken Stabler]], color analyst<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myespn.go.com/blogs/hashmarks/0-8-150/Ex-Raiders-star-Stabler-leaves-radio-gig.html |title=Ex-Raiders star Stabler leaves radio gig |publisher=ESPN |last=Williamson |first=Bill |date=July 11, 2008 |accessdate=October 8, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009061830/http://myespn.go.com/blogs/hashmarks/0-8-150/Ex-Raiders-star-Stabler-leaves-radio-gig.html |archivedate=October 9, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabama/huntsvilletimes/index.ssf?/base/sports/1215854130308570.xml&coll=1 |title=Stabler leaves UA radio job |work=The Huntsville Times |date=July 12, 2008 |accessdate=October 8, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609071808/http://www.al.com/alabama/huntsvilletimes/index.ssf?%2Fbase%2Fsports%2F1215854130308570.xml&coll=1 |archivedate=June 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Future opponents==\n\n===Non-division conference opponents===\nAlabama plays Tennessee as a permanent non-division opponent annually and rotates around the ''East'' division among the other six schools.<ref name=\"nondivopp\">{{cite web| title=SEC Future Football Schedule Rotation Announced|publisher=fbschedules.com| url=http://www.fbschedules.com/2014/05/sec-future-football-schedule-rotation-2025/|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#9E1B32; color:white; text-align:center;\"\n| '''2021''' || <span style=\"color:white;\">'''2022'''</span> || '''2023 ''' || '''2024''' || '''2025'''\n|- align=center\n| vs Tennessee || at Tennessee || vs Tennessee || at Tennessee || vs Tennessee\n|- align=center\n| at Florida || vs Vanderbilt || at Kentucky || vs South Carolina || at Missouri\n|}\n\n===Non-conference opponents===\nAnnounced schedules as of April 26, 2020.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Alabama Crimson Tide|2021|2022|2023|2024|2025|2026|2027|2028|2029|2030|2031|2032|2033|2034|2035}}\n|-\n| vs. [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]]\n| [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]]\n| [[Central Michigan Chippewas football|Central Michigan]]\n| [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky]]\n| at [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]]\n| at [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]]\n| West Virginia\n| at [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame]]\n| Notre Dame\n| at [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech]]\n| Georgia Tech\n| at [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]]\n| Oklahoma\n| at [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]]\n| Virginia Tech\n|- \n| [[Southern Miss Golden Eagles football|Southern Miss]]\n| at [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]]\n| Texas\n| [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]]\n| Louisiana\u2212Monroe\n| South Florida\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|- \n| [[New Mexico State Aggies football|New Mexico State]]\n| [[Louisiana-Monroe Warhawks football|Louisiana\u2212Monroe]]\n| at South Florida\n| at [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]]\n| Wisconsin\n| Florida State\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|- \n| [[Mercer Bears football|Mercer]]\n| [[Austin Peay Governors football|Austin Peay]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|}\n:'''Source:'''<ref name=\"nonconfopp\">{{cite web|url=https://fbschedules.com/ncaa/alabama/|title=Alabama Crimson Tide Football Future Schedules|publisher=FBSchedules.com|accessdate=April 26, 2020}}</ref>\n* The 2020 game against USC will be part of the [[Advocare Classic]] held at [[AT&T Stadium]] in [[Arlington, Texas]].<ref name=\"USC2020\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/23585956/alabama-crimson-tide-usc-trojans-kick-2020-season-arlington-texas|title=Alabama-USC to kick off 2020 season in Texas|work=ESPN.com|access-date=June 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* The 2021 game against Miami will be part of the [[Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game]] held at [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]].<ref name=\"MIA2021\">{{cite news |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/college/acc/university-of-miami/article171325272.html|title=Miami Hurricanes to renew football rivalry with Nick Saban and Alabama|first=George |last=Richards |newspaper=[[Miami Herald]] |date=September 5, 2017 |access-date=June 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alabama Crimson Tide home football stadiums]]\n* [[University of Alabama traditions]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-la|refs=\n{{efn-la|name=\"notea\"|In 1995, the NCAA forfeited Alabama eight regular season victories and one tie from the 1993 season.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alabama Put on Probation College football: NCAA sanctions program for three years. The team is banned from postseason play next season. |work=Los Angeles Times |date=August 3, 1995 <!--|accessdate=October 7, 2008-->}}</ref>}}\n{{efn-la|name=\"noteb\"|In 2009, the NCAA vaca}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=Southern Fried Football: The History, Passion, and Glory of the Great Southern Game |url=https://archive.org/details/southernfriedfoo0000barn |url-access=registration |last=Barnhart |first=Tony |author2=[[Keith Jackson]] |publisher=Triumph Books |year=2000 |isbn=1-60078-093-8}}\n* {{cite book |title=Roll Tide: The Alabama Crimson Tide Story |last=Davis |first=Terry |publisher=Creative Education |year=1999 |isbn=0-88682-975-5}}\n* {{cite book |title=Talk of the Tide: an oral history of Alabama football since 1920 |last=Forney |first=John |publisher=Crane Hill Publishers |year=1993 |isbn=1-881548-03-1}}\n* {{cite book |title=Crimson Nation |last=Gold |first=Eli |authorlink=Eli Gold |publisher=Thomas Nelson Incorporated |year=2005 |isbn=1-4016-0190-1 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/crimsonnation0000gold }}\n* {{cite book |title=The Crimson Tide \u2013 An Illustrated History |last=Groom |first=Winston |authorlink=Winston Groom |publisher=The University of Alabama Press |year=2000 |isbn=0-8173-1051-7}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Crimson Tide: Alabama Football |last=Langford |first=George |publisher=H. Regnery Co |year=1974 |isbn=0-8092-8363-8}}\n* {{cite book |title=Crimson Tide Madness: Great Eras in Alabama Football |last=Sharpe |first=Wilton |publisher=Cumberland House Publishing |year=2007 |isbn=1-58182-580-3}}\n* {{cite book |title=Tales from 1978\u201379 Alabama Football: A Time of Champions |last=Townsend |first=Steve |publisher=Sports Publishing LLC |year=2003 |isbn=1-58261-425-3}}\n* {{cite book |title=Crimson Storm Surge: Alabama Football Then and Now |last=Walsh |first=Christopher J. |publisher=Taylor Trade Publishing |year=2005 |isbn=1-58979-279-3}}\n* {{cite book |title=Football Powers of the South |last=Wells |first=Lawrence |publisher=Sports Yearbook Company |year=2000 |isbn=0-916242-27-7}}\n* {{cite book |title=Alabama Football: The Greatest Games, Players, Coaches, and Teams in the Glorious Tradition of Crimson Tide Football |author=Athlon Sports |author2=[[Mike Shula]] |publisher=Triumph Books |year=2006 |isbn=1-57243-880-0}}\n* {{cite book |title=Greatest Moments in Alabama Crimson Tide Football History |author=''[[The Tuscaloosa News]]'' |author2=Mike Bynum, Associated Press |publisher=Distributors |year=2003 |isbn=1-928846-65-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alabama Crimson Tide football}}\n* {{Official website}}\n<!-- List only OFFICIAL websites \u2013 others will be removed. See talk page discussion. -->\n\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{University of Alabama}}\n{{Southeastern Conference football navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football|*]]\n[[Category:American football teams established in 1892]]\n[[Category:1892 establishments in Alabama|Crimson Tide]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCollege Football Hall of Fame inductees", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alabama_Crimson_Tide_football"}
{"title_page": "Beekeeping in Ireland", "text_new": "{{Use Irish English|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n[[File: St. Gobnait stained glass window design.tif|thumb|right|[[Harry Clarke]]'s design drawing for the [[Saint Gobnait]] window in [[Honan Chapel]], Cork, Ireland (1914). Saint Gobnait of Ballyvourney is a sixth-century patron saint of beekeepers.]]\n\n'''Beekeeping in [[Ireland]]''' has been practiced for at least 2000 years and has seen a surge in popularity in modern times, evidenced by the numerous organizations promoting and assisting beekeeping. Despite the increased pressures on bees and beekeepers through new diseases and loss of habitat, there are now in excess of 3,500 members within beekeeping associations.\n\n==History==\n===From early to modern beekeeping===\nHoney bees were brought to Ireland, most likely from Britain, sometime after the end of the last ice age.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Edwards, R.J., Brooks, A. |title=) The Island of Ireland: Drowning the Myth of an Irish Land-bridge? I |journal=The Irish Naturalists' Journal (Special Supplement) |date=2008 |pages=19\u201334 |url=http://www.tara.tcd.ie/bitstream/handle/2262/40560/Edwards&Brooks_INJ08_TARA.pdf;jsessionid=37D3E595A904F39A39A571C1E59DAADC?sequence=1 |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref> [[Solinus]] in the 3rd century A.D. makes mention of Ireland as having \"few bees\". The earliest reference from within Ireland about bees are in the Bee Judgements of the [[Brehon Laws]] which among other issues dealt with the ownership and value of swarms, the compensation paid by the beekeeper to a person stung by one of his bees and the compensation paid to the beekeeper if a person's hens began eating his bees. The Brehon Laws began to be codified about 438-441 A.D. having been handed down orally from previous generations, they contain no [[Latin]] loan words relating to bees or beekeeping, which provides further evidence that beekeeping vocabulary was established before the arrival of Christianity in about 430 A.D. However legend has it that St. [[Modomnoc]] first brought bees to Ireland from [[Wales]] in the early 540's A.D. just after the effects of the [[extreme weather events of 535\u2013536]] A.D. would have been subsiding. A \"great mortality of bees\" was recorded in 950 A.D., and again in 992 A.D. when it was said that \"Bees were largely kept in Ireland at this time, and were a great source of wealth to the people\". In 1443 A.D \"the third [[epizooty]] of bees\" was recorded.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Flemming |first1=George |title=Animal plagues: Their history, nature and prevention |date=1871 |publisher=Chapman and Hall |location=London |pages=[https://archive.org/details/animalplaguesthe00flem/page/53 53], 58, & 118 |url=https://archive.org/details/animalplaguesthe00flem |accessdate=6 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first beekeeping book in Ireland was ''Instructions for managing bees'' in 1733, it included recommendations for the use of [[skep]]s and stipulated the best size to use to encourage at least one [[swarming (honey bee)|swarm]] per year with two afterswarms to follow. The bees would traditionally have been killed at the end of each season, often with the use of brimstone matches, to be able to extract the honey and wax. However, by the mid-1700s boxes for keeping bees had begun to be used and methods of extracting the honey and wax, without killing the bees, were being devised.\nIn the 1870s Brother Joeseph, a Carmelite monk from [[Loughrea]], imported a Bar and Frame Hive<ref>{{cite book |last1=W. Augustus Munn |title=A Description of the Bar and Frame Hive |date=1844 |publisher=S. & J. Bentley, Wilson, and Fley |pages=2\u201321 |url=https://www.scribd.com/document/28931799/Bar-and-Frame-Hive |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> from Mr. Abbott of London and then began to produce his own versions, he is also recorded as being one of the first to import the ''Ligurian'' Italian honey bee (''[[apis mellifera ligustica|A. m. ligustica]]'') with a view to selective breeding \"..as being more prolific.. and harder workers.. would improve our home breed (the Irish strain of ''[[apis mellifera mellifera|A. m. mellifera]]'')\". In 1881 the Reverend George Proctor was believed to be the first in the country to own [[langstroth hive|Langstroth Hives]] (invented in 1852) with their moveable frames, which subsequent modern hives are based upon.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Crane|first=Eva|date=1998|title=Irish Beekeeping in the past|url=https://www.evacranetrust.org/uploads/document/d2797417eaa6d577c75c7f0b4142668276cc178e.pdf|journal=Ulster Folklife|volume=44|pages=45\u201351|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=1\u20135, 6\u201311, 271\u2013275}}</ref>\n\nIn 1912 the ''[[Isle of Wight Disease]]'' (IoWD) arrived in Ireland, wiping out the [[Indigenous (ecology)|indigenous]] native Irish Black Bee (''A. m. mellifera''), Ireland was restocked with ''A. m. mellifera'' imports mainly originating from Hollund, but also from France.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=146\u2013148}}</ref>\n\n===Formation of the Associations===\nIn 1880 the British Beekeepers Association (BBKA) decided to tour Ireland with a \"bee tent\" to show modern beekeeping equipment and manipulations of bees to the public. They were joined by Brother Joseph, throughout much of Ireland as he continued on his \"holy crusade\" for the honey bee; he later proposed the formation of an Irish beekeeping association \"for promoting and instructing the improved methods of bee culture to the cottagers of Ireland\". In 1881 the Irish Beekeepers Associations (IBKA) was formed, holding a honey show in Dublin; in 1908 their name was changed to Irish Beekeepers' Association (IBA), in 1939 it was wound up due to decreasing membership.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=vi, 30\u201343, 72\u201374, 271\u2013276}}</ref>\n\nIn 1943 the County Dublin Beekeepers' Association was formed, from which an attempt was made to revive the old IBA to form an ''all'' Ireland body. On St. Patrick's Day in 1944 the Federation of Irish Beekeepers' Associations was formed; the recently formed Ulster Bee Keepers' Association (UBKA) did not associate themselves with it.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=171\u2013172}}</ref>\n\nIn 1926 the Banbridge and District Beekeeping Association was formed; in 1934 its name became the Northern Ireland Bee Keepers' Association. In 1942 the UBKA was formed and in 1951 the smaller NIBKA affiliated with it and was later absorbed into it. In 1949 there were 6,000 beekeepers with 16,000 hives, the most common of which was the CDB Hive. At the 14th Annual Conference in 1959 a lecture was given entitled \"How to take advantage of the ''[[buckfast bee|Buckfast]]'' strain of bees, to be shortly introduced into Northern Ireland\". At the 15th Annual Conference in 1960 a member of the Ministry of Agriculture gave the lecture \"The Buckfast Strain of Honeybee and its dissemination throughout Northern Ireland\". In 1966 at the 21st Annual Conference of the UBKA it was decided that all subsequent Conferences should be held at Greenmount Agricultural and Horticultural College; it was also at this conference that the Ministry of Agriculture informed the UBKA \"that due to the increase of Nosema, the ''Buckfast'' Queen distribution scheme was being suspended\", a scheme initially begun to improve the local bee stock (the ''A. m. mellifera'' imported after the IoWD).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=135}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966 the FIBKA raised the subject of forming an All-Ireland Beekeepers' Alliance but the UBKA unanimously rejected the suggestion, opting instead to support continued co-operation.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=121\u2013123, 126\u2013129, 130}}</ref>\n\n==Honeybee diseases, pests and poisons==\n\n===Varroa===\nPresently the ''[[Varroa destructor]]'' mite is the single greatest threat to bee colonies in Ireland. If left untreated colonies will die within three to four years, although typically after the initial infestation there can be a rapid increase in the mite population which would lead to colony collapse.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=B\u00fcChler |first1=Ralph |title=Varroa Tolerance in Honey Bees\u2014Occurrence, Characters and Breeding |journal=Bee World |date=1994 |volume=75 |issue=2 |pages= 54\u201370 |doi=10.1080/0005772X.1994.11099201 }}</ref> Varroa mites arrived in Ireland in 1998 and in several years had spread throughout most of the island.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McMullan |first1=John |title=Adaptation in Honey Bee (Apis mellifera) Colonies Exhibiting Tolerance to Varroa destructor in Ireland |journal=Bee World |date=2018 |volume=95 |issue=2 |pages=39\u201343 |doi=10.1080/0005772X.2018.1431000 |doi-access=free }}</ref> The mortality rate for over-wintered colonies during 2015/16 in the Republic of Ireland was 29.5% and for Northern Ireland was 28.2%; for comparison Wales was 22.4% and Scotland was 18%, the European average was 12%.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brodschneider |first1=Robert |title=Preliminary analysis of loss rates of honey bee colonies during winter 2015/16 from the COLOSS survey |journal=Journal of Apicultural Research |date=2016 |volume=55 |issue=5 |pages=375\u2013378 |doi=10.1080/00218839.2016.1260240 |doi-access=free }}</ref> As a result of varroa there are now no [[wildlife|wild]] colonies surviving, [[feral]] colonies, swarms that have escaped from apiaries, will die within a short time, however their hives can be re-occupied afterwards by new swarms for the cycle to repeat; these feral colonies can become a source of large varroa populations, this and the fact that varroa has shown resistance to previously effective treatments can result in regional loses as high as 40-60%.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dr. Eric C. Mussen |title=Treating Colonies for Varroa Mite Infestations |url=http://entomology.ucdavis.edu/files/147623.pdf |website=entomology.ucdavis.edu |publisher=University of California, Davis. |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> On the occasions where feral colonies appear to be able to survive with varroa on a long term basis, closer study has discovered that the local strain of varroa have become non-lethal as opposed to the bees becoming resistant<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Thomas Seeley |title=Honey bees of the Arnot Forest: A population of feral colonies persisting with Varroa destructor in the northeastern United States |journal=Apidologie |date=2007 |volume=38 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201329 |doi=10.1051/apido:2006055 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/226076088 |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> or in which the varroa acts as a host to a non-lethal Deformed Wing Virus (DWV),<ref>{{cite journal |last1=G. J. Mordecai |last2=L. E. Brettell |last3=S. J. Martin |last4=D. Dixon |last5=I. M. Jones |last6=Declan C. Schroeder |title=Superinfection exclusion and the long-term survival of honey bees in Varroa-infested colonies |journal=The ISMA Journal: Multidisciplinary Journal of Microbial Eology |date=2016 |volume=10 |pages=1082\u20131191 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/ismej2015186 |accessdate=28 November 2018|pmid=26505829 }}</ref> both of which are exceptionally rare and non-reproducible, therefore a Parasite Management System must be maintained to continually manage the varroa mite.<ref>{{cite web |last1=J. Ambrose, D. Tarpy, J. Summers |title=Managing Varroa Mites in Honey Bee Colonies |url=https://content.ces.ncsu.edu/managing-varroa-mites-in-honey-bee-colonies |website=content.ces.ncsu.edu |publisher=North Carolina State University |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> As an alternative to treatment against the varroa mite and in the hope to re-establish a wild population, in 2013 a Varroa Tolerance Breeding Program was set up by NIHBS,<ref>{{cite web |title=Varroa tolerance breeding prog. |url=http://nihbs.org/ireland-varroa-monitoring-project/ |website=nihbs.org |publisher=NIHBS (Native Irish Honey Bee Society) |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref> focusing solely on the ''[[Apis mellifera mellifera|A. m. mellifera]]'', in conjunction with several breeding groups throughout Ireland,<ref>{{cite web |title=Queen Rearing (A.m.mellifera) |url=http://nihbs.org/queen-rearing/ |website=nihbs.org |publisher=NIHBS |accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref> including the Galtee Bee Breeding Group (GBBG)<ref>{{cite web |title=GBBG - Home page |url=http://gbbg.net/ |website=Galtee Bee Breeding Group |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> whose apiary manager, Miche\u00e1l Mac Giolla Coda (a former President of BIBBA,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Patterson |first1=R. |title=Miche\u00e1l Mac Giolla Coda |url=http://www.dave-cushman.net/bee/michealmacgiollacoda.html |website=dave-cushman.net |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=BIBBA |url=https://bibba.com/ |website=bibba.com |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> FIBKA and founding member of NIHBS<ref>{{cite web |last1=Patterson |first1=Roger |title=Lecturer: Miche\u00e1l Mac Giolla Coda. Galtee Bee Breeding Group, Ireland. |url=http://www.dave-cushman.net/bee/bibbaconflect.html |website=www.dave-cushman.net |publisher=2014 BIBBA/SICAMM Conference |accessdate=1 January 2019}}</ref>), in 2012 stated that \"the plan is to harness the bee\u2019s natural defences against the mite\" by improving the bees \"grooming and hygiene habits\" through selective breeding \"by observing the number of damaged mites\" without DNA analysis nor the use of [[Artificial insemination#Species|Instrumental Insemination]];<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eoine |first1=Burke-Kennedy |title=Breeding a better bee |journal=The Irish Times |date=2012 |volume=Thurs. 19th April 2012 |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/breeding-a-better-bee-1.504494 |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> in 2009 research was published that showed that marks on mite's exoskeletons, previously attributed as damage caused by grooming was more likely to be mere \"regular dorsal dimples (indentations)\";<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Davis |first1=Arthur R. |title=Regular dorsal dimples on Varroa destructor \u2013 Damage symptoms or developmental origin? |journal=Apidologie |volume=40 |date=2008 |issue=2 |pages=151\u2013162 |doi=10.1051/apido/2009001 |url=https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1051%2Fapido%2F2009001.pdf |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> in 2018 it was announced that varroa resistant ''[[Buckfast bees|Buckfast]]'' bees would be made available for sale in 2019,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dr. Peter St\u00f6fen |title=REPORTS: NEW: \"Hygiene\"-Buckfast Queens |url=https://buckfast-zucht.de/index.php?seite=berichte&la=en |website=buckfast-zucht.de |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> modern methods of breeding, such as Instrumental Insemination, had been used to impart this genetic trait into the wider ''Buckfast'' population. To date there has been no progress of such breeding projects towards imparting varroa resistance into the ''A. m. mellifera'' population in Ireland. Research, in co-ordination with NIHBS, was conducted in 2017 to determine if the ''A. m. mellifera'' in Ireland possessed varroa resistant characteristics, which had been observed in other ''A. mellifera'' such as the ''Buckfast bee'', based on an Executive Summary the conclusion was that it possessed no such resistance against the varroa mite (the paper has yet to be fully published).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Prof. Grace McCormack |title=Enhancement and protection of native Irish breeding stock of Apis mellifera mellifera with Varroa tolerance |url=https://www.agriculture.gov.ie/media/migration/farmingschemesandpayments/otherfarmersschemes/conservationgeneticresources/geneticresourcesprojects/2017/EnhancementNativeIrishBreedingStockApis270818.pdf |website=www.agriculture.gov.ie |publisher=NUI Galway |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Acarine===\n''[[Acarine]]'' or as it was known at the time, the ''[[Isle of Wight Disease]]'' (IoWD), was first reported in England on the Isle of Wight in 1906 where it wiped out 75% of colonies in the first year and later arrived in Ireland  by 1912, in several years it had spread throughout most of the island. By 1923 \"the country was swept clean of bees\", by 1927 the IBA requested the government to adopt a restocking scheme for re-population and also for \"importation of (resistant) Queen bees for re-sale at reduced prices\", many of the local bee Associations had already begun to import their own stocks, having chosen not to wait on the government assistance. The majority of the bees were [[Netherlands|Dutch]] ''A. m. mellifera'', with their characteristic swarminess.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=146\u2013148}}</ref> Modern DNA analysis, in 2017, has shown that the majority of ''Irish'' bees in Ireland are Dutch ''A. m. mellifera'' with the second largest group of ''A. m. mellifera'' originating from France, and smaller amounts of DNA originating from Norway and Switzerland.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Native Irish Honey Bee Society (NIHBS) |last2=E. Moore. |last3=G. Soland |last4=G. McCormack NIHBS Secretary |last5=J. Hasset |last6=K. Browne |last7=M. Geary |title=A significant pure population of the dark European honey bee (Apis mellifera mellifera) remains in Ireland |journal=Journal of Apicultural Research |date=2018 |volume=57 |issue=3 |pages=337\u2013350 Intro &  |doi=10.1080/00218839.2018.1433949 |doi-access=free }}</ref> In 1921 the cause of the IoWD was found to be the ''[[Acarapis woodi]]'' a tracheal mite, its common name ''Acarine'' is due to it belonging to the subclass ''[[Acari]]''. The Varroa mite is also a member of this subclass and therefore treatments against Varroa in its phoretic stage will also be effective against ''Acarapis woodi''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=J. Rennie |last2=P. B. White |last3=E. J. Harvey |title=Isle of Wight disease in hive bees |date=1921 |publisher=Edinburgh, Robert Grant & Son |pages=24 (XXIX) |url=https://ia800206.us.archive.org/5/items/cu31924003692633/cu31924003692633.pdf |accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref> In 2004 research was conducted to determine how the differences in the [[tracheas]] of various subspecies of ''Apis mellifera'' related to ''Acarapis woodi'', it was found that ''[[Apis mellifera macedonica|A. m. macedonica]]'', in which the ''Acarapis woodi'' are absent, has significantly smaller (up to 21%) measurements for its tracheas when compared to ''[[Apis mellifera carnica|A. m. carnica]]'' and ''A. m. ligustica'', in which ''Acarapis woodi'' are present: The research put forward the size of the tracheas of honey bees as a possible explanation for certain subspecies, or strains within them, being more susceptible to ''Acarine'' than others; the larger the tracheas, the greater the susceptibility to ''Acarine''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=F. Hatjina |last2=C. Papaefthimiou |last3=A. Gregorc |last4=G. Theophilidis |title=Differences in the morphology of prothoracic and propodeal spiracles in three strains of Apis mellifera: Possible relation to resistance against Acarapis woodi |journal=Journal of Apicultural Research |date=2004 |volume=43 |issue=3 |pages=105\u2013113 |doi=10.1080/00218839.2004.11101119 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/236022760 |accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref>  The ''A. m. mellifera'' is considered a large bee within ''Apis mellifera'', especially when compared to ''A. m. carnica'' and ''A. m. ligustica''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=M. L. Winston |title=The Biology of the Honey Bee |date=1991 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=978-0674074095 |pages=10 |edition= Paperback |url=https://books.google.com/?id=-5iobWHLtAQC&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref> In 1945 [[Brother Adam]], the breeder of the [[Buckfast bee]], obtained \"pure native\" Old Irish Black Bee queens (an Irish strain of [[apis mellifera mellifera|''A. m. mellifera'']]) that had survived the Acarine epidemic \"from a secluded place in the far [[west of Ireland]]\", from which he raised virgin queens and then crossed them with his ''Buckfast'' drones known to be resistant to Acarine, at his isolated Closed Mating Station on Dartmoor,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jean-Marie Van Dyck |title=Sherberton Br. Adam protected mating place (Dartmoor, GB) |url=http://perso.unamur.be/~jvandyck/homage/elver/pedgr/shr_BA_shr.html |website=Karl Kehrle Foundation |accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref> however like the British Black Bee from which it was descended, these too also all died from Acarine, in 1983 Brother Adam wrote \"the ''old'' English (and by inference Irish) brown bee\u2026 lives today only in the memory.. and was completely wiped out\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brother Adam |title=\"Isle of Wight\" or Acarine Disease: its Historical and Practical Aspects. |journal=Bee World |date=1968 |volume=49 |issue=1 |pages=6\u201318 |doi=10.1080/0005772X.1968.11097180}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Brother Adam |title=In Search of the Best Strains of Bees |date=1983 |publisher=Peacock Press |isbn=978-0907908067 |edition= 2nd Revised}}</ref>\n\n===AFB and EFB===\nOriginally both [[American foulbrood]] (AFB) caused by the spore-forming bacterium ''[[Paenibacillus larvae]]'' and [[European foulbrood]] (EFB) caused by the non-spore forming bacterium ''Melissococcus plutonius'',<ref>{{cite book |last1=J. D. & B. D. Yates |title=Beekeeping Study Notes for the BBKA Examination. Vol. 1. Mod. 1, 2 & 3. |date=2012 |publisher=Northern Bee Books |isbn=978-0905652818 |pages=180\u2013184 |edition=2}}</ref> were both referred to as Foul Brood and have been known in Ireland since at least 1897. In the Irish Bee Journal of 1901 \"the rapid spread of foul brood, that most terrible pest\" was discussed. They are both extremely infectious and persistent diseases affecting only the brood, spores of AFB can survive for up to 40 years. The adoption of modern beekeeping aided in the spreading of both these diseases, with the use of moveable frames, non-destruction of colonies each year and beekeeping equipment moving between apiaries. They are the two brood diseases which are notifiable in both jurisdictions of Ireland;<ref>{{cite web |last1=Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine (Republic of Ireland) |title=List of Notifiable Diseases |url=https://www.agriculture.gov.ie/animalhealthwelfare/diseasecontrol/listofnotifiablediseases/ |website=agriculture.gov.ie |accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Department of Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs (Northern Ireland) |title=Bee Health |url=https://www.daera-ni.gov.uk/articles/bee-health |website=daera-ni.gov.uk |accessdate=3 December 2018|date=2015-05-05 }}</ref> in 1903 the Bee Pest Act was enacted throughout all Ireland and in 1945 The Bee Pest Prevention Act was enacted in Northern Ireland (which repealed the previous 1908 Act), UKBA and government officials worked closely to bring this about, initially the 1945 Act also included [[Acarapis woodi|Acarine]] and [[Nosema (microsporidian)|Nosema]] as notifiable diseases reflecting their devastating effects on bee populations at the time. Bee Inspectors have been appointed to regularly inspect beehives and testing facilities have been established for beekeepers to have the contents of their hives diagnosed for disease, these services are provided free of charge. In 1945 in Northern Ireland, 14% of hives inspected (including unoccupied) were found to contain AFB, however by 1949 this had been reduced to 2.8%, but in 1950 11.9% of unoccupied hives inspected contained AFB spores.<ref>{{cite book |last1=J. K. Watson |title=Beekeeping in Ireland a History |date=1981 |publisher=Glendale |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=94\u201395, 135\u2013137, 145 |edition=1}}</ref> Although [[Oxytetracycline]] [[tetracycline]], an [[antibiotic]], can be used for treatment against EFB, it is dependent on the Bee Inspector, it used to be a treatment against AFB however it and all other treatments for AFB are now illegal. The only course of action that can be taken once AFB is confirmed in the hive by a Bee Inspector with the use of a field testing kit, is for the hive to be sealed at night and the entire hive and bees to be burned. In both cases a ban on moving anything from the apiary during the outbreak will be imposed.<ref>{{cite book |last1=J. D. & B. D. Yates |title=Beekeeping Study Notes for the BBKA Examination. Vol. 1. Mod. 1, 2 & 3. |date=2012 |publisher=Northern Bee Books |isbn=978-0905652818 |pages=184\u2013193 |edition=2}}</ref>\n\n===Other bee diseases and pests===\nThe other usual [[List of diseases of the honey bee|diseases of the honey bee]] are present in Ireland, although currently it is believed that Ireland is free from the [[small hive beetle| Small Hive Beetle]] (''Aethina tumida Murray'')<ref>{{cite web |title=Small Hive Beetle |url=https://www.agriculture.gov.ie/media/migration/farmingsectors/beekeepingandhoney/SmallHiveBeetleInfoSheetforbeekeepersIreland30092014.pdf |website=agriculture.gov.ie |publisher=Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine. |accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref> and [[Tropilaelaps]] mercedesae.<ref>{{cite web |title=TROPILAELAPS spp. mites |url=https://www.agriculture.gov.ie/media/migration/farmingsectors/beekeepingandhoney/TropilaelapsInfoSheetforbeekeepersIreland300914.pdf |website=agriculture.gov.ie |publisher=Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine |accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Pesticide poisoning and forage destruction===\nOf the agricultural chemicals used, it is the fungicides and the insecticides that can affect bees the most. Fungicides, if they infect he pollen, will get into the [[Bee pollen|bee bread]] which may affect it's consitiuents resulting in poor nutritional value. Also some fungicides are synergistic with some acaricides used to combat varroa, magnifying their effect on the bees themselves.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Celia F. Davis |title=The Honey Bee Around and About |date=2014 |publisher=Bee Craft Ltd. |isbn=978-0-900147-15-9 |pages=107\u2013109 |edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\nFrom agriculture there is widespread use of pesticides which allegedly{{Weasel inline|date=November 2018}} cause harm to bees{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}, along with widespread destruction of habitat which is essential for bee foraging.\n\n==Organisations==\nThe main beekeeping organizations in the [[Republic of Ireland]] are the Federation of Irish Beekeepers' Associations (FIBKA) and the Irish Beekeepers Association/''Cumann Beachair\u00ed na h\u00c9ireann'' (CLG), while in [[Northern Ireland]] the main beekeeping organizations are the Ulster Beekeepers Association (UBKA) and the Institute of Northern Ireland Beekeepers (INIB). There are also a number of other organisations within [[Ireland]], including the Native Irish Honey Bee Society (NIHBS) and the Irish Buckfast Beekeepers Association (IBBA).\n\n===Federation of Irish Beekeepers' Associations (FIBKA)===\nFIBKA is the largest organisation of beekeeping associations in Ireland, claiming to be established in 1881 and re-constituted 1943.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=30\u201343, 72\u201373, 171\u2013175}}</ref><ref>[https://irishbeekeeping.ie/about-us/ FIBKA history]</ref> FIBKA is a not-for-profit federation of beekeeping associations in Ireland with currently 60 affiliated associations which between them have over 3,500 members.\n\nFIBKA's goals include promotion of the conservation of the ''[[Apis mellifera mellifera|A. m. mellifera]]'' which they call \"the native dark bee\" as stated in their Constitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://irishbeekeeping.ie/about-us/|title=FIBKA Constitution Jan. 2016, point 3.6}}</ref> Advertisements for the sale of other types of bees, such as the [[Buckfast bee]], are regularly shown in their publications.<ref>{{cite web |title=Beekeeping Equipment and Supplies |url=https://irishbeekeeping.ie/beekeeping-supplies/ |website=irishbeekeeping.ie |publisher=FIBKA |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> FIBKA runs a summer course in beekeeping<ref>[https://irishbeekeeping.ie/wp-event/beekeeping-summer-school-gormanston-2019/ FIBKA Summer Course]</ref> every year since 1961. This is held at [[Gormanston, County Meath|Gormanston]], [[County Meath|Co. Meath]] in [[Gormanston College]] and holds examinations in the full range of beekeeping education, from the preliminary exams up to Honey Judge. FIBKA is a signatory, contributor to, and supporter of the All-Ireland Pollinator Plan, and is a member of the European Professional Beekeepers Association,<ref>{{cite web |title=European Professional Beekeepers Association - Members |url=http://www.professional-beekeepers.eu/?page_id=35 |website=professional-beekeepers.eu |publisher=Professional Beekeepers |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> the Council of National Beekeeping Associations in the United Kingdom and Ireland,<ref>{{cite web |title=Council of National Beekeeping Assoc.'s in the U.K. & Ireland - Members |url=http://www.conba.org.uk/ |website=conba.org |publisher=CONBA |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> the UK National Honey Show, and the Tree Council of Ireland.\n\n===Irish Beekeepers' Association CLG (IBA)===\nThe IBA is \"a democratic and egalitarian company, founded in October 2017\", as an \"alternative organisation (to FIBKA)\"<ref>{{cite web |title=IBA Blog - Message from our Director |url=https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com/blog/message-from-our-director |website=www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com |publisher=IBA |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref> their stated goals are \"to be Open, Fair and Transparent in all Our Actions for Our Members and to promote Beekeeping for '''all''' Beekeepers\" ... \"throughout the island of Ireland\", they \"hope to create an environment of mutual respect and understanding, so that no beekeeper ever feels marginalised or ostracised because of the type of bee they keep\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Irish Beekeepers Association - Home Page |url=https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com/ |website=www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com |publisher=IBA |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref> They offer membership insurance for both the North and South of Ireland, also offering individual membership not just association membership. It provides facilities and benefits comparable to those available from FIBKA, although it is necessarily smaller in both membership (21 association members)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com/map-of-affiliated-associations.html|title=IBA - Map of Affiliated Associations}}</ref> and the number of available lecturers due to its recent establishment. They support and endorse the All-Ireland Pollinator plan as well as the National Heritage Plan.<ref>{{cite web |title=The National Heritage Plan |url=https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com/national-heritage-plan.html |website=www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com |publisher=IBA |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Native Irish Honey Bee Society (NIHBS)===\nNIHBS promotes the conservation, study, and improvement of ''[[Apis mellifera mellifera|A. m. mellifera]]'', \"the only honeybee native to Ireland\" (Article 5.i. of the Constitution). They support research into this area with a number of Irish universities, working with and obtaining financial aid from Government Departments,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Native Irish Honey Bee - Genetic Resource Grant Aid Scheme |url=https://www.agriculture.gov.ie/farmingsectors/beekeepinghoney/thenativeirishhoneybee/ |website=Department of Agriculture, Food and Marine |publisher=DAFM |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> relating to the genetics of ''[[Apis mellifera mellifera|A. m. mellifera]]'' with a focus on Varroa tolerance.\n\nIn 2018 results from DNA analysis was published, which found that the bees being kept by NIHBS members were amongst the purest Amm in Europe. <ref>https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/00218839.2018.1433949</ref>\n\nNihbs also aims \"to establish areas of conservation throughout the island for the conservation of ''[[Apis mellifera mellifera]]''\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nihbs.org/about-us/aims-objectives/|title=The Native Irish Honey Bee Society - Aims & Objectives, 1 & 2|work=nihbs.org}}</ref> in the same manner as has been established on the islands of [[Colonsay]] and Oronsay in Scotland,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-24428707|title=Honeybee sanctuary status for Colonsay and Oransay|work=bbc.co.uk|date=2013-10-07}}</ref> where it is now a legal offence<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ssi/2013/279/note/made|title=The Bee Keeping (Colonsay and Oronsay) Order 2013}}</ref> to keep any other bee except ''[[Apis mellifera mellifera|A. m. mellifera]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://farm4.static.flickr.com/3686/32262438273_ea10d39c7b_b.jpg|title=Argyll & Bute Council sign at harbour}}</ref>\n\n===Irish Buckfast Beekeepers Association (IBBA)===\nThe IBBA promotes the keeping and breeding of ''[[Buckfast bees|Buckfast]]'' bees in [[Ireland]]. It is affiliated with the ''Federation of European Buckfast Beekeepers\u2019 Associations'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gdeb.eu/|title= Gemeinschaft der europ\u00e4ischen Buckfastimker e.V.|work=Community of European Buckfast beekeepers}}</ref> an international group of breeders dedicated to maintaining and improving this bee breed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://perso.unamur.be/~jvandyck/homage/elver/index.html|title=Honeybee Queens Pedigrees}}</ref> but supports beekeepers irrespective of the type of honeybee kept by the beekeeper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beekeeping.ie/html/open_letter.html|title=IBBA open letter}}</ref> A controlled open mating area has been established within the Five Glens area of north [[County Leitrim]], to enable Buckfast beekeepers to bring their virgin Buckfast queens to be mated with ''Buckfast'' [[Drone (bee)|drones]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Isolated mating - How, where and why it works |url=http://www.beekeeping.ie/html/local_bees.html |website=beekeeping.ie |publisher=The Irish Buckfast Beekeepers\u2019 Association |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Ulster Beekeepers Association (UBKA)===\nThe UBKA was formed in 1942<ref>{{cite web |title=UBKA - About |url=https://www.ubka.org/about/ |website=ubka.org |publisher=UBKA |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref> and is an association of the 12 affiliated local beekeeping associations in [[Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web |title=UBKA - Local Associations |url=https://www.ubka.org/about/local-associations/ |website=ubka.org |publisher=UBKA |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref> UBKA also works in partnership with FIBKA in the development of beekeeping education, and is a member of the Council of National Beekeeping Associations in the United Kingdom and Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |title=Council of National Beekeeping Assoc.'s in the U.K. & Ireland - Members |url=http://www.conba.org.uk/ |website=conba.org |publisher=CONBA |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> The UBKA holds an Annual Conference at the CAFRE Greenmount Campus site in Antrim.\n\n===Institute of Northern Ireland Beekeepers (INIB)===\nThe INIB was formed in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |title=Institute of Northern Ireland Beekeepers - Home page |url=https://www.inibeekeepers.com/ |website=inibeekeepers.com |publisher=INIB |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref> Members automatically become members of the BBKA.<ref>{{cite web |title=INIB - Membership |url=https://www.inibeekeepers.com/membership/ |website=inibeekeepers.com |publisher=INIB |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref> The INIB holds an Annual Conference and Honey Show at Lough Neagh Discovery Centre, Oxford Island, with its primary focus being the promotion of beekeeping through education and to this effect works closely with the UBKA.\n\n==Publications==\n* ''Irish Bee Journal'' (IBJ) was published by the Rev J.G. Digges from 1901 to 1933, and was succeeded by ''An Beachaire''. FIBKA archives include bound volumes of the IBJ and these are available to researchers.\n* ''An Beachaire'',<ref>[https://irishbeekeeping.ie/education/an-beachaire-current-issues/ ''An Beachaire'']</ref> subtitled ''The Irish Beekeeper'', was first published as a successor to the Irish Bee Journal in 1947, and is now published monthly by the Federation of Irish Beekeepers' Associations of which it is the official organ. The [[Gaeilge|Irish]] word for bee is \"beach\", with \"an beachaire\" meaning \"the beekeeper\". An Beachaire is a useful tool for communicating with beekeepers nationwide.\n* The ''Irish Beekeepers' Association CLG'' (IBA) publishes a bimonthly newsletter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com/subscribe-to-newsletter.html|title=Subscription page for our newsletter|website=Irish Beekeepers Association CLG Cumann Beachair\u00ed na h\u00c9ireann|language=en|access-date=2018-09-15}}</ref>\n* ''Bee Craft Magazine''<ref>{{cite web |title=Bee Craft Magazine |url=http://www.bee-craft.com/ |website=bee-craft.com |publisher=Bee Craft Ltd. |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> is offered by the IBA to members at a 10% reduced price.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com/beecraft-magazine.html|title=Annual Subscription to BeeCraft Magazine|website=Irish Beekeepers Association CLG Cumann Beachair\u00ed na h\u00c9ireann|language=en|access-date=2018-09-15}}</ref> Although this is a UK publication, much of its content is applicable to Ireland.\n* ''The Four Seasons'' (Ceithre Raithe na Bliana) magazine is published four times per year by the NIHBS, formally it was the voice of the GBBG.<ref>{{cite web |title=Four Seasons Magazine |url=http://nihbs.org/about-us/four-seasons-magazine/ |website=nihbs.org |publisher=NIHBS |accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n* Digital versions of back issues of ''BBKA News'',<ref>[https://bbkanews.com/ ''BBKA News'']</ref> subtitled ''The Newsletter of the British Beekeepers' Association'', are provided to members of the Federation of Irish Beekeepers' Associations.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Apimondia]] - International Federation of Beekeepers' Associations\n* [[Beekeeper]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.irishbeekeeping.ie Federation of Irish Beekeepers' Associations]\n* [https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com Irish Beekeepers Association]\n* [https://www.ubka.org/ Ulster Beekeepers Association]\n* [https://www.inibeekeepers.com/ Institute of Northern Ireland Beekeepers]\n* [https://www.bbka.org.uk/ British Beekeepers Association]\n* [http://www.beekeeping.ie/ Irish Buckfast Beekeepers' Association]\n* [http://nihbs.org/ Native Irish Honey Bee Society]\n* [http://www.bee-craft.com/ BeeCraft magazine]\n\n[[Category:Beekeeping by country|Ireland]]\n[[Category:Agriculture in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Beekeeping]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Irish English|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n[[File: St. Gobnait stained glass window design.tif|thumb|right|[[Harry Clarke]]'s design drawing for the [[Saint Gobnait]] window in [[Honan Chapel]], Cork, Ireland (1914). Saint Gobnait of Ballyvourney is a sixth-century patron saint of beekeepers.]]\n\n'''Beekeeping in [[Ireland]]''' has been practiced for at least 2000 years and has seen a surge in popularity in modern times, evidenced by the numerous organizations promoting and assisting beekeeping. Despite the increased pressures on bees and beekeepers through new diseases and loss of habitat, there are now in excess of 3,500 members within beekeeping associations.\n\n==History==\n===From early to modern beekeeping===\nHoney bees were brought to Ireland, most likely from Britain, sometime after the end of the last ice age.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Edwards, R.J., Brooks, A. |title=) The Island of Ireland: Drowning the Myth of an Irish Land-bridge? I |journal=The Irish Naturalists' Journal (Special Supplement) |date=2008 |pages=19\u201334 |url=http://www.tara.tcd.ie/bitstream/handle/2262/40560/Edwards&Brooks_INJ08_TARA.pdf;jsessionid=37D3E595A904F39A39A571C1E59DAADC?sequence=1 |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref> [[Solinus]] in the 3rd century A.D. makes mention of Ireland as having \"few bees\". The earliest reference from within Ireland about bees are in the Bee Judgements of the [[Brehon Laws]] which among other issues dealt with the ownership and value of swarms, the compensation paid by the beekeeper to a person stung by one of his bees and the compensation paid to the beekeeper if a person's hens began eating his bees. The Brehon Laws began to be codified about 438-441 A.D. having been handed down orally from previous generations, they contain no [[Latin]] loan words relating to bees or beekeeping, which provides further evidence that beekeeping vocabulary was established before the arrival of Christianity in about 430 A.D. However legend has it that St. [[Modomnoc]] first brought bees to Ireland from [[Wales]] in the early 540's A.D. just after the effects of the [[extreme weather events of 535\u2013536]] A.D. would have been subsiding. A \"great mortality of bees\" was recorded in 950 A.D., and again in 992 A.D. when it was said that \"Bees were largely kept in Ireland at this time, and were a great source of wealth to the people\". In 1443 A.D \"the third [[epizooty]] of bees\" was recorded.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Flemming |first1=George |title=Animal plagues: Their history, nature and prevention |date=1871 |publisher=Chapman and Hall |location=London |pages=[https://archive.org/details/animalplaguesthe00flem/page/53 53], 58, & 118 |url=https://archive.org/details/animalplaguesthe00flem |accessdate=6 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first beekeeping book in Ireland was ''Instructions for managing bees'' in 1733, it included recommendations for the use of [[skep]]s and stipulated the best size to use to encourage at least one [[swarming (honey bee)|swarm]] per year with two afterswarms to follow. The bees would traditionally have been killed at the end of each season, often with the use of brimstone matches, to be able to extract the honey and wax. However, by the mid-1700s boxes for keeping bees had begun to be used and methods of extracting the honey and wax, without killing the bees, were being devised.\nIn the 1870s Brother Joeseph, a Carmelite monk from [[Loughrea]], imported a Bar and Frame Hive<ref>{{cite book |last1=W. Augustus Munn |title=A Description of the Bar and Frame Hive |date=1844 |publisher=S. & J. Bentley, Wilson, and Fley |pages=2\u201321 |url=https://www.scribd.com/document/28931799/Bar-and-Frame-Hive |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> from Mr. Abbott of London and then began to produce his own versions, he is also recorded as being one of the first to import the ''Ligurian'' Italian honey bee (''[[apis mellifera ligustica|A. m. ligustica]]'') with a view to selective breeding \"..as being more prolific.. and harder workers.. would improve our home breed (the Irish strain of ''[[apis mellifera mellifera|A. m. mellifera]]'')\". In 1881 the Reverend George Proctor was believed to be the first in the country to own [[langstroth hive|Langstroth Hives]] (invented in 1852) with their moveable frames, which subsequent modern hives are based upon.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Crane|first=Eva|date=1998|title=Irish Beekeeping in the past|url=https://www.evacranetrust.org/uploads/document/d2797417eaa6d577c75c7f0b4142668276cc178e.pdf|journal=Ulster Folklife|volume=44|pages=45\u201351|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=1\u20135, 6\u201311, 271\u2013275}}</ref>\n\nIn 1912 the ''[[Isle of Wight Disease]]'' (IoWD) arrived in Ireland, wiping out the [[Indigenous (ecology)|indigenous]] native Irish Black Bee (''A. m. mellifera''), Ireland was restocked with ''A. m. mellifera'' imports mainly originating from Hollund, but also from France.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=146\u2013148}}</ref>\n\n===Formation of the Associations===\nIn 1880 the British Beekeepers Association (BBKA) decided to tour Ireland with a \"bee tent\" to show modern beekeeping equipment and manipulations of bees to the public. They were joined by Brother Joseph, throughout much of Ireland as he continued on his \"holy crusade\" for the honey bee; he later proposed the formation of an Irish beekeeping association \"for promoting and instructing the improved methods of bee culture to the cottagers of Ireland\". In 1881 the Irish Beekeepers Associations (IBKA) was formed, holding a honey show in Dublin; in 1908 their name was changed to Irish Beekeepers' Association (IBA), in 1939 it was wound up due to decreasing membership.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=vi, 30\u201343, 72\u201374, 271\u2013276}}</ref>\n\nIn 1943 the County Dublin Beekeepers' Association was formed, from which an attempt was made to revive the old IBA to form an ''all'' Ireland body. On St. Patrick's Day in 1944 the Federation of Irish Beekeepers' Associations was formed; the recently formed Ulster Bee Keepers' Association (UBKA) did not associate themselves with it.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=171\u2013172}}</ref>\n\nIn 1926 the Banbridge and District Beekeeping Association was formed; in 1934 its name became the Northern Ireland Bee Keepers' Association. In 1942 the UBKA was formed and in 1951 the smaller NIBKA affiliated with it and was later absorbed into it. In 1949 there were 6,000 beekeepers with 16,000 hives, the most common of which was the CDB Hive. At the 14th Annual Conference in 1959 a lecture was given entitled \"How to take advantage of the ''[[buckfast bee|Buckfast]]'' strain of bees, to be shortly introduced into Northern Ireland\". At the 15th Annual Conference in 1960 a member of the Ministry of Agriculture gave the lecture \"The Buckfast Strain of Honeybee and its dissemination throughout Northern Ireland\". In 1966 at the 21st Annual Conference of the UBKA it was decided that all subsequent Conferences should be held at Greenmount Agricultural and Horticultural College; it was also at this conference that the Ministry of Agriculture informed the UBKA \"that due to the increase of Nosema, the ''Buckfast'' Queen distribution scheme was being suspended\", a scheme initially begun to improve the local bee stock (the ''A. m. mellifera'' imported after the IoWD).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=135}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966 the FIBKA raised the subject of forming an All-Ireland Beekeepers' Alliance but the UBKA unanimously rejected the suggestion, opting instead to support continued co-operation.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=121\u2013123, 126\u2013129, 130}}</ref>\n\n==Honeybee diseases, pests and poisons==\n\n===Varroa===\nPresently the ''[[Varroa destructor]]'' mite is the single greatest threat to bee colonies in Ireland. If left untreated colonies will die within three to four years, although typically after the initial infestation there can be a rapid increase in the mite population which would lead to colony collapse.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=B\u00fcChler |first1=Ralph |title=Varroa Tolerance in Honey Bees\u2014Occurrence, Characters and Breeding |journal=Bee World |date=1994 |volume=75 |issue=2 |pages= 54\u201370 |doi=10.1080/0005772X.1994.11099201 }}</ref> Varroa mites arrived in Ireland in 1998 and in several years had spread throughout most of the island.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McMullan |first1=John |title=Adaptation in Honey Bee (Apis mellifera) Colonies Exhibiting Tolerance to Varroa destructor in Ireland |journal=Bee World |date=2018 |volume=95 |issue=2 |pages=39\u201343 |doi=10.1080/0005772X.2018.1431000 |doi-access=free }}</ref> The mortality rate for over-wintered colonies during 2015/16 in the Republic of Ireland was 29.5% and for Northern Ireland was 28.2%; for comparison Wales was 22.4% and Scotland was 18%, the European average was 12%.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brodschneider |first1=Robert |title=Preliminary analysis of loss rates of honey bee colonies during winter 2015/16 from the COLOSS survey |journal=Journal of Apicultural Research |date=2016 |volume=55 |issue=5 |pages=375\u2013378 |doi=10.1080/00218839.2016.1260240 |doi-access=free }}</ref> As a result of varroa there are now no [[wildlife|wild]] colonies surviving, [[feral]] colonies, swarms that have escaped from apiaries, will die within a short time, however their hives can be re-occupied afterwards by new swarms for the cycle to repeat; these feral colonies can become a source of large varroa populations, this and the fact that varroa has shown resistance to previously effective treatments can result in regional loses as high as 40-60%.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dr. Eric C. Mussen |title=Treating Colonies for Varroa Mite Infestations |url=http://entomology.ucdavis.edu/files/147623.pdf |website=entomology.ucdavis.edu |publisher=University of California, Davis. |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> On the occasions where feral colonies appear to be able to survive with varroa on a long term basis, closer study has discovered that the local strain of varroa have become non-lethal as opposed to the bees becoming resistant<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Thomas Seeley |title=Honey bees of the Arnot Forest: A population of feral colonies persisting with Varroa destructor in the northeastern United States |journal=Apidologie |date=2007 |volume=38 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201329 |doi=10.1051/apido:2006055 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/226076088 |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> or in which the varroa acts as a host to a non-lethal Deformed Wing Virus (DWV),<ref>{{cite journal |last1=G. J. Mordecai |last2=L. E. Brettell |last3=S. J. Martin |last4=D. Dixon |last5=I. M. Jones |last6=Declan C. Schroeder |title=Superinfection exclusion and the long-term survival of honey bees in Varroa-infested colonies |journal=The ISMA Journal: Multidisciplinary Journal of Microbial Eology |date=2016 |volume=10 |pages=1082\u20131191 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/ismej2015186 |accessdate=28 November 2018|pmid=26505829 }}</ref> both of which are exceptionally rare and non-reproducible, therefore a Parasite Management System must be maintained to continually manage the varroa mite.<ref>{{cite web |last1=J. Ambrose, D. Tarpy, J. Summers |title=Managing Varroa Mites in Honey Bee Colonies |url=https://content.ces.ncsu.edu/managing-varroa-mites-in-honey-bee-colonies |website=content.ces.ncsu.edu |publisher=North Carolina State University |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> As an alternative to treatment against the varroa mite and in the hope to re-establish a wild population, in 2013 a Varroa Tolerance Breeding Program was set up by NIHBS,<ref>{{cite web |title=Varroa tolerance breeding prog. |url=http://nihbs.org/ireland-varroa-monitoring-project/ |website=nihbs.org |publisher=NIHBS (Native Irish Honey Bee Society) |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref> focusing solely on the ''[[Apis mellifera mellifera|A. m. mellifera]]'', in conjunction with several breeding groups throughout Ireland,<ref>{{cite web |title=Queen Rearing (A.m.mellifera) |url=http://nihbs.org/queen-rearing/ |website=nihbs.org |publisher=NIHBS |accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref> including the Galtee Bee Breeding Group (GBBG)<ref>{{cite web |title=GBBG - Home page |url=http://gbbg.net/ |website=Galtee Bee Breeding Group |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> whose apiary manager, Miche\u00e1l Mac Giolla Coda (a former President of BIBBA,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Patterson |first1=R. |title=Miche\u00e1l Mac Giolla Coda |url=http://www.dave-cushman.net/bee/michealmacgiollacoda.html |website=dave-cushman.net |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=BIBBA |url=https://bibba.com/ |website=bibba.com |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> FIBKA and founding member of NIHBS<ref>{{cite web |last1=Patterson |first1=Roger |title=Lecturer: Miche\u00e1l Mac Giolla Coda. Galtee Bee Breeding Group, Ireland. |url=http://www.dave-cushman.net/bee/bibbaconflect.html |website=www.dave-cushman.net |publisher=2014 BIBBA/SICAMM Conference |accessdate=1 January 2019}}</ref>), in 2012 stated that \"the plan is to harness the bee\u2019s natural defences against the mite\" by improving the bees \"grooming and hygiene habits\" through selective breeding \"by observing the number of damaged mites\" without DNA analysis nor the use of [[Artificial insemination#Species|Instrumental Insemination]];<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eoine |first1=Burke-Kennedy |title=Breeding a better bee |journal=The Irish Times |date=2012 |volume=Thurs. 19th April 2012 |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/breeding-a-better-bee-1.504494 |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> in 2009 research was published that showed that marks on mite's exoskeletons, previously attributed as damage caused by grooming was more likely to be mere \"regular dorsal dimples (indentations)\";<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Davis |first1=Arthur R. |title=Regular dorsal dimples on Varroa destructor \u2013 Damage symptoms or developmental origin? |journal=Apidologie |volume=40 |date=2008 |issue=2 |pages=151\u2013162 |doi=10.1051/apido/2009001 |url=https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1051%2Fapido%2F2009001.pdf |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> in 2018 it was announced that varroa resistant ''[[Buckfast bees|Buckfast]]'' bees would be made available for sale in 2019,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dr. Peter St\u00f6fen |title=REPORTS: NEW: \"Hygiene\"-Buckfast Queens |url=https://buckfast-zucht.de/index.php?seite=berichte&la=en |website=buckfast-zucht.de |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> modern methods of breeding, such as Instrumental Insemination, had been used to impart this genetic trait into the wider ''Buckfast'' population. To date there has been no progress of such breeding projects towards imparting varroa resistance into the ''A. m. mellifera'' population in Ireland. Research, in co-ordination with NIHBS, was conducted in 2017 to determine if the ''A. m. mellifera'' in Ireland possessed varroa resistant characteristics, which had been observed in other ''A. mellifera'' such as the ''Buckfast bee'', based on an Executive Summary the conclusion was that it possessed no such resistance against the varroa mite (the paper has yet to be fully published).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Prof. Grace McCormack |title=Enhancement and protection of native Irish breeding stock of Apis mellifera mellifera with Varroa tolerance |url=https://www.agriculture.gov.ie/media/migration/farmingschemesandpayments/otherfarmersschemes/conservationgeneticresources/geneticresourcesprojects/2017/EnhancementNativeIrishBreedingStockApis270818.pdf |website=www.agriculture.gov.ie |publisher=NUI Galway |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Acarine===\n''[[Acarine]]'' or as it was known at the time, the ''[[Isle of Wight Disease]]'' (IoWD), was first reported in England on the Isle of Wight in 1906 where it wiped out 75% of colonies in the first year and later arrived in Ireland  by 1912, in several years it had spread throughout most of the island. By 1923 \"the country was swept clean of bees\", by 1927 the IBA requested the government to adopt a restocking scheme for re-population and also for \"importation of (resistant) Queen bees for re-sale at reduced prices\", many of the local bee Associations had already begun to import their own stocks, having chosen not to wait on the government assistance. The majority of the bees were [[Netherlands|Dutch]] ''A. m. mellifera'', with their characteristic swarminess.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=146\u2013148}}</ref> Modern DNA analysis, in 2017, has shown that the majority of ''Irish'' bees in Ireland are Dutch ''A. m. mellifera'' with the second largest group of ''A. m. mellifera'' originating from France, and smaller amounts of DNA originating from Norway and Switzerland.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Native Irish Honey Bee Society (NIHBS) |last2=E. Moore. |last3=G. Soland |last4=G. McCormack NIHBS Secretary |last5=J. Hasset |last6=K. Browne |last7=M. Geary |title=A significant pure population of the dark European honey bee (Apis mellifera mellifera) remains in Ireland |journal=Journal of Apicultural Research |date=2018 |volume=57 |issue=3 |pages=337\u2013350 Intro &  |doi=10.1080/00218839.2018.1433949 |doi-access=free }}</ref> In 1921 the cause of the IoWD was found to be the ''[[Acarapis woodi]]'' a tracheal mite, its common name ''Acarine'' is due to it belonging to the subclass ''[[Acari]]''. The Varroa mite is also a member of this subclass and therefore treatments against Varroa in its phoretic stage will also be effective against ''Acarapis woodi''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=J. Rennie |last2=P. B. White |last3=E. J. Harvey |title=Isle of Wight disease in hive bees |date=1921 |publisher=Edinburgh, Robert Grant & Son |pages=24 (XXIX) |url=https://ia800206.us.archive.org/5/items/cu31924003692633/cu31924003692633.pdf |accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref> In 2004 research was conducted to determine how the differences in the [[tracheas]] of various subspecies of ''Apis mellifera'' related to ''Acarapis woodi'', it was found that ''[[Apis mellifera macedonica|A. m. macedonica]]'', in which the ''Acarapis woodi'' are absent, has significantly smaller (up to 21%) measurements for its tracheas when compared to ''[[Apis mellifera carnica|A. m. carnica]]'' and ''A. m. ligustica'', in which ''Acarapis woodi'' are present: The research put forward the size of the tracheas of honey bees as a possible explanation for certain subspecies, or strains within them, being more susceptible to ''Acarine'' than others; the larger the tracheas, the greater the susceptibility to ''Acarine''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=F. Hatjina |last2=C. Papaefthimiou |last3=A. Gregorc |last4=G. Theophilidis |title=Differences in the morphology of prothoracic and propodeal spiracles in three strains of Apis mellifera: Possible relation to resistance against Acarapis woodi |journal=Journal of Apicultural Research |date=2004 |volume=43 |issue=3 |pages=105\u2013113 |doi=10.1080/00218839.2004.11101119 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/236022760 |accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref>  The ''A. m. mellifera'' is considered a large bee within ''Apis mellifera'', especially when compared to ''A. m. carnica'' and ''A. m. ligustica''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=M. L. Winston |title=The Biology of the Honey Bee |date=1991 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=978-0674074095 |pages=10 |edition= Paperback |url=https://books.google.com/?id=-5iobWHLtAQC&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref> In 1945 [[Brother Adam]], the breeder of the [[Buckfast bee]], obtained \"pure native\" Old Irish Black Bee queens (an Irish strain of [[apis mellifera mellifera|''A. m. mellifera'']]) that had survived the Acarine epidemic \"from a secluded place in the far [[west of Ireland]]\", from which he raised virgin queens and then crossed them with his ''Buckfast'' drones known to be resistant to Acarine, at his isolated Closed Mating Station on Dartmoor,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jean-Marie Van Dyck |title=Sherberton Br. Adam protected mating place (Dartmoor, GB) |url=http://perso.unamur.be/~jvandyck/homage/elver/pedgr/shr_BA_shr.html |website=Karl Kehrle Foundation |accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref> however like the British Black Bee from which it was descended, these too also all died from Acarine, in 1983 Brother Adam wrote \"the ''old'' English (and by inference Irish) brown bee\u2026 lives today only in the memory.. and was completely wiped out\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brother Adam |title=\"Isle of Wight\" or Acarine Disease: its Historical and Practical Aspects. |journal=Bee World |date=1968 |volume=49 |issue=1 |pages=6\u201318 |doi=10.1080/0005772X.1968.11097180}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Brother Adam |title=In Search of the Best Strains of Bees |date=1983 |publisher=Peacock Press |isbn=978-0907908067 |edition= 2nd Revised}}</ref>\n\n===AFB and EFB===\nOriginally both [[American foulbrood]] (AFB) caused by the spore-forming bacterium ''[[Paenibacillus larvae]]'' and [[European foulbrood]] (EFB) caused by the non-spore forming bacterium ''Melissococcus plutonius'',<ref>{{cite book |last1=J. D. & B. D. Yates |title=Beekeeping Study Notes for the BBKA Examination. Vol. 1. Mod. 1, 2 & 3. |date=2012 |publisher=Northern Bee Books |isbn=978-0905652818 |pages=180\u2013184 |edition=2}}</ref> were both referred to as Foul Brood and have been known in Ireland since at least 1897. In the Irish Bee Journal of 1901 \"the rapid spread of foul brood, that most terrible pest\" was discussed. They are both extremely infectious and persistent diseases affecting only the brood, spores of AFB can survive for up to 40 years. The adoption of modern beekeeping aided in the spreading of both these diseases, with the use of moveable frames, non-destruction of colonies each year and beekeeping equipment moving between apiaries. They are the two brood diseases which are notifiable in both jurisdictions of Ireland;<ref>{{cite web |last1=Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine (Republic of Ireland) |title=List of Notifiable Diseases |url=https://www.agriculture.gov.ie/animalhealthwelfare/diseasecontrol/listofnotifiablediseases/ |website=agriculture.gov.ie |accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Department of Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs (Northern Ireland) |title=Bee Health |url=https://www.daera-ni.gov.uk/articles/bee-health |website=daera-ni.gov.uk |accessdate=3 December 2018|date=2015-05-05 }}</ref> in 1903 the Bee Pest Act was enacted throughout all Ireland and in 1945 The Bee Pest Prevention Act was enacted in Northern Ireland (which repealed the previous 1908 Act), UKBA and government officials worked closely to bring this about, initially the 1945 Act also included [[Acarapis woodi|Acarine]] and [[Nosema (microsporidian)|Nosema]] as notifiable diseases reflecting their devastating effects on bee populations at the time. Bee Inspectors have been appointed to regularly inspect beehives and testing facilities have been established for beekeepers to have the contents of their hives diagnosed for disease, these services are provided free of charge. In 1945 in Northern Ireland, 14% of hives inspected (including unoccupied) were found to contain AFB, however by 1949 this had been reduced to 2.8%, but in 1950 11.9% of unoccupied hives inspected contained AFB spores.<ref>{{cite book |last1=J. K. Watson |title=Beekeeping in Ireland a History |date=1981 |publisher=Glendale |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=94\u201395, 135\u2013137, 145 |edition=1}}</ref> Although [[Oxytetracycline]] [[tetracycline]], an [[antibiotic]], can be used for treatment against EFB, it is dependent on the Bee Inspector, it used to be a treatment against AFB however it and all other treatments for AFB are now illegal. The only course of action that can be taken once AFB is confirmed in the hive by a Bee Inspector with the use of a field testing kit, is for the hive to be sealed at night and the entire hive and bees to be burned. In both cases a ban on moving anything from the apiary during the outbreak will be imposed.<ref>{{cite book |last1=J. D. & B. D. Yates |title=Beekeeping Study Notes for the BBKA Examination. Vol. 1. Mod. 1, 2 & 3. |date=2012 |publisher=Northern Bee Books |isbn=978-0905652818 |pages=184\u2013193 |edition=2}}</ref>\n\n===Other bee diseases and pests===\nThe other usual [[List of diseases of the honey bee|diseases of the honey bee]] are present in Ireland, although currently it is believed that Ireland is free from the [[small hive beetle| Small Hive Beetle]] (''Aethina tumida Murray'')<ref>{{cite web |title=Small Hive Beetle |url=https://www.agriculture.gov.ie/media/migration/farmingsectors/beekeepingandhoney/SmallHiveBeetleInfoSheetforbeekeepersIreland30092014.pdf |website=agriculture.gov.ie |publisher=Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine. |accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref> and [[Tropilaelaps]] mercedesae.<ref>{{cite web |title=TROPILAELAPS spp. mites |url=https://www.agriculture.gov.ie/media/migration/farmingsectors/beekeepingandhoney/TropilaelapsInfoSheetforbeekeepersIreland300914.pdf |website=agriculture.gov.ie |publisher=Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine |accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Pesticide poisoning and forage destruction===\nOf the agricultural chemicals used, it is the fungicides and the insecticides that can affect bees the most. Fungicides, if they infect he pollen, will get into the [[Bee pollen|bee bread]] which may affect it's consitiuents resulting in poor nutritional value. Also some fungicides are synergistic with some acaricides used to combat varroa, magnifying their effect on the bees themselves.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Celia F. Davis |title=The Honey Bee Around and About |date=2014 |publisher=Bee Craft Ltd. |isbn=978-0-900147-15-9 |pages=107\u2013109 |edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\nFrom agriculture there is widespread use of pesticides which allegedly{{Weasel inline|date=November 2018}} cause harm to bees{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}, along with widespread destruction of habitat which is essential for bee foraging.\n\n==Organisations==\nThe main beekeeping organizations in the [[Republic of Ireland]] are the Federation of Irish Beekeepers' Associations (FIBKA) and the Irish Beekeepers Association/''Cumann Beachair\u00ed na h\u00c9ireann'' (CLG), while in [[Northern Ireland]] the main beekeeping organizations are the Ulster Beekeepers Association (UBKA) and the Institute of Northern Ireland Beekeepers (INIB). There are also a number of other organisations within [[Ireland]], including the Native Irish Honey Bee Society (NIHBS) and the Irish Buckfast Beekeepers Association (IBBA).\n\n===Federation of Irish Beekeepers' Associations (FIBKA)===\nFIBKA is the largest organisation of beekeeping associations in Ireland, claiming to be established in 1881 and re-constituted 1943.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=James K. |title=Bee-keeping in Ireland: A history. |date=1981 |publisher=The Glendale Press |isbn=978-0907606000 |pages=30\u201343, 72\u201373, 171\u2013175}}</ref><ref>[https://irishbeekeeping.ie/about-us/ FIBKA history]</ref> FIBKA is a not-for-profit federation of beekeeping associations in Ireland with currently 60 affiliated associations which between them have over 3,500 members.\n\nFIBKA's goals include promotion of the conservation of the ''[[Apis mellifera mellifera|A. m. mellifera]]'' which they call \"the native dark bee\" as stated in their Constitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://irishbeekeeping.ie/about-us/|title=FIBKA Constitution Jan. 2016, point 3.6}}</ref> Advertisements for the sale of other types of bees, such as the [[Buckfast bee]], are regularly shown in their publications.<ref>{{cite web |title=Beekeeping Equipment and Supplies |url=https://irishbeekeeping.ie/beekeeping-supplies/ |website=irishbeekeeping.ie |publisher=FIBKA |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> FIBKA runs a summer course in beekeeping<ref>[https://irishbeekeeping.ie/wp-event/beekeeping-summer-school-gormanston-2019/ FIBKA Summer Course]</ref> every year since 1961. This is held at [[Gormanston, County Meath|Gormanston]], [[County Meath|Co. Meath]] in [[Gormanston College]] and holds examinations in the full range of beekeeping education, from the preliminary exams up to Honey Judge. FIBKA is a signatory, contributor to, and supporter of the All-Ireland Pollinator Plan, and is a member of the European Professional Beekeepers Association,<ref>{{cite web |title=European Professional Beekeepers Association - Members |url=http://www.professional-beekeepers.eu/?page_id=35 |website=professional-beekeepers.eu |publisher=Professional Beekeepers |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> the Council of National Beekeeping Associations in the United Kingdom and Ireland,<ref>{{cite web |title=Council of National Beekeeping Assoc.'s in the U.K. & Ireland - Members |url=http://www.conba.org.uk/ |website=conba.org |publisher=CONBA |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> the UK National Honey Show, and the Tree Council of Ireland.\n\n===Irish Beekeepers' Association CLG (IBA)===\nThe IBA is \"a democratic and egalitarian company, founded in October 2017\", as an \"alternative organisation (to FIBKA)\"<ref>{{cite web |title=IBA Blog - Message from our Director |url=https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com/blog/message-from-our-director |website=www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com |publisher=IBA |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref> their stated goals are \"to be Open, Fair and Transparent in all Our Actions for Our Members and to promote Beekeeping for '''all''' Beekeepers\" ... \"throughout the island of Ireland\", they \"hope to create an environment of mutual respect and understanding, so that no beekeeper ever feels marginalised or ostracised because of the type of bee they keep\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Irish Beekeepers Association - Home Page |url=https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com/ |website=www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com |publisher=IBA |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref> They offer membership insurance for both the North and South of Ireland, also offering individual membership not just association membership. It provides facilities and benefits comparable to those available from FIBKA, although it is necessarily smaller in both membership (21 association members)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com/map-of-affiliated-associations.html|title=IBA - Map of Affiliated Associations}}</ref> and the number of available lecturers due to its recent establishment. They support and endorse the All-Ireland Pollinator plan as well as the National Heritage Plan.<ref>{{cite web |title=The National Heritage Plan |url=https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com/national-heritage-plan.html |website=www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com |publisher=IBA |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Native Irish Honey Bee Society (NIHBS)===\nNIHBS promotes the conservation, study, and improvement of ''[[Apis mellifera mellifera|A. m. mellifera]]'', \"the only honeybee native to Ireland\" (Article 5.i. of the Constitution). They support research into this area with a number of Irish universities, working with and obtaining financial aid from Government Departments,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Native Irish Honey Bee - Genetic Resource Grant Aid Scheme |url=https://www.agriculture.gov.ie/farmingsectors/beekeepinghoney/thenativeirishhoneybee/ |website=Department of Agriculture, Food and Marine |publisher=DAFM |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> relating to the genetics of ''[[Apis mellifera mellifera|A. m. mellifera]]'' with a focus on Varroa resistance, the conclusion of which found \"that the selected (Native Irish Black) bees not alone have the capability of controlling the number of Varroa mites in a hive\"\n\nIn 2018 results from DNA analysis was published, which found that the bees being kept by NIHBS members were amongst the purest Amm in Europe. |last5=J. Hassett |last6=K. Browne |last7=M. Geary |title=A significant pure population of the dark European honey bee (Apis mellifera mellifera) remains in Ireland |journal=Journal of Apicultural Research |date=2018 |volume=57 |issue=3 |pages=337\u2013350 |doi=10.1080/00218839.2018.1433949 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nNihbs also aims \"to establish areas of conservation throughout the island for the conservation of ''[[Apis mellifera mellifera]]''\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nihbs.org/about-us/aims-objectives/|title=The Native Irish Honey Bee Society - Aims & Objectives, 1 & 2|work=nihbs.org}}</ref> in the same manner as has been established on the islands of [[Colonsay]] and Oronsay in Scotland,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-24428707|title=Honeybee sanctuary status for Colonsay and Oransay|work=bbc.co.uk|date=2013-10-07}}</ref> where it is now a legal offence<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ssi/2013/279/note/made|title=The Bee Keeping (Colonsay and Oronsay) Order 2013}}</ref> to keep any other bee except ''[[Apis mellifera mellifera|A. m. mellifera]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://farm4.static.flickr.com/3686/32262438273_ea10d39c7b_b.jpg|title=Argyll & Bute Council sign at harbour}}</ref>\n\n===Irish Buckfast Beekeepers Association (IBBA)===\nThe IBBA promotes the keeping and breeding of ''[[Buckfast bees|Buckfast]]'' bees in [[Ireland]]. It is affiliated with the ''Federation of European Buckfast Beekeepers\u2019 Associations'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gdeb.eu/|title= Gemeinschaft der europ\u00e4ischen Buckfastimker e.V.|work=Community of European Buckfast beekeepers}}</ref> an international group of breeders dedicated to maintaining and improving this bee breed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://perso.unamur.be/~jvandyck/homage/elver/index.html|title=Honeybee Queens Pedigrees}}</ref> but supports beekeepers irrespective of the type of honeybee kept by the beekeeper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beekeeping.ie/html/open_letter.html|title=IBBA open letter}}</ref> A controlled open mating area has been established within the Five Glens area of north [[County Leitrim]], to enable Buckfast beekeepers to bring their virgin Buckfast queens to be mated with ''Buckfast'' [[Drone (bee)|drones]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Isolated mating - How, where and why it works |url=http://www.beekeeping.ie/html/local_bees.html |website=beekeeping.ie |publisher=The Irish Buckfast Beekeepers\u2019 Association |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Ulster Beekeepers Association (UBKA)===\nThe UBKA was formed in 1942<ref>{{cite web |title=UBKA - About |url=https://www.ubka.org/about/ |website=ubka.org |publisher=UBKA |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref> and is an association of the 12 affiliated local beekeeping associations in [[Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web |title=UBKA - Local Associations |url=https://www.ubka.org/about/local-associations/ |website=ubka.org |publisher=UBKA |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref> UBKA also works in partnership with FIBKA in the development of beekeeping education, and is a member of the Council of National Beekeeping Associations in the United Kingdom and Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |title=Council of National Beekeeping Assoc.'s in the U.K. & Ireland - Members |url=http://www.conba.org.uk/ |website=conba.org |publisher=CONBA |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> The UBKA holds an Annual Conference at the CAFRE Greenmount Campus site in Antrim.\n\n===Institute of Northern Ireland Beekeepers (INIB)===\nThe INIB was formed in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |title=Institute of Northern Ireland Beekeepers - Home page |url=https://www.inibeekeepers.com/ |website=inibeekeepers.com |publisher=INIB |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref> Members automatically become members of the BBKA.<ref>{{cite web |title=INIB - Membership |url=https://www.inibeekeepers.com/membership/ |website=inibeekeepers.com |publisher=INIB |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref> The INIB holds an Annual Conference and Honey Show at Lough Neagh Discovery Centre, Oxford Island, with its primary focus being the promotion of beekeeping through education and to this effect works closely with the UBKA.\n\n==Publications==\n* ''Irish Bee Journal'' (IBJ) was published by the Rev J.G. Digges from 1901 to 1933, and was succeeded by ''An Beachaire''. FIBKA archives include bound volumes of the IBJ and these are available to researchers.\n* ''An Beachaire'',<ref>[https://irishbeekeeping.ie/education/an-beachaire-current-issues/ ''An Beachaire'']</ref> subtitled ''The Irish Beekeeper'', was first published as a successor to the Irish Bee Journal in 1947, and is now published monthly by the Federation of Irish Beekeepers' Associations of which it is the official organ. The [[Gaeilge|Irish]] word for bee is \"beach\", with \"an beachaire\" meaning \"the beekeeper\". An Beachaire is a useful tool for communicating with beekeepers nationwide.\n* The ''Irish Beekeepers' Association CLG'' (IBA) publishes a bimonthly newsletter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com/subscribe-to-newsletter.html|title=Subscription page for our newsletter|website=Irish Beekeepers Association CLG Cumann Beachair\u00ed na h\u00c9ireann|language=en|access-date=2018-09-15}}</ref>\n* ''Bee Craft Magazine''<ref>{{cite web |title=Bee Craft Magazine |url=http://www.bee-craft.com/ |website=bee-craft.com |publisher=Bee Craft Ltd. |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> is offered by the IBA to members at a 10% reduced price.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com/beecraft-magazine.html|title=Annual Subscription to BeeCraft Magazine|website=Irish Beekeepers Association CLG Cumann Beachair\u00ed na h\u00c9ireann|language=en|access-date=2018-09-15}}</ref> Although this is a UK publication, much of its content is applicable to Ireland.\n* ''The Four Seasons'' (Ceithre Raithe na Bliana) magazine is published four times per year by the NIHBS, formally it was the voice of the GBBG.<ref>{{cite web |title=Four Seasons Magazine |url=http://nihbs.org/about-us/four-seasons-magazine/ |website=nihbs.org |publisher=NIHBS |accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n* Digital versions of back issues of ''BBKA News'',<ref>[https://bbkanews.com/ ''BBKA News'']</ref> subtitled ''The Newsletter of the British Beekeepers' Association'', are provided to members of the Federation of Irish Beekeepers' Associations.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Apimondia]] - International Federation of Beekeepers' Associations\n* [[Beekeeper]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.irishbeekeeping.ie Federation of Irish Beekeepers' Associations]\n* [https://www.irishbeekeepersassociation.com Irish Beekeepers Association]\n* [https://www.ubka.org/ Ulster Beekeepers Association]\n* [https://www.inibeekeepers.com/ Institute of Northern Ireland Beekeepers]\n* [https://www.bbka.org.uk/ British Beekeepers Association]\n* [http://www.beekeeping.ie/ Irish Buckfast Beekeepers' Association]\n* [http://nihbs.org/ Native Irish Honey Bee Society]\n* [http://www.bee-craft.com/ BeeCraft magazine]\n\n[[Category:Beekeeping by country|Ireland]]\n[[Category:Agriculture in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Beekeeping]]\n", "name_user": "Jjgetty", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed inaccurate information about NIHBS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beekeeping_in_Ireland"}
{"title_page": "254-260 Canal Street", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP \n| name = 254-260 Canal Street\n| nrhp_type = \n| image = 254-260 Canal Street.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| caption = (2012)\n| location= 254-260 [[Canal Street (Manhattan)|Canal Street]]<br>[[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|43|6|N|74|0|5|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin =Lower Manhattan#Manhattan#New York City\n| area =\n| architect= [[James Bogardus]]\n| architecture= [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Italian Renaissance Revival]]\n| added = June 7, 2006\n| governing_body = Private\n| refnum=06000475<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n| designated_other2_name = NYC Landmark\n| designated_other2_date = March 12, 1985\n| designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n| designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n| designated_other2_number =\n| designated_other2_color = #ffep78\n}}\n\n'''254-260 Canal Street''', also known as the '''Bruce Building''',<ref>Miller, Tom. [http://daytoninmanhattan.blogspot.com/2011/03/1857-james-bogardus-george-bruce.html \"The 1857 James Bogardus \"George Bruce Building\" No. 254 Canal Street\"] ''Daytonian in Manhattan'' (MArch 1, 2011)</ref> on the corner of [[Lafayette Street (Manhattan)|Lafayette Street]] in the [[Chinatown, Manhattan|Chinatown]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], was built in 1856-57 and was designed in the [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Italian Renaissance revival style]]. The [[cast iron|cast-iron]] elements of the facade may have been provided by [[James Bogardus]], a pioneer in the use of [[cast-iron architecture|cast iron in architecture]].<ref name=nycland>{{cite nycland}}, p.36</ref> The building was constructed for [[George Bruce (industrialist)|George Bruce]], a prosperous printer and inventor of new technologies in the printing industry, which was then one of New York's leading industries.<ref name=gayle /> It was converted to offices in 1987 by architect Jack L. Gordon.<ref name=aia4>{{cite AIA4}}, p.74</ref>\n\nThe use of cast-iron columns in the large, five-story tall building allowed for the installation of large windows that improved manufacturing conditions and efficiency. The lot had become available because a lumber mill standing on the site had recently been destroyed by fire, making fire-retardant cast-iron construction attractive. The mildly [[Italianate architecture|Italianate]] style of the building, makes it a particularly handsome example of nineteenth century industrial architecture.<ref name=\"gayle\">Margot Gayle, Cast Iron Architecture in America, Dover Books, 1974, p. 166</ref> It has been called \"Beautiful!\"<ref name=aia4 /> and \"an important early example of cast-iron architecture in New York City\".<ref name=nycland /> If the cast iron did in fact come from Bogardus' iron works, the building would be \"the largest and most important of his extant works.\"<ref name=aia4 />\n\nThe building was designated a [[List of New York City Landmarks|New York City landmark]] in 1985, and was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2006.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{commonscat-inline}}\n* [http://www.nychinatown.org/storefronts/canal/254canal.html photo of 254 Canal Street]  (A Journey through Chinatown).\n\n<!--spacing-->\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Renaissance Revival architecture in New York City]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings completed in 1857]]\n[[Category:James Bogardus buildings]]\n[[Category:1857 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Chinatown, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Cast-iron architecture in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP \n| name = 254-260 Canal Street\n| nrhp_type = \n| image = 254-260 Canal Street.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| caption = (2012)\n| location= 254-260 [[Canal Street (Manhattan)|Canal Street]]<br>[[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|43|6|N|74|0|5|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin =Lower Manhattan#Manhattan#New York City\n| area =\n| architect= [[James Bogardus]]\n| architecture= [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Italian Renaissance Revival]]\n| added = June 7, 2006\n| governing_body = Private\n| refnum=06000475<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n| designated_other2_name = NYC Landmark\n| designated_other2_date = March 12, 1985\n| designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n| designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n| designated_other2_number =\n| designated_other2_color = #ffep78\n}}\n\n'''254-260 Canal Street''', also known as the '''Bruce Building''',<ref>Miller, Tom. [http://daytoninmanhattan.blogspot.com/2011/03/1857-james-bogardus-george-bruce.html \"The 1857 James Bogardus \"George Bruce Building\" No. 254 Canal Street\"] ''Daytonian in Manhattan'' (MArch 1, 2011)</ref> on the corner of [[Lafayette Street (Manhattan)|Lafayette Street]] in the [[Chinatown, Manhattan|Chinatown]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], was built in 1856-57 and was designed in the [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Italian Renaissance revival style]]. The [[cast iron|cast-iron]] elements of the facade may have been provided by [[James Bogardus]], a pioneer in the use of [[cast-iron architecture|cast iron in architecture]].<ref name=nycland>{{cite nycland}}, p.36</ref> The building was constructed for [[George Bruce (industrialist)|George Bruce]], a prosperous printer and inventor of new technologies in the printing industry, which was then one of New York's leading industries.<ref name=gayle /> It was converted to offices in 1987 by architect Jack L. Gordon.<ref name=aia4>{{cite AIA4}}, p.74</ref>\n\nThe use of cast-iron columns in the large, five-story tall building allowed for the installation of large windows that improved manufacturing conditions and efficiency. The lot had become available because a lumber mill standing on the site had recently been destroyed by fire, making fire-retardant cast-iron construction attractive. The mildly [[Italianate architecture|Italinate]] style of the building, makes it a particularly handsome example of nineteenth century industrial architecture.<ref name=\"gayle\">Margot Gayle, Cast Iron Architecture in America, Dover Books, 1974, p. 166</ref> It has been called \"Beautiful!\"<ref name=aia4 /> and \"an important early example of cast-iron architecture in New York City\".<ref name=nycland /> If the cast iron did in fact come from Bogardus' iron works, the building would be \"the largest and most important of his extant works.\"<ref name=aia4 />\n\nThe building was designated a [[List of New York City Landmarks|New York City landmark]] in 1985, and was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2006.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{commonscat-inline}}\n* [http://www.nychinatown.org/storefronts/canal/254canal.html photo of 254 Canal Street]  (A Journey through Chinatown).\n\n<!--spacing-->\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Renaissance Revival architecture in New York City]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings completed in 1857]]\n[[Category:James Bogardus buildings]]\n[[Category:1857 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Chinatown, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Cast-iron architecture in New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Sharper", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/254-260_Canal_Street"}
